<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     09-22 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State employees won't be dialing for
dollars any longer after their attempts to cash in on a $1,000
radio call-in contest brought the Capitol's telephone system to a
crashing halt.
   ``I guess the economy is so bad in Texas that everybody is
trying to get money,'' Carl Stringfellow, state director of
telecommunications, said Tuesday. ``But you shouldn't be using
state phones to be calling on to radio contests.''
   Officials reset the phone system to prevent any calls to the
exchange set aside for radio call-in contests after service was
disrupted several times, Stringfellow said.
   ``We thought we had just had an equipment failure,'' he said.
``But the second time it went down one of our employees suggested
it was at the same time as one of the radio contests.''
   Officials discovered the phone failure occurred within a minute
of the start of a contest by a local radio station offering a
$1,000 prize.
   The Capitol phone system has about 14,000 lines, and its usual
capacity is about 2,000 calls at any time. But the radio contest
bumped the phone traffic up to 8,000 calls, Stringfellow said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forget about toga parties. Miami University
students have come up with something more relevant for the 1980s
and this presidential year _ the Pledge party.
   As in Pledge of Allegiance, of course.
   Police were responding for the second time to noise complaints
about a party at a student's house when Miami junior Bob LeBoeuf
led 150 to 200 revelers in the Pledge.
   ``I thought it'd be funny,'' said LeBoeuf, who led the group
from a trough containing beer kegs and ice. ``What are the police
going to do with 200 people standing around saying the pledge _
arrest them for being patriotic?''
   No, but they did cite host Kimberly A. Mart for violating the
city's noise ordinance after the patriotic partyers pushed police
noise meters over the town's 70-decibel limit. The citation, the
second given for the Sept. 10 party, could cost Mart $128. She was
scheduled to appear in court on Tuesday for the misdemeanor
violation.
   ``The officers were kind of laughing when they took the meter
reading,'' said Karen Stevens, 21, who lives at the house. ``People
weren't saying it in any hostile way. They had smiles on their
faces and some had hands over their hearts. No big deal, we
thought.''
</TEXT>
