<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Italy-Mafia     09-22 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Italy-Mafia,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leading Mafia Investigator Agrees to Stay On</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italy's top Mafia investigator has withdrawn his
resignation, alleviating a crisis in the country's war on organized
crime.
   Giovanni Falcone, an investigating magistrate in the Sicilian
capital of Palermo, had charged when he offered his resignation
July 30 that Mafia investigations were obstructed.
   He also said his methods ``differ radically'' from those of his
superior, Antonino Meli, who was appointed chief investigating
magistrate of the anti-Mafia judicial ``pool'' in February.
   Falcone asked for a transfer and the other members of the pool
then announced their resignations.
   A former colleague of Falcone charged in July that Meli was
weakening the pool by assigning its judges non-Mafia cases and
sending Mafia cases to investigators outside the pool.
   Falcone told judicial officials Wednesday that he was staying on
``in conformance with the ruling'' last week by the Superior
Council of Magistrates, the national judicial watchdog that
appointed Meli.
   The council, praising the pool's work, found that Meli did not
divert cases and called on Falcone not to quit.
   Magistrates in the pool, especially Falcone, have been credited
for some of the country's biggest successes against organized
crime, including the ``maxi'' anti-Mafia trial that ended in
December with 338 convictions.
   U.S. authorities say Falcone provided critical help in
investigations such as the one leading to the New York trial of
suspects in the case of the ``Pizza Connection,'' which discovered
that pizza parlors in the United States were used as fronts for
heroin dealing.
</TEXT>
