<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Harvest     09-22 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Harvest,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Izvestia Says Grain Harvest Down This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union's grain harvest this year will be
smaller than the relatively good harvests of the two previous years
because of drought in the country's breadbasket, Izvestia reported.
   The Soviet government newspaper gave no figures, but said the
harvest was just drawing to a close and it was clear it would fall
short of the 231 million tons harvested in each of the past two
years.
   A significant shortfall in the grain harvest would be a blow to
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's efforts to improve food
supplies to consumers and reform agriculture. It also would require
the Soviet Union to use more of its scare foreign currency to buy
grain instead of machinery and equipment to modernize the economy.
   ``The summer drought has inflicted an appreciable blow on the
principle grainaries of the country _ the Volga region, the Urals,
western Siberia and northern Kazakhstan,'' Izvestia said in the
report Wednesday.
   It said experts of the government's giant agro-industrial
complex had determined ``the grain procurements as a whole around
the country will be somewhat lower than the level of the two
previous years.''
   Izvestia said that although it was reporting bad news, it was a
sign of progress in Soviet society that the news about such a
sensitive area of Soviet life could be reported at all.
   Last year's harvest was considered by Western observers to be
good because the growing season was unusually damp and cool.
   Figures for 1986 and 1987 were well above the average for
1981-1985 of about 203.5 million tons but well below official
targets, which Western observers consider unrealistic.
   The 1986 target was 255 million tons, and Soviet officials are
trying to boost that to 275 million tons over several years' time.
   Western experts say the Soviet Union uses about 240-255 million
tons of grain a year and must import what it cannot produce.
   Gorbachev is trying to reform Soviet agriculture by giving
families and small brigades of farm workers more responsibility and
greater security on the huge state and collective farms.
   The Soviet leader hopes to encourage farmers to work harder by
offering them a chance to earn more money and live better.
</TEXT>
