<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pope-SouthAfrica     09-22 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope-South Africa,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Condemns Apartheid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II condemned South Africa's
policy of apartheid on Wednesday but also expressed a desire to
visit that country.
   The pope returned Monday from a 10-day trip to Zimbabwe,
Botswana, Lesotho, Swaziland and Mozambique. He also made a brief,
unscheduled stop in South Africa.
   ``Apartheid remains in clear conflict with human dignity from
the Christian point of view,'' said John Paul, because ``all human
beings enjoy the same dignity that cannot be weakened by belonging
to a race.''
   ``Surmounting discrimination in this field is an integral part
of the program for liberation and self-determination of the African
people,'' he told a general audience.
   The pontiff, whose plane stopped in South Africa because of
stormy weather and mechanical difficulties at the airport in
Lesotho, also said he believes that in the future he will be able
to visit the faithful in such countries as South Africa, Angola,
Namibia, Sao Tome and Principe.
   Some anti-apartheid leaders in South Africa said the pope did
not speak out strongly enough against that nation during his
southern Africa trip. South Africa's system of apartheid gives the
nation's white minority control of the government and denies the 26
million blacks a vote in national affairs.
</TEXT>
