<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TownArson     09-22 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Town Arson,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Another Fire Appears To End Hopes That Arson Siege Had Ended</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE RECHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of Jefferson tried to go about
business as usual Wednesday despite a fiery reminder that their
small town on the edge of the White Mountains remains under siege
by an arsonist.
   At 10:10 Tuesday night, volunteer firefighters rushed to a
burning unoccupied log cabin _ the 20th suspicious fire in the town
of 900 since early May, but the first since Aug. 23.
   ``It's gone on so long now that people are making the effort to
live each day as it comes, and live their normal lives,'' said
state Sen. Charles Bond, a Jefferson resident.
   ``People had been trying to relax and hope that it is over,''
Bond said. ``There's a feeling of disappointment, I'm sure.''
   The fire extensively damaged the interior of the cabin, which is
about 10 miles from the center of town.
   Most residents have tired of talking about their ordeal and
shrug off questions from reporters. But a phone call to the general
store Wednesday morning revealed that residents were talking among
themselves about the latest fire.
   Except for several cases of smoke inhalation, there have been no
injuries in the house and brush fires. But several families have
been left homeless and townspeople are fearful and angry. Many,
with weapons ready, have taken to keeping watch over their homes
all night.
   The Jefferson Firemen's Association has raised $5,000 for a
reward for information leading to an arrest and conviction.
Firefighters only hope it isn't a neighbor, or a good friend.
   State Fire Marshal William Toland said he has received calls
from current and former firefighting authorities throughout New
England with the names of known arsonists, and the possibility that
one might be living in the Jefferson area.
   ``It takes time to check them all out,'' he said.
   The investigation has progressed, he said, declining to say more.
   Charles King, a national arson expert who spent 23 years with
the New York City Fire Department and has investigated 10,000
fires, expects the fires to continue ``until they catch him. If
he's not scared off by now, it's kind of a `try and catch me'
thing,'' he said.
   ``When you have multiple fires, and have no leads, the person
who is setting the fires has to continue setting them for you to
catch them.''
   New Hampshire authorities have ``just got to get lucky. They
have a monster,'' he said.
   Bond and King point to the surrounding wilderness and sparse
population as impediments to catching the arsonist with match in
hand.
   There is no realistic way to patrol the area, Bond said of the
town's 100 square miles.
   ``There are so many areas where they can do what they do and
just melt into the woods,'' King said. ``How can you patrol the
area around Jefferson?''
   In New York City, the population is more dense and there are
more sources of information, King said. ``In the city, there's
always that little old lady who sits up all night and sees
everything.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
