<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--China-Execution     09-22 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--China-Execution,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canton Robber Put To Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities executed a Canton man convicted of
robbing tourists including a visitor from Japan who was forced to
surrender a camera and $820 in yen, a newspaper reported today.
   The China Daily said the Canton City Intermediate People's Court
condemned to death Li Zhaoheng, who was executed Tuesday, and
handed down life sentences to an accomplice for multiple armed
robberies in the city's Yuexiu Park in August and September of last
year.
   A third man was sentenced to seven years in prison. The ages and
professions of the three men were not given.
   Among the victims, it said, was a Japanese tourist robbed of
110,000 Japanese yen ($820, a camera and his passport, and a
Chinese man who was stabbed in the chest and stomach.
   The daily said the robbers were armed with a dagger.
   China usually metes out harsh punishment for crimes in which
foreigners are victimized, and there have been several cases of the
death sentence being given to Chinese who attack or rob foreigners.
   Execution is normally by a bullet to the back of the head.
</TEXT>
