<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TWA-Consumers     09-22 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-TWA-Consumers,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consumer Group Seeks Federal Investigation of TWA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A consumer group is asking the Transportation
Department to investigate the fitness of Trans World Airlines
because of a series of impending financial transactions critics say
threaten the carrier's financial health.
   The petition by the Consumer Federation of America maintains
that plans to convert TWA into a private company would saddle the
airline with $2.3 billion in debt and declining assets because more
than $700 million in TWA's cash could be used in the transaction.
   TWA Chairman Carl Icahn earlier this month won investor support
for the stock deal which would allow Icahn to recover his $440
million investment and control 90 percent of TWA's stock through a
new holding company. Icahn now owns about 77 percent of the airline.
   The petition filed by the consumer group claims TWA could be put
``on the brink of bankruptcy'' by the transaction, which also has
been denounced by TWA's unions.
   A suit filed by the Air Line Pilots Association in the New York
Supreme Court asks that the court prevent Icahn ``from looting
TWA'' through the stock transaction plan. It maintains that Icahn
will ``strip TWA of $665 million'' and threaten the airline's
economic future.
   The Consumer Federation told the department that air travelers
holding nearly $500 million in advance and unused tickets as well
as credits on TWA frequent flyer programs stand to loose
substantial amounts should TWA go bankrupt or be forced to cut
service or routes.
   The federation alleged that Icahn, who purchased TWA in 1985
when it was near collapse, has run up large debts at the company
while holding on to large amounts of cash, cash equivalents and
marketable securities. But the petition alleges most of those cash
assets will be wiped out in the stock transaction.
   ``The precarious financial structure after this (transaction)
raises serious questions about whether the airline will be able to
meet its financial and quality of service obligations to the
public,'' said Mark Cooper, director of research for the Consumer
Federation.
   ``After running up huge amounts of debt, the Icahn-led group now
proposes to take all its money and then some out of TWA, leave the
company with absolutely no equity and leave the airline on the
brink of bankruptcy,'' he continued.
   Furthermore, the federation maintained that consumers are
``virtual captives of TWA'' because of its domination in several
cities, such as St. Louis, where more than 80 percent of all
flights are operated by TWA.
   ``The failure of the airline or a significant reduction in
service would have a devastating impact on these consumers who have
few alternatives for air travel,'' said Cooper
   TWA officials in St. Louis and New York did not immediately
return calls seeking comment Wednesday.
   Earlier this week the General Accounting Office, the
investigative arm of Congress, found that TWA had achieved dominant
control of airport traffic in and out of St. Louis since it
acquired Ozark Air Lines two years ago. Ozark had been TWA's
biggest competitor at St. Louis.
   Bill Mosely, a Transportation Department spokesman, said the
petition was still being reviewed. ``We are expecting some decision
fairly soon,'' he said.
   Earlier this year the department launched an in-depth
examination of Texas Air Corp., the holding company of Eastern
Airlines and Continental Airlines, after questions were raised
about the company's financial dealings. No irregularities were
found at Texas Air.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
