<DOCNO> AP880922-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 0158EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hungary-Diplomacy     09-22 0688</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hungary-Diplomacy,0708</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hungary Opens Up To Capitalist World</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary is performing a delicate
balancing act between East and West as it opens its doors to the
business and technology of the capitalist world.
   Communist Party chief Karoly Grosz has extended a diplomatic
hand to many nations the rest of the Eastern Europe keeps at a
distance.
   Hungary is the first East bloc nation that is to normalize
diplomatic ties with South Korea. The announcement was made in
Seoul on Sept. 13, but no date has been set.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Istvan Komoroczki said the move was
``in harmony with a Hungarian drive to openness to the world,
irrespective of social systems.
   In the same week, Budapest also became the first Eastern bloc
nation to agree to resume diplomatic ties with Israel, severed
after the 1967 Middle East war. After a private visit to Budapest
Sept. 14-15, Israeli Premier Yitzhak Shamir, the first Israeli head
of goverment to visit Hungary, said Israel would renew full
diplomatic ties with Hungary ``in the near future.'' No date was
set.
   Grosz became party boss in May and immediately embarked on a
series of trips to the West, including visits to the United States,
Canada and Britain. The communist leader has emphasized Hungary's
need for Western technology and investments that would reverse its
economic slump and allow it to begin chipping at an $18 billion
foreign debt.
   ``I hardly think I have to reiterate the importance to the life
and development of this country of mutually advantageous external
economic relations,'' Grosz told the English-language official
Daily News last week.
   After being named Hungary's premier in June 1987, Grosz also
visited West Germany in October of that year and Greece in November.
   But the Communist Party leader has been careful not to neglect
or antagonize his Soviet bloc allies as he opens his country to
capitalitstic influences, unlike Romanian leader Nicolae Ceausescu,
whose maverick policies won him Western support in the 1970s but
irritated Moscow.
   In a balancing move, Grosz made a quick visit to Moscow before
his 10-day U.S. tour in July, apparently to win Soviet leader
Mikhail Gorbachev's support for his overtures toward the West.
   While visiting East Germany in September, Grosz emphasized the
need to boost economic relations between the two countries,
although East Berlin has balked at Gorbachev's proposed reforms.
   Budapest also has refrained from criticizing Czechoslovakia,
although Hungarian activists oppose a joint hydroelectric project
on the Danube River that links them.
   When relations between Romania and Hungary hit an all-time low
this summer in the wake of Bucharest's alleged discrimination
against its 1.7 million minority Hungarians, Grosz met with
Ceausescu in Romania on Aug. 28.
   The Hungarian leader drew criticism at home for his failure to
persuade the Romanian government to scrap its plan to raze
thousands of villages inhabited by the Hungarian minority.
   A Western analyst in Budapest, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Hungary, with its good human rights record and
liberal policies, has presented itself to the West as
``user-friendly.''
   At the same time, Budapest seems to have Moscow's approval in
pursuing whatever foreign policy it chooses _ as long as they don't
damage its ties to the Warsaw Pact alliance.
   This independence began long before Grosz and Gorbachev, but it
received a boost when the two leaders came to power.
   In 1985, Hungary was the East bloc host of a 35-nation cultural
forum under the Helsinki human rights accords.
   In March 1987, Hungary became the first East bloc country to
join the West in backing a minority rights resolution at the Vienna
Conference on Security and Cooperation in Europe.
   More recently, Budapest was the site Aug. 30-31 of a closed-door
meeting of arms experts from NATO and the Warsaw Pact, and it has
offered to host a Soviet-U.S. summit.
   Hungary's joint bid with Austria to host the 1995 World's Fair
in Vienna and Budapest has strengthened the impression that Hungary
is seeking a role similar to that of neutral Austria, a center of
East-West contacts.
</TEXT>
