<DOCNO> AP880922-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 0157EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DeltaCrash     09-22 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Delta Crash,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delta Crash Investigations Study Tapes for Sound of Flap Settings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators of last month's Delta Air Lines
crash in Texas are trying to determine whether several ``click''
sounds on the jet's cockpit voice recorder are indications the
flight crew set the flaps before takeoff.
   The Boeing 727 crashed seconds after taking off from the
Dallas-Fort Worth airport Aug. 31, killing 14 of the 108 people
aboard. The investigation has focused on whether a false flap
setting may have kept the plane from gaining altitude.
   At least two clicks can be heard on the recording, according to
sources close to the investigation. But additional sounds also are
being studied to determine the exact number of clicks and whether
they relate directly to the flaps' position.
   The flaps, which provide an aircraft with lift during takeoff,
were supposed to have been set at 15 degrees for proper takeoff of
Flight 1141.
   The Dallas Morning News on Wednesday quoted National
Transportation Safety Board officials it did not name as saying
they were studying the possibility that the flaps were extended,
but not far enough.
   ``What you hear (on the tape of the cockpit conversation) are
two `clicks' in quick succession. That means that the flaps were at
least at the 5-degree setting,'' the newspaper quoted one source as
saying.
   The Boeing 727 has flap settings of 2, 5 and 15 degrees. The
flap control mechanism in the cockpit has notches that produce
clicking sounds as the lever is moved.
   Meanwhile, investigators are expected to conduct tests in flight
simulators to determine what minimum flap setting would have been
required for the plane to gain proper lift.
   Some aviation experts who have followed the accident
investigation say the Boeing 727, which was not fully loaded,
should have been able to take off even with a lower than optimum
flap setting.
   Drucella Anderson, a spokeswoman for the NTSB, said Wednesday
the safety board would have no comment on what investigators are
examining on the cockpit voice recorder tapes.
   Investigators have uncovered conflicting evidence as to the
jet's flap setting at the time of takeoff.
   The voice recorder shows the co-pilot acknowledged having set
the flaps to 15 degrees during the routine preflight checklist.
   ``Fifteen, fifteen, green,'' the co-pilot was heard to say on
the cockpit recorder tape, according to sources involved in the
investigation.
   One source suggested that the co-pilot, if he set the flaps,
probably did so earlier and was reading off the flap setting at the
time his response was recorded.
   The reference to ``green'' refers to a light showing the
position of separate control surfaces on the forward edge of the
wings called slats. A green light shows them to be in the extended
position.
   Slats also are supposed to be extended during takeoff, but
investigators have said they found the slats on the wrecked
aircraft in an unlocked but retracted position.
   Investigators have said the jack screws on the wings also
indicated the flaps were in a retracted position and the flap-slat
control lever in the cockpit was found in an up position,
indicating the flaps were retracted. The co-pilot who was
responsible for setting the flaps has told investigators he cannot
remember anything after the aircraft was pushed back from the gates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880922-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 0238EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-NevadaSenate Bjt   09-22 0697</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nevada Senate, Bjt,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nevada Senate Campaign Turns Bitter, Political Trickery Charged</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Republican Sen. Chic Hecht struggles
to hold his seat against a strong challenge from Democratic Gov.
Dick Bryan, their battle has turned bitter with party and campaign
officials making accusations on usually-untouchable subjects such
as Bryan's sex life and Hecht's intelligence.
   On the surface, Bryan and Hecht have been debating one another
on familiar themes _ a possible nuclear dump in Nevada, defense
spending, conservative vs. liberal philosophies and balanced
budgets.
   Hecht, 59, has sought to link Bryan to organized labor in this
state of legalized gambling as well as tie the Democrat to the
liberal views of presidential nominee Michael Dukakis. He also has
accused Bryan of deserting voters who elected him to a second
four-year term as governor in 1986.
   In turn, Bryan, 51, has attacked Hecht for flip-flops on the
nuclear waste dump, for voting against Social Security increases,
and for being generally ineffective. He also points to poll after
poll showing him with a comfortable lead over the one-term
incumbent.
   And both have been publicly critical of another level of the
campaign in which top party officials and key campaign staffers
have accused one another of ``dirty tricks.''
   Bryan blasted Clark County Republican Chairman Charles Ivy for
``a despicable campaign tactic'' in mentioning on a radio talk show
that there have been rumors about Bryan's ``little extramarital
hobbies'' since he was first elected to the state Assembly in 1968.
   ``This kind of crap kind of discourages people from putting
their names on the line,'' said Bryan, adding that there is no
truth to the rumors of infidelity and he would consider legal
action after the election.
   Hecht insisted his campaign staff had nothing to do with the
comment, and any staffer would be fired immediately if involved.
   Hecht also has complained about recent news accounts citing his
verbal miscues, including a reference to a nuclear repository that
unintentionally came out as ``nuclear suppository.'' He also noted
the opposition's references to Hecht's recent ranking by Senate
administrative assistants as the least effective member of the
Senate.
   Hecht, a Las Vegas businessman, upset Sen. Howard Cannon in 1982
after the incumbent was bloodied during a tough primary fight.
Cannon had to fight mob shadows after he was named in the
indictment of then Teamsters president Roy Lee Williams and mob
figure Allen Dorfman. He testified at length in their trial just a
month before the election.
   Bryan campaign chief Sam Singer describes the Hecht campaign as
``Watergate-style politics the likes of which this state has never
seen,'' and blames Hecht campaign chief Ken Rietz for the ``dirty
tricks.''
   Rietz responds that Singer's attack ``is a little bit like the
pot calling the kettle black,'' adding that the Bryan camp
criticized him for political low blows ``and now they're
distributing information on me.''
   Singer circulated a stack of news clips linking Rietz to
political espionage during the Watergate era and quoting
then-Republican National Chairman George Bush, now the GOP
presidential nominee, as saying in 1973 he wanted none of the
people involved in the activity ever working on GOP campaigns again.
   Rietz said Bush wasn't referring to him but rather was talking
about those convicted in the Watergate scandal. ``That didn't
include me. I was not charged with anything during Watergate,'' he
said. ``I've been working in Republican campaigns ever since then.''
   Singer said the Hecht campaign has shown ``a series of dirty
tricks'' that began with a Rietz employee or ex-employee trying to
dig up information on Democratic Lt. Gov. Bob Miller, who would
take over Bryan's job as governor should Bryan defeat Hecht.
   Singer said that was followed by claims by Ivy that Bryan had
engaged in extramarital affairs, misstatements and misleading
advertisements, and what appeared to be a planted story about Lt.
Gov. Miller's ties to a casino executive convicted of skimming.
   ``There are dirty fingerprints everywhere,'' said Singer.
``Nevada's gaming industry has a black book (of unsavory types
excluded from clubs) and if Nevada politics had a black book
Senator Hecht's campaign would be in it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
