<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 0336EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Corruption     09-22 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Corruption,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Says Former Politburo Member Cheated to Skip Military
Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Politburo member Geidar Aliev ducked
military service in World War II and later covered up his scheme
with phony records saying he was a veteran, a newspaper reported.
   A lengthy article in Wednesday's editions of the weekly
Literaturnaya Gazeta accused Aliev, the former Communist Party boss
of Azerbaijan and a close associate of the late Soviet leader
Leonid I. Brezhnev, of rampant corruption.
   Aliev, Brezhnev's last appointment to the ruling Politburo
before he died in 1982, worked for many years in the Azerbaijan KGB
secret police.
   Aliev, 65, was dropped from the Politburo on Oct. 21, 1987,
ostensibly for health reasons. But there were suggestions that he
was tainted with corruption in his association with Brezhnev, now
widely criticized for permitting corruption and stagnation.
   A KGB commission established years ago that when Nazi Germany
attacked the Soviet Union in 1941, the 18-year-old Aliev ``quit his
studies in the industrial institute ... and to avoid being called
into the army went to his motherland, his native town,
Nakhichevan,'' said the article, which was written by lawyer Arkady
Vaksberg. ``There he obtained a document stating that he allegedly
suffered from a severe form of tuberculosis and was freed from
service.''
   He then began work in the archives of the NKVD, the precursor of
the KGB, Vaksberg said.
   After the war, Aliev obtained documents saying he was a war
veteran, the article said.
   Despite the commission's discovery, Aliev's older brother,
Gasan, intervened. Aliev was reprimanded but remained in the
Communist Party and was able to build his career, the article said.
   Vaksberg said a former KGB officer and state prosecutor, Gambai
Mamedov, repeatedly tried to draw the attention of Azerbaijani
officials to widespread corruption and falsification of production
statistics under Aliev. But the lawyer said Mamedov was hounded out
of his job and the republic by officials, who lavished praise on
Aliev in party and government meetings.
   He said that since Aliev's ouster, Mamedov has been able to
return to Baku, the Azerbaijan capital, from Leningrad where he
lived in the apartment of his wife's relatives.
</TEXT>
