<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Shevardnadze 1stLd-Writethru a0439 09-22 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Shevardnadze, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0439,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Extra Precautions Taken As Soviet Foreign Minister's Arrives</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: ADDS 5 grafs with additional detail on Shevardnadze, trip
plans</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nervous airport security dog prompted extra
precautions as Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze arrived
Wednesday night for what could be the last full-dress U.S.-Soviet
talks in Washington during the Reagan administration.
   Shevardnadze landed without incident, however, and was taken to
the Soviet Embassy where he will stay during two days of meetings
with Secretary of State George Shultz and other senior U.S.
officials, ending in a call on President Reagan at the White House
on Friday.
   The Soviet Aeroflot jetliner carrying Shevardnadze from New York
was parked more distant than usual from terminal buildings and news
media facilities at Andrews Air Force Base, outside Washington,
because a dog used to sniff and detect explosives became nervous,
said a State Department official who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   But it proved to be just a precaution and no explosives were
found, the official said.
   A motorcade carried Deputy Secretary of State John C. Whitehead,
Assistant Secretary Rozanne Ridgway and other welcoming officials
from the State Department and Soviet Embassy to planeside while
camera crews assigned to photograph the arrival were left at their
usual position at least 250 feet away.
   Shevardnadze, making no arrival statement, left the airport
immediately.
   By State Department count, his negotiations with Shultz on arms
control, human rights, U.S.-Soviet and regional issues will be
their 28th meeting.
   They are expected to meet again at U.N. headquarters in New York
next week and possibly in Europe if there is a breakthrough on
human rights and other issues before the current review session at
Vienna, Austria, of the 1975 Helsinki accords on East-West security
and cooperation.
   But Ms. Ridgway told reporters this week there is no possibility
that the two sides will be able to resolve differences before the
end of the year on their mutual goal of achieving 50 percent cuts
in strategic ballistic missile warheads to enable Reagan to sign
another arms treaty before the end of his presidency.
   Shevardnadze's schedule also includes a separate meeting with
Vice President George Bush, the Republican candidate to succeed
Reagan, arranged at Bush's request, a U.S. official said. Bush's
Democratic rival, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis has not asked
for a meeting with the Soviet minister, the official added.
</TEXT>
