<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 0154EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Gilbert-Hawaii     09-22 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gilbert-Hawaii,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hawaii Tourist Industry Gets Unexpected Boost from Hurricane
Gilbert</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Gilbert, which wreaked havoc on
resorts in Mexico and the Caribbean, has given an unexpected boost
to Hawaii's tourist industry during a normally slow month, tourism
officials say.
   Tourists, hearing of the devastation left in Gilbert's wake, are
rearranging travel plans, officials said Wednesday. At least one
company that books trips to Hawaii has employees working overtime
to handle the demand.
   Pleasant Hawaiian Holidays, the leading seller of tour packages
to Hawaii, is receiving 40 percent more phone calls than normal for
this time of year, according to spokesman Ken Phillips. The company
is headquartered in Westlake Village, Calif.
   ``I know that they have required overtime for reservationists,
bringing people back from vacations early, adding as much as
possible to the staff,'' to handle the increased Hawaii business,
Phillips said.
   September is considered a slow period for Hawaii travel,
Phillips said.
   Tom Vericella, vice president for Hawaii travel at American
Express Travel Related Services, agreed that Gilbert is boosting
tourism figures in Hawaii.
   ``Certainly we have seen an increase at our reservations center
in Atlanta,'' he said.
   Gilbert crippled resorts in Jamaica and Mexico's Yucatan
Peninsula, both considered major competitors for Hawaii's tourist
industry. The hurricane is believed to have killed more than 200
people as it swept through the Gulf of Mexico and into the mainland
last week.
</TEXT>
