<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bentsen     09-22 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bentsen,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Seeks Votes In ``The Big Enchilada'' _ California</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate
Lloyd Bentsen is turning his attention from rural health care to
high-technology and trade as he searches for votes on the diverse
West Coast.
   Bentsen arrived in California on Wednesday, carrying from Texas
the Democrats' new health care proposals. He mixed those with
attacks on the Republicans _ especially Dan Quayle _ as he
campaigned in a Sacramento hospital and at a Fresno rally.
   California's 47 electoral votes are the most of any state. Polls
show the tickets in a virtual tie here, and the Democrats hope to
win the state for the first time since 1964.
   The Texas senator planned today to address employees of the
Intel semiconductor company and then travel to Washington state to
visit Scott Paper Co. Washington has 10 electoral votes.
   On Wednesday, Bentsen and his wife, B.A., scrubbed and put on
hospital garb and visited an intensive care ward for newborn babies
at Sutter Memorial Hospital in Sacramento, underscoring Michael
Dukakis' pledge for a program getting pre-natal care to poor women.
   Bentsen said Republicans George Bush and Dan Quayle had
supported the Reagan administration's cuts in medical care
programs, including maternal and child health.
   ``It's easy to vote against something and call yourself a
conservative, but America pays a very heavy price for neglecting
health care for children,'' he said.
   ``A quarter of our children have not received their measles
vaccines,'' he said. ``Dan Quayle voted against it.''
   In Fresno, an agricultural center in the San Joaquin Valley,
Bentsen told a downtown rally ``the agriculture policy of this
administration has been a disaster for the American farmer.''
   He talked about how the nation's drug problems have worsened in
the past eight years. He continued to blast the Republicans for the
record budget deficits. And, he continued to hammer at Bush's
selection of Quayle as his running mate.
   ``We believe that America deserves a vice president to take on
the toughest and most important job in the world if that was
necessary. Do you think the junior senator from Indiana is up to
that job?''
   ``No,'' yelled the crowd.
   The colorful rally included a huge American flag behind Bentsen,
a staging the Democrats have taken up lately to counter George
Bush's flag-waving campaign.
   There were protesters from both the right and the left greeting
Bentsen. Some opposed his position in favor of keeping abortion
legal, others opposed his support of aid to the Contra rebels in
Nicaragua. A couple of people were dressed up in prison uniforms,
delivering the GOP attack on Massachusetts' prison furlough program
under Dukakis.
   Before leaving Texas, Bentsen himself announced the ticket's
rural health care initiative, including a fund to subsidize rural
hospitals in financial trouble.
   The Democratic ticket is trailing the Republicans in Texas,
despite Bentsen's presence, according to recent polls.
   At the rally in Fresno, Bentsen told the 300 supporters how
important their state was to the ticket.
   ``You're the big banana. The big enchilada. Forty-seven
electoral votes,'' he said.
</TEXT>
