<1ST_LINE>r i PM-GreatTrainRobber     09-22 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Great Train Robber,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Son Of Great Train Robber Seeks Royal Pardon For Father</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son of fugitive Ronald Biggs has arrived in
Britain to seek a royal pardon for his father, a member of the gang
that pulled off the notorious Great Train Robbery of 1963.
   Mike Biggs, 14, said upon arriving Wednesday at Heathrow Airport
that he plans to present Queen Elizabeth II with a letter urging
her to suspend the 30-year sentence imposed on his father for his
part in the robbery.
   ``I want to see my father a free man,'' the young Biggs told
reporters after his flight from Brazil, where his father has lived
in exile since 1970.
   ``It is his right. He has lived for the past 25 years as an
honest man. I have lived with him for the past 14 years and know he
is not a thief anymore,'' Biggs said.
   A spokesman for Buckingham Palace, speaking on condition on
anonymity, said it would be ``highly unlikely'' for the queen to
meet the youth. The British monarch is on vacation in Scotland.
   The senior Biggs, 59, took part in the $7-million robbery from
the Glasgow-to-London mail train Aug. 8, 1963. At the time, it was
Britain's largest heist.
   Less than $980,000 was recovered, but most of the 15 gang
members, including Biggs, were caught and sentenced to prison.
   Biggs escaped from London's Wandsworth Jail in July 1965 and
fled to France, where he had plastic surgery on his face, then to
Australia and finally in 1970 to Brazil, which has no extradition
treaty with Britain.
   In 1985, Biggs said his reported $325,000 share of the robbery
was long gone. He said in an interview this year that he supports
himself by selling souvenirs.
</TEXT>
