<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Quayle     09-22 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle, Admonished By Goldwater, Prepares Foreign Policy Address</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Speech to L.A. World Affairs Council set for about 3:05 p.m.
EDT; top unlikely</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle is shrugging off a rebuke
from Barry Goldwater about the tenor of the flag-draped Bush
campaign, saying, ``We're talking about the issues.''
   The Republican vice presidential nominee was delivering a
foreign policy address today at the Los Angeles World Affairs
Council before heading home to Washington.
   Goldwater, who retired this year after a long Senate career as
``Mr. Conservative,'' stole the show from the Indiana senator
Wednesday in Phoenix when he delivered his surprise dart at a
Rotary Club luncheon.
   After introducing Quayle, Goldwater reclaimed the microphone.
   ``I forgot something that I had to say, and I hope you take this
kindly. But I want you to go back and tell George Bush to start
talking about the issues, O.K.?'' the 1964 Republican presidential
candidate said.
   Goldwater did not elaborate, but the dig seemed aimed at Bush's
capture-the-flag campaigning, from his constant criticism of
Michael Dukakis for vetoing a 1977 bill to penalize teachers who
refuse to lead the Pledge of Allegiance to his stop Tuesday at a
New Jersey flag factory.
   Goldwater brushed aside reporters' questions afterwards, saying,
``I'm not talking. I want to get the hell outof here.''
   Quayle, before the 400 Rotarians, laughed and said only, ``I
wish Barry would just say what's on his mind.''
   Later, he told reporters in Bakersfield, Calif., ``Barry
Goldwater is my dear friend. We're talking about the issues.''
   Quayle almost crossed paths with his Democratic counterpart,
Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas, at the airport in Fresno, Calif.,
where their campaign planes were parked 400 yards apart for a
while. They did not meet.
   The final day of summer was an unusual one for the 41-year-old
Quayle, who trekked from Las Vegas to Phoenix to California's San
Joaquin Valley before reuniting with his wife Marilyn, for a
fund-raiser at a posh Los Angeles hotel. A dozen feminists were
waiting there with signs protesting Bush and Quayle's opposition to
abortion.
   He was hounded in two stops in the Phoenix area by Vietnam
veterans, three of them clad in colorful chicken costumes.
   He made a detour to pick up Goldwater at his home, only to get
admonished.
   Arizona's ousted Republican Gov. Evan Mecham showed up to
deliver an unsolicited endorsement of Quayle.
   At California State University-Fresno, he was greeted by
sky-divers, balloons and a phalanx of students chanting
``Bush-Noriega '88!''
   But inside a student union, he got an enthusiastic reception
from 600 students as he denounced Dukakis for opposing the death
penalty and signing a proclamation in February 1985 supporting a
union boycott of table grapes.
   In both Fresno and at a rally before 1,000 people outside the
courthouse in Bakersfield, Quayle lit into Dukakis as ``a
card-carrying member of the ACLU'' and charged he would appoint
judges like Rose Bird, the liberal California Supreme Court Justice
who was recalled in part for opposing the death penalty.
   At Frye Elementary School in Chandler, Ariz., he offered
children a brief civics lesson on free speech after demonstrators
yelled ``Chicken hawk'' at him.
   ``Don't pay any attention to them. You know, in this country of
ours, we have a thing called freedom of speech. ... '' he said.
``They have the freedom of speech, but you know what, kids? So do
we.''
</TEXT>
