<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Nicaragua     09-22 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinista Opponent Condemns Wright's Revelations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An opponent activist says U.S. House
Speaker Jim Wright may have jeopardized the security of domestic
critics of the ruling Sandinistas by saying the CIA tried to
destabilize Nicaragua.
   Enrique Bolanos Gayer, a former president of the anti-Sandinista
Private Enterprise Council, on Wednesday called Wright's statements
``irresponsible, full of politicking and moral and ethical faults.''
   He said Wright made the comments out of ``ambition and a
partisan fight to reach the White House. ... In his internal
politicking, lacking ethics and morals, (Wright) is capable of
sacrificing the security of people.''
   Bolanos made his remarks from Miami to Radio Liberacion, the
Nicaraguan rebels' clandestine radio station.
   Wright, D-Texas, said Tuesday that Congress had received ``clear
testimony'' that the Reagan administration sought to secretly
undermine the Nicaraguan peace process, thus damaging long-term
prospects for an accord between the leftist Sandinistas and
U.S.-supported Contra rebels.
   President Reagan on Wednesday accused Wright of talking
indiscreetly about U.S. intelligence secrets, but stopped short of
denying the claim.
   The Sandinista government had no immediate response, but the
official newspaper Barricada ran a banner headline Wednesday
saying, ``CIA Confesses To Plan Melton.''
   In July, the Sandinistas expelled U.S. Ambassador Richard
Melton, saying he was carrying out an adminstration plan to
undermine Nicaragua's government by supporting opposition groups.
   The Sandinistas expelled him and seven other U.S. diplomats the
day after a July 10 rally they said was part of that plan. Police
arrested more than 40 opposition leaders at the big anti-government
march in the southern city of Nandaime after clashing with
protesters.
   The Contras said earlier this week that further talks to forge a
lasting peace to replace a March 23 preliminary cease-fire pact
cannot be held until the 40 are freed.
   The day after the Nandaime rally, the government suspended for
15 days the only opposition newspaper, La Prensa, and closed the
Roman Catholic radio station for 38 days.
   President Daniel Ortega said this week that the National
Endowment for Democracy, a U.S. government organization, provides
more than $600,000 for several opposition groups, including La
Prensa.
   According to a June 24 letter obtained by The Associated Press
from Rep. Robert Michel, R-Ill., to Gilberto Cuadra, president of
the Private Enterprise Council, the House was discussing an
additional $1 million to opposition groups, while Senate
legislation would provide $2 million.
   On Tuesday, the government said it had refused to grant
permission for an opposition march set for Sunday.
   An editorial Wednesday in Barricada advised the opposition
groups not to ``continue being ridiculous by soliciting permission
to take to the streets to provoke the authorities. We already know
the story.''
</TEXT>
