<HEAD>Dollar Inches Up Against Yen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched up against the Japanese yen at
the close of trading Thursday, while share prices lost ground on
the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar opened at 134.35 yen and moved in a narrow range of
134.27-124.55 yen in light trading. It closed at 134.47 yen, up
0.29 yen from the previous day's close of 134.16 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, the main index
on the stock exchange, declined 284.35 points, or 1.03 percent,
from Wednesday's close to finish the day's trade at 27,428.31.
   Exchange dealers said trading was slow as players were sidelined
ahead of a long holiday weekend in Japan. Markets will be closed
Friday for a national holiday, Autumn Equinox Day.
   Also an upcoming meeting of the group of seven, consisting of
finance ministers and central bank heads from seven industrial
nations, was scheduled over the weekend, prompting many market
participants to sit out and watch the situation Thursday, dealers
said.
   ``The basic trend is to buy the dollar, but it's not an active
one,'' said an exchange dealer with Sumitomo Bank in Tokyo. ``The
slight gain in the dollar today was a result of its rise in New
York (overnight),'' he said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Securities dealers said share prices opened on bullishly, but
most institutional investors concentrated their purchases to
large-capital steel shares, leading to declines in other issues.
   ``Steel shares absorbed the market's energy,'' said a trader at
a Japanese securities firm, who asked not to be identified.
   One trader said buying interest was down due to continued
unconcertainty over the emperor's condition. Palace physicians say
the 87-year-old monarch is in stable but serious condition four
days after falling ill due to intestinal hemorrhaging.
</TEXT>
