<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     09-22 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up, Stocks Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained marginally on the Tokyo foreign
exchange market today while share prices declined sharply on the
Stock Exchange.
   After opening at 134.35 yen, the dollar moved in a narrow range
of 134.27-134.55 yen in light trading. It closed at 134.47 yen, up
0.29 yen from the previous day's close.
   Exchange dealers said the slight gain reflected strong showing
of the currency in New York and London overnight, but the lack of
fresh incentives prevented the dollar from strengthening further.
   ``The dollar is in a difficult position to move too far because
of the upcoming Group of Seven meeting,'' said an exchange dealer
in Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity. ``But market
participants are expecting no major changes in the meeting,
either.''
   The meeting of the Group of Seven, in which foreign ministers
and central bank chiefs from the seven major industrialized nations
discuss international economic and fiscal policies, is scheduled on
Saturday in West Berlin.
   Foreign Minister Kiichi Miyazawa said he expects the current
international cooperation in fiscal policies will be maintained
after that meeting.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, the main index
on the stock exchange, declined 284.35 points, or 1.03 percent,
from Wednesday's close to finish the day's trading at 27,428.31.
   Securities dealers attributed the drop of share prices to profit
taking.
   ``After the news of the Emperor's ailing health shook Japan
Monday night, the general direction of the market has been
negative,'' said a dealer at a major securities firm. ``So everyone
is trying to take advantage of yesterday's gain.''
   Despite the downward trend, the Nikkei index gained 164.08
points Wedneday.
   Most securities dealers expect the market will remain
directionless and unpredictable until Emperor Hirohito's condition
becomes clearer.
   ``The market as a whole appears to be regaining energy after
more than a month long slump,'' said another dealer at a major
securities firm, requesting anonymity. ``The increased volume and
the popularity of large-capital shares are one of the signs of
that.''
   The volume traded on the first section of the exchange, where
most major shares are listed, was 850 million shares.
   Both the Tokyo Stock Exchange and Tokyo foreign exchange markets
will be closed Friday because of a national holiday. The stock
exchange will have a half day session Saturday while foreign
exchange dealing will remain closed until Monday.
</TEXT>
