<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SouthAfrica-Bombs     09-22 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Bombs,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Bombs Explode In Four Cities, 38 Injured</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty-eight people were hurt
across South Africa in five bombings over nine hours, according to
police, who said the first blast injured 18 whites, while the
next-to-last hurt 19 blacks.
   A 1 a.m. blast today inside the Why Not disco in the
Johannesburg suburb of Hillbrow injured 19 blacks, three seriously,
and caused extensive damage, police said. The disco is frequented
almost exclusively by blacks.
   During the Wednesday evening rush hour, a bomb exploded at the
main white bus terminal in downtown Johannesburg, injuring 19
people, all but one of them white, police said.
   The explosion occurred just after 5 p.m. in one of the new
concrete trash bins installed throughout the city last year to
muffle the effects of bombs. It shattered windows of four buses,
damaged a fast-food cafe, and broke the windows of buildings and
cars in the area.
   Meanwhile, police said early today that bombs exploded overnight
in Pretoria and in the southern towns of King William's Town and
Fort Beaufort. There were no injuries in the three attacks, police
said.
   In Pretoria, a bomb placed at the front door extensively damaged
the home of Shakes el Goolam, an Asian candidate in the municipal
elections next month, police said. The explosion occurred at 1:25
a.m.
   In Fort Beaufort, an explosive device damaged the back of a
public library and in King William's Town, a suspected mini-limpet
mine exploded in the front of the magistrate's court building.
   No one claimed responsibility for any of the attacks.
   Minister of Law and Order Adriaan Vlok described the blast at
the bus terminal as a ``repulsive act'' carried out by ''cowards.''
   There have been more than 110 bombings in South Africa since the
government declared a nationwide state of emergency in June 1986.
Police have blamed virtually all the attacks on the outlawed
African National Congress, the main black group attempting to
overthrow the white minority government.
   However, in recent weeks bombs have exploded at the headquarters
of anti-apartheid groups and at public facilities frequented mostly
by blacks.
   Under apartheid, South Africa's 26 million blacks have no say in
national affairs.
</TEXT>
