<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Aliens-Amnesty     09-22 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Aliens-Amnesty,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Orders Work Permits, Bars Deportation of Aliens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has barred the
deportation of up to 100,000 aliens until it decides whether the
Immigration and Naturalization Service was too restrictive in
denying them amnesty.
   In a decision made public Wednesday, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals also authorized temporary work permits for the aliens.
   The court ordered the temporary measures until it rules on
whether the INS exceeded its authority by denying amnesty to aliens
who had left the United States briefly. Depending on its ruling,
the court could reopen the now-expired deadline for aliens to apply
for amnesty under the new immigration law.
   The court said it would hear arguments in the case in November
under an accelerated schedule. The government is appealing a
federal judge's ruling in April that the INS interpreted the
grounds for amnesty too narrowly.
   ``This is a great day for our system of justice,'' said Ralph
Abascal, a California Rural Legal Assistance lawyer in the case. He
said four other federal judges around the nation have restricted
INS enforcement of related provisions of the amnesty law, but that
this was the first order from an appellate court.
   The number of aliens potentially affected by the case is
estimated to be from 50,000 to 100,000 nationwide, he said.
   Justice Department lawyer Scott McIntosh, who represented the
INS, declined comment.
   The new immigration law allowed aliens who have been in the U.S.
continuously since Jan. 1, 1982, to apply for amnesty by May, the
first step toward legal residence.
   A trip outside the country that is ``brief, casual and
innocent'' does not disqualify an alien from amnesty. Under an INS
interpretation, however, any departure after May 1, 1987, when
amnesty applications began, that lacked advance approval from the
INS could not be ``innocent'' and made the alien ineligible for
amnesty.
   Abascal said in a statement that the INS had used its reading of
the law to bar amnesty to several aliens who had made brief trips
to Mexico to see a dying relative, and to one who fell asleep in a
car shortly before his friends went to Tijuana for a two-hour
frolic.
   Chief U.S. District Judge Lawrence Karlton of Sacramento ruled
in April that the INS interpretation was not authorized by the law.
After finding that numerous aliens had been denied amnesty
improperly or had been discouraged from applying, he issued a
nationwide order in June reopening the application period through
Nov. 30, which the government appealed.
   The appeals court decision requires that the government question
any aliens arrested under the immigration law to see if they would
be eligible for amnesty if not for foreign travel of the kind
covered by the suit. If so, the aliens must be released without
bond and given work permits while the court case is pending.
   The same rights must be provided to aliens who approach the INS
with questions about their status and are covered by the case.
   Abascal said the INS also is required to contact aliens who have
been denied amnesty because of brief trips out of the country and
tell them their cases are being reopened.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880922-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 0524EDT</FILEID>
