<2ND_LINE>PM-Gandhi-Punjab, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0495,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Visits Punjab Amid Massive Security</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to restore time element.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GOINDWAL, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi, protected by
a bulletproof vest and shield, appealed for help in his
government's fight against Sikh terrorism on his first visit to the
embattled Punjab since 1985.
   Gandhi placed the foundation stone for a new paper mill in this
small village amid tight security on his one-day trip Wednesday to
the northern state, where Sikh extremists are fighting for an
independent homeland.
   The government hopes the $170 million mill will help pump new
life into a state shattered by six years of guerrilla and terrorist
attacks.
   Sikh radicals have killed more than 1,950 people in Punjab this
year, nearly double the toll for 1987.
   The prime minister was accompanied by more than 6,000
paramilitary troops, mostly armed with steel-tipped bamboo sticks,
and stood at the podium behind a bulletproof shield.
   ``The anti-nationals want to break democracy in India, but we
must give our lives to maintain it,'' Gandhi said, wearing a
bulletproof vest as he addressed the crowd of 15,000 factory
workers, students and teachers.
   ``We have no fight with the Sikhs, only the terrorists. We are
fighting strongly, and we are getting results,'' the prime minister
said, speaking in Hindi.
   Punjab is the only Indian state with a Sikh majority.
Nationwide, members of the Sikh faith comprise just 2 percent of
India's 800 million people, but they form 60 percent of Punjab's 18
million people.
   Punjab has been one of the biggest crises for the Gandhi
government, which fears the separatist movement could become a
full-scale civil war and fan insurgencies by other restless
minorities.
   ``We maintain respect for all religions,'' Gandhi told the crowd.
   Gandhi's mother, Prime Minister Indira Gandhi, was assassinated
by two of her Sikh bodyguards in October 1984, four months after
she ordered an army raid on the Golden Temple in the Punjab city of
Amritsar, where Sikh militants were holed up. More than 2,000
people, mostly Sikhs, died in the raid on Sikhdom's holiest shrine.
</TEXT>
