<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     09-22 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Latest Poll Shows Presidential Dead Heat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush and Michael Dukakis are locked in a
statistical dead heat in a presidential race that could be decided
by a large number of independents who remain undecided, according
to a poll released today by The Atlanta Journal and The Atlanta
Constitution.
   Bush, the Republican nominee, held a 43-40 percent lead over the
Democratic candidate, a margin that close to others that have shown
him picking up ground quickly since the GOP convention in August.
   Another 15 percent were undecided, however, including 40 percent
of the registered voters who labeled themselves independent.
   The survey completed Sunday polled 2,355 voters nationwide. It
has a margin of error of plus or minus two percentage point,
rendering Bush's advantage potentially insignificant.
   Of those calling themselves independent, 33 percent said they
favored Bush and 22 percent chose Dukakis.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Pulls Even in Democratic Maryland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush has pulled even with
Michael Dukakis in Maryland, a state where Democrats hold a
two-to-one edge over Republicans, according to a new poll.
   The results released Wednesday by WBAL-TV show Bush closing a
Dukakis lead that had been 21 percentage points several months ago.
   In the latest survey of 638 likely voters conducted Sept. 8-11,
Dukakis was favored by a margin of 48-47 percent, with 5 percent
undecided. The margin of error of the poll was plus or minus three
percentage points.
   The poll was conducted for the television station by Western
Maryland College political science professor Herbert C. Smith.
</TEXT>
