<DOCNO> AP880922-0060 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 0833EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DomesticViolence     09-22 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Domestic Violence,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Faults Judge, Others For Freeing Man Who Later Killed Two,
Then Self</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS G. KATSARELAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man on parole for manslaughter and held
for harassment was freed on $500 bail and allowed to commit a
double murder-suicide because a judge did not take steps to
discover the man's violent past, a report said.
   The report by Morris County Assignment Judge Reginald Stanton
also said failures by probation officers, prosecutors and family
caseworkers contributed to the release of Nicolas Vutca of
Parsippany-Troy Hills.
   No officials will be disciplined, however, because no one was
guilty of ``repeated acts'' of violating proper procedures, Stanton
said.
   Vutca, a Romanian national, killed his wife, Dorina, and her
mother, Maria Vacariu, on Sept. 10 at their home in Effort, Pa.,
and then shot himself to death.
   ``Looking at the total situation, we see an incredible
combination of things that went wrong,'' said Stanton's report,
which was released Tuesday and submitted to state Supreme Court
Chief Justice Robert Wilentz.
   ``If any one of them had gone right, the tragic consequence
might have been avoided.''
   Vutca was convicted of aggravated manslaughter in 1983 in the
stabbing death a year earlier of his live-in girlfriend. He was
paroled in 1986 and married Dorina last year.
   Vutca was arrested Aug. 17 on charges of harassment and
violating a court order to stay away from his wife. Mrs. Vutca and
her mother then moved to Pennsylvania.
   Superior Court Judge Karen D. Russell set bail at $25,000 the
day of the arrest. The next day, Morris County Judge Paul Bangiola,
in a routine bail-review hearing, reduced the bail to $5,000, or
$500 if paid in cash.
   Vutca posted bail, tracked down his wife and mother-in-law and
shot them to death, authorities said.
   Stanton's report said Bangiola didn't know about Vutca's
manslaughter conviction when he lowered bail because Ms. Russell's
bail memorandum mentioning the conviction didn't arrive on his desk
until the next day.
   The report also said a probation officer failed to notify the
county prosecutor's office about Bangiola's hearing, and the
hearing was conducted without a prosecutor present.
   The report said ``many judges in Judge Bangiola's position would
have seen the $25,000 bail and suspected that the case must involve
something more than verbal threats.'' It said Bangiola could have
telephoned Ms. Russell or taken other steps to find out more about
Vutca's background.
   Bangiola said through his secretary he would not comment on the
report.
   Stanton said judges and court employees have been
``re-educated'' about proper procedures, and that workers and the
prosecutor's office have been encouraged to inform him or other
judges ``when they think something has gone wrong.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880922-0061 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 0832EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SynagogueArson     09-22 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Synagogue Arson,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Youth Says He's Sorry For Burning Synagogue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As Congregation Sharai Torah observed Yom Kippur
at a nearby Jewish school, a 12-year-old boy apologized for setting
fire to the congregation's building days earlier.
   Two youths were arrested on arson and other charges after they
allegedly spray-painted swastikas on the walls of the Orthodox
synagogue, set a fire and unrolled and burned six Torahs, the
sacred handwritten scrolls that contain the first five books of the
Old Testament.
   The crime, on the Sabbath before Yom Kippur, shocked Brooklyn's
huge Jewish community. An estimated 10,000 people turned out Sunday
for a memorial service for the burned Torahs.
   ``We believe that everything, including this fire, is from
God,'' said the president of the 300-member Brooklyn congregation,
Hirsch Wolf.
   The president of the Rabbinical Council of America, Rabbi Max N.
Schreier, issued a statement Wednesday calling it an ``act of
ruthless vandalism the likes of which have not been seen since the
Holocaust.''
   One of the accused youths, a 12-year-old boy identified only by
his first name, Joey, said he was only out to have fun Saturday
morning when he and a 15-year-old companion desecrated the
synagogue.
   In an interview with New York Newsday published Wednesday, Joey
said he hadn't known what a synagogue was and did not vandalize it
out of anti-Semitism. If he had the opportunity, he said, he would
tell members of the congregation, ``I'm really sorry.''
   Meanwhile, the president of a Bellaire, Ohio, synagogue that
closed two years ago donated a Torah to the Brooklyn congregation.
The Torah was flown to New York Tuesday in time for the sundown
start of Yom Kippur, the most solemn holiday on the Jewish calendar.
</TEXT>
