<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880922-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 0908EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Heart-FishOil     09-22 0621</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Heart-Fish Oil,0638</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study Finds Fish Oil Promising Addition to Common Heart Procedure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fish oil provides the first effective way of
keeping newly opened heart arteries working smoothly after
angioplasty, a procedure used on 200,000 Americans annually with
heart disease, according to a study published today.
   ``It looks very promising,'' said Dr. Gregory J. Dehmer. ``It's
the only agent so far that has even shown a hint of having an
effect. This study is a little like the light at the end of the
tunnel.''
   Dehmer, now a cardiologist at the University of North Carolina,
was in charge of the fish oil experiment at the Veterans
Administration Medical Center in Dallas.
   Angioplasty is widely used because it provides a non-surgical
alternative to coronary bypass operations for people with coronary
artery disease. Doctors use tiny balloons to squeeze open clogged
heart arteries.
   A major drawback of the procedure is restenosis, the spontaneous
reclosing of the newly cleared arteries. This happens in about
one-third of all patients within six months of their angioplasties.
   When the VA doctors tested fish oil on 82 men, they found that
it cut the restenosis rate by two to three times in men who were at
especially high risk of this complication.
   Reaction from other experts was mixed.
   Dr. Alexander Leaf of Massachusetts General Hospital, who is
conducting a major study of fish oil in angioplasty, said he
believes the therapy works.
   But Dr. Spencer B. King III of Emory University commented: ``My
main concern is that a lot of small studies have made it look like
restenosis was helped by so many different interventions. I would
like to see bigger numbers before I buy into this.''
   The study was published in today's New England Journal of
Medicine. One similar recent study also found that fish oil seemed
to prevent restenosis, while two others showed no effect.
   ``Although it's in the New England Journal, it's a little
premature to rush out and buy a carload of fish oil for every
angioplasty patient,'' said Dr. Donald Baim of Boston's Beth Israel
Hospital, a co-author of one of the negative studies.
   The researchers said they do not recommend that all angioplasty
patients take fish oil, because their study was too small to be the
basis of sweeping recommendations. And they said people undergoing
angioplasties should not take the supplements unless they discuss
it with their doctors.
   However, Dr. Eric H. Eichhorn, a co-author of the study,
commented, ``If I were undergoing angioplasty, the balance of
potential benefits versus risks is such that I would take it
myself.''
   Fish oil capsules, widely available in drug and health stores,
have been advertised as a way of warding off heart disease,
although evidence is still skimpy.
   Eskimos who eat large quantities of oily fish, such as salmon,
have remarkably low levels of heart disease. However, doctors
disagree over whether fish oil capsules will prevent the gradual
buildup of fatty deposits in the arteries, a process called
atherosclerosis, that underlies heart attacks.
   Leaf said the latest study suggests to him that fish oil
capsules may be of benefit to everyone at risk of heart disease,
not just those undergoing angioplasty.
   ``Since angioplasty restenosis pathologically appears to be a
very rapid progression of atherosclerosis, the fact that they find
they can prevent restenosis suggests that fish oil will prevent
coronary heart disease and heart attacks,'' Leaf said.
   In the latest study, half the patients took 18 capsules of
MaxEPA fish oil daily, starting a week before their angioplasties
and continuing for six months. After three months, 19 percent of
those who took fish oil had restenosis, compared with 46 percent in
the comparison group.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
