<HEAD>UNDATED: SUBS 1st item to restore embargo.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release at 11 a.m. EDT; time set by source.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The landmark 1986 tax overhaul boosted the
bite on 250 giant, profitable corporations by about $9 billion last
year but still left 16 of them legally paying no federal income
tax, a private research group said today.
   The number among the 250 that paid no tax was down from 40 in
1986 and from a high of 72 in 1982, according to Citizens for Tax
Justice, a labor-financed organization whose reports were credited
with helping win passage of the new tax law two years ago.
   The 1986 law cut tax rates for most individuals and corporations
but took away or reduced several deductions and credits. One result
was to shift about $125 billion of the federal tax burden from
individuals to corporations over a five-year period.

</TEXT>
