<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FiresRdp     09-22 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fires Rdp,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Onset Of Dry Weather Doesn't Concern Yellowstone Firefighters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YELLOWSTONE NATIONAL PARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warmer, drier weather was
returning today but officials expressed confidence that the fires
that have blackened half of the oldest national park would not
flare anew.
   Meanwhile, a newspaper report said park officials allowed fires
to burn unattended for nearly three weeks after they were ordered
to fight all fires because they wanted to protect pristine areas
from the destruction caused by bulldozers, fire engines and
irrigation equipment. In all, the fires have blackened roughly half
the park's 2.2 million acres.
   Elsewhere, officials banned outdoor smoking in parts of northern
California and hundreds of firefighters prepared to go home after a
9,000-acre blaze in Oregon was contained.
   The National Weather Service confirmed what firefighters in
Yellowstone already knew: This summer was one of the park's warmest
and driest on record.
   The weather service said Wednesday that temperatures at the
Mammoth area of the park in June averaged 55.4, or 7.8 degrees
higher than average. Average temperature in July was 66.4 degrees,
2.8 degrees above average. Temperatures were just slightly above
normal in August.
   Rainfall totals were more than an inch less than normal each
month, and the weather service said it is unlikely any major
precipitation will offset the park's shortage soon.
   Steady rain Tuesday prevented the remaining blazes from growing
significantly. Although skies have since cleared, longer nights are
bringing longer periods of ``humidity recovery,'' when small fuels
such as pine needles and twigs can soak up moisture, area commander
Ken Dittmer said.
   ``The worst is over,'' Dittmer said.
   Forecasts for the weekend called for another cooling trend,
accompanied by a chance of showers, which could help the 4,500
firefighters battling the blazes. Winds are expected to remain calm.
   The New York Times reported today that officials concerned about
the destruction caused by firefighting equipment did not fight the
Yellowstone portion of the Clover-Mist fire until nearly three
weeks after Interior Secretary Donald P. Hodel's July 21 order that
all fires be fought.
   Bulldozers were allowed in the park only on a case-by-case basis
even at the height of the fires, the paper reported, and bulldozers
were never used to make fire lines around the Yellowstone part of
the Clover-Mist blaze, which has burned 411,000 acres in the park
and the adjacent Shoshone National Forest.
   The Times also reported that park rangers threatened a
firefighting crew with citations for destroying park vegetation
when they crossed a meadow with their truck to extinguish a spot
fire.
   Elsewhere, state firefighters battling blazes that have charred
more than 40,000 acres in northern California issued an emergency
decree banning outdoor smoking in portions of 44 counties.
   Jerry Partain, director of the California Department of
Forestry, said ``the extreme danger'' posed by fire and acute dry
conditions prompted the decree.
   Fire officials predicted they will have the Vacaville fire out
by Saturday evening. The blaze has destroyed seven homes, blackened
27,000 acres and caused an estimated $1.83 million in damage.
   In Oregon, 400 firefighters were scheduled to go home from the
Shady Beach fire in Willamette National Forest after the blaze was
contained at just under 9,000 acres Wednesday night, U.S. Forest
Service spokesman Chuck Tonn said. Another 400 firefighters are
scheduled for release Friday, leaving fewer than 1,000 on the
lines, he said.
</TEXT>
