<HEAD>Gun-Toting 7-Year-Old to be Transferred, Officials Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKELAND, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 7-year-old accused of making sexual
remarks and waving an unloaded .38-caliber handgun at his
first-grade classmates will be transferred to another school after
undergoing psychological testing, officials say.
   ``Looking at the severity and the sadness ... the boy is in need
of some help. I intend to pursue psychological testing,'' John A.
Stewart, Polk County school superintendent, said Wednesday.
   The outcome of the evaluation will determine whether he is sent
to a school for children with emotional problems, said Bill Duncan,
who oversees discipline for Polk County schools.
   Crystal Lake Elementary School Principal W. James Pace sent a
letter home with students Wednesday, informing parents of a
sheriff's investigation and assuring them their children were safe
at school.
   ``It is also not fair to blame the school because this
happened,'' he wrote. ``This could happen at any school.''
   The boy, who told investigators he brought the handgun from
home, was suspended immediately after the Sept. 12 incident,
Stewart said.
   He apparently pulled the gun from his knapsack twice, once after
a gym class and again after school. There reportedly were some
sexual remarks shouted at a girl followed by angry banter between
the boy and another boy, Stewart said.
   He also carried two bullets, but they were too large to fit the
gun, which authorities described as a derringer.
   After receiving reports from investigators, Stewart said he was
particularly disturbed by the ``level of violence and strange level
of knowledge of sexual behavior at such an early age.''
   ``We need to see what is at the root of the problem,'' Stewart
added.
   The boy and others from the group were questioned Wednesday to
determine what happened. Stewart said he will study results of that
closed, fact-finding session before making any decisions.
   ``Expulsion may not be the best approach with a boy this age _
he wouldn't learn anything by expulsion,'' said Stewart.
   Sheriff Detective Paul Baggett said the boy may have made a
derogatory sexual statement to a girl while the children were
walking home, but his statement was not a demand for sexual favors,
as some officials had reported earlier.
</TEXT>
