<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FrequentLifesaver     09-22 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Frequent Lifesaver,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officer Called to Help Save Choking Baby Two Nights in a Row</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEYMOUTH, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Weymouth Police Officer Tony Giorgi is
ready for anything in the line of duty _ especially choking babies.
He's saved two on back-to-back nights by coaching mothers over the
telephone.
   Giorgi, who helped save one baby Monday night, said he couldn't
believe it when a call came in Tuesday night from another panicky
mother.
   ``I thought it was a joke,'' Giorgi said. ``I couldn't believe
it was happening again.''
   Mark Landry was feeding formula to his 12-day-old daughter Elise
when she vomited and began to turn red. Landry's wife, Karen,
called police.
   While an ambulance was dispatched, Giorgi coached Mrs. Landry on
how to help dislodge the food caught in the baby's throat.
   ``I heard something and I said, `Is that the baby crying?' The
mother was still upset, but I knew that as long as she (the baby)
was crying, she was breathing. I told them we were out of the
woods,'' Giorgi said.
   The child had apparently choked on thick formula in her throat.
She was taken to South Shore Hospital and released.
   Monday night, Giorgi helped save 6-month-old Kelly Bobo, who was
choking on a clothing tag. Giorgi told the baby's mother, Susan
Bobo, over the phone how to fish the tag out of the baby's mouth
with her finger.
   Giorgi, 40, said saving the babies has renewed him after a
period of personal and professional turmoil.
   During a leave from 1984 to 1986, Giorgi was indicted, tried and
acquitted on charges connected to a Weymouth drugstore break-in. He
is now a department dispatcher.
</TEXT>
