<2ND_LINE>PM-Name In Blood,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Victim In Double Homicide Scrawled A Name On Bloody
Floor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Scottsbluff, the town, is cq in 2nd and 7th grafs; Scotts
Bluff County is cq in 9th graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GERING, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One victim of a double homicide used a tube
of white grease and the bloody floor of his kitchen to scrawl out a
name before he died, authorities said.
   Richard Valdez, 25, squeezed grease onto the floor and wrote the
letters ``JFF BOPE,'' according to an affidavit for the arrest of
Jeff J. Boppre, 25, a Scottsbluff resident whose whereabouts is
unknown to police.
   The message was found next to Valdez's body and the tube of
grease was found partly underneath his body Monday, the affidavit
said.
   Valdez's father said Valdez told family and friends that someone
was out to kill him, and he had vowed to leave a message behind if
he died.
   ``He told me if he was killed, he would write his name in his
own blood _ he'd write the name of the guy that did the shooting,''
Gilbert Valdez Sr. said.
   The warrant for Boppre's arrest charges him with two counts of
first-degree murder in the shooting deaths of Valdez and Valdez's
girlfriend, Sharon Condon, 19. The victims were shot a number of
times with a small-caliber handgun, officials said. Ms. Condon was
six to seven months pregnant.
   The victims' bodies were found Monday in a house about 1{ miles
north of Scottsbluff, which is near the Wyoming border. Shell
casings found at the scene matched shell casings found at Boppre's
residence, officials said.
   The slayings may be drug-related, authorities said Wednesday.
   Scotts Bluff County Attorney Brian Silverman said Boppre and
Valdez had dealt with drugs in the past. In the house, police found
$11,000 in cash, more than 3 pounds of marijuana and a number of
small packets of cocaine worth about $3,000, the affidavit said.
</TEXT>
