<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 0950EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Britain-Czechs     09-22 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Czechs,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Britain Expels Three Czech Diplomats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain today ordered the explusion of three Czech
diplomats, including two military attaches, for engaging in
``activities incompatible with their status.''
   The terse announcement by the Foreign Office was couched in the
diplomatic parlance for spying.
   The statement said the Czechoslovak ambassador, Jan Fidler, was
summoned to the Foreign Office this morning and told the three must
leave Britain within 14 days.
   The expelled diplomats were Maj. Bedrich Kramar, the assistant
military and air attache; Maj. Vlastmil Netolicky, a member of the
military attache's staff; and Paval Moudry, a member of the
commercial section.
   Britain last expelled Czech diplomats in 1984 when two were
ordered out, and Communist Czechoslovakia expelled two diplomats in
retaliation.
   Two other Czech diplomats had been ordered out the previous year.
   ``The foreign secretary (Sir Geoffrey Howe) wishes it to be
clearly understood that, while we wish to build up our relations
with Czechoslovakia, we are not prepared to relax our policy on the
sort of activities to which May. Kramar, Maj. Netolicky and Mr.
Moudry had engaged,'' the Foreign Office announcement said.
   A ministry spokesman refused to elaborate on the allegations
against the three envoys. Kramar and Moudry have been posted in
Britain since 1984, and Netolicky arrived in September 1985, the
Foreign Office said.
   The Foreign Office expelled three other diplomats recently for
offenses ranging from traffic violations to carrying guns.
   A Cuban diplomat was sent home this month along with Cuba's
ambassador for firing a gun at intelligence agents tailing him in a
London street. A Vietnamese envoy was expelled for pulling a gun on
demonstrators outside his embassy, and a Tunisian was expelled for
refusing to pay parking fines.
</TEXT>
