<2ND_LINE>PM-Provincial Strike,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tentative Contract Reached With Civil Service Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tentative agreement that
would end a provincewide civil service strike over wages was
reached after nearly 15 hours of talks.
   ``It doesn't go all the way but it goes far enough that the
bargaining committee is prepared to recommend it to the
membership,'' union president John Shields said Wednesday. ``We
hope that we can get them back to work.''
   During the strike that began Saturday, about 27,000 of the
union's 29,000 members stayed out of work, closing government
offices and liquor stores.
   Mediator Don Munroe said he expected ratification to be
completed Saturday and workers back on the job by Monday.
   An exhausted Munroe told a late-night news conference Wednesday
that a three-year deal had been reached that includes a wage
increase of 5{ percent, retroactive to Aug. 1, and increases 5 and
5{ percent in the following two years.
   The deal came after Premier Bill Vander Zalm said there should
be more money for some provincial government employees. One Social
Services Ministry clerk with two children said issues welfare
checks larger than her pay to families the same size as hers.
   During the strike, the Social Services Ministry opened an
emergency center in Vancouver to handle urgent cases. Regular mail
delivery of welfare checks wasn't affected.
   Prison guards and some health-care workers, considered to be
essential services, stayed on the job.
</TEXT>
