<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Yugoslavia     09-22 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Slavic Students Demonstrate Against Albanians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of chanting, flag-waving
Slavic students called a school strike today and marched around the
capital of ethnically troubled Kosovo, protesting alleged
harassment by Albanians.
   About 1,000 teen-agers marched behind the red, blue and white
flag of Yugoslavia's largest republic, Serbia, after going to four
schools to declare a boycott of classes and collect supporters for
their protest.
   Plainclothes police kept a close watch, but there was no atempt
to interfere and uniformed police stopped traffic on the main
thoroughfare to allow the marchers to pass.
   The march illustrated the high level of tension in this city of
200,000.
   ``We are afraid to go to school,'' said the students when youth
officials tried to persuade them to return to class.
   On Tuesday night, about 5,000 Serbs and Montenegrins, both
Slavs, rallied after a Serbian girl allegedly was attacked by an
ethnic Albanian Monday night.
   That rally was one of the latest in a series of meetings backing
Serbian Communist Party leader Slobodan Milosevic, who wants more
control over Serbia's two autonomous provinces of Vojvodina and
Kosovo.
   Kosovo, one of Yugoslavia's poorest and most backward regions,
has a history of ethnic tension between Serbs and Montenegrins, who
see the province as their historic homeland, and the Albanians, who
now make up about 90 percent of Kosovo's 2 million people.
   In 1981, ethnic riots left at least nine dead and prompted
federal authorities in Belgrade to impose martial law for a few
weeks.
   Kosovo's Albanians have not yet staged any public protests in
response to the current wave of Slav rallies. But Serbs allege
individual harassment by Albanians have increased and nervous
residents in both ethnic groups report tension at a high level.
   Federal authorities dispatched extra police units, equipped with
armored pesonnel carriers, to Kosovo earlier this month.
   Today's protest started when about 200 Slav teenagers walked up
the central downtown street, chanting ``Kosovo is Serbia,'' and
``We will give our lives, but we will not give Kosovo.''
   Some participants said the march was sparked by the alleged rape
attempt Monday night, but others said there had been fresh trouble
Wednesday involving a fight between Albanian and Serbian students.
   A worried Serbian mother, who did not identify herself, sobbed
outside one school: ``Children should not solve problems. I have a
child in there. I am afraid.''
   A Serbian woman, looking at the march, said, ``What will happen
now? Albanian kids know who is marching and they could do
something.''
</TEXT>
