<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Cathedral-Attack 1stLd-Writethru a0482 09-22 0749</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cathedral-Attack, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0482,0766</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nude Man Kills Usher, Wounds Police Officer Inside St. Patrick's
Cathedral</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Recasts lead. SUBS 4th graf pvs, `That evening,' with 5 grafs
to UPDATE with morning purification rite, picking up 5th graf pvs,
`He suddenly...'. SUBS 20th graf, `The cardinal...,' to delete
outdated reference to purification rite.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A deranged man ran naked into St. Patrick's
Cathedral, then killed an elderly usher and seriously injured a
police officer with an iron prayerbook stand before being shot and
killed by police, officials said.
   The 250-pound attacker, identified as Jorge DelGado, 32, of
Manhattan, had attended morning Mass celebrated by Cardinal John
O'Connor prior to Wednesday's attack and stood directly before the
cardinal as he administered the Holy Eucharist, O'Connor told
reporters.
   ``I felt he was totally disoriented. The cathedral is a magnet
for all people. People sleep in it and engage in the strangest
behavior in the cathedral. I patted him on the shoulder and said,
`God bless you.' He stood for a moment and left,'' O'Connor said.
   O'Connor performed a purification rite before the 8 a.m. Mass
today. The Rev. Peter Finn, a spokesman, said the rite is performed
``whenever a sacred place has been violated and profaned.''
   It was the first time the rite was performed in the 109-year
history of the cathedral.
   ``While the cathedral has been desecrated, while this
magnificent temple of almighty God, famous throughout the world,
has been violated, we must not forget that two men were killed here
last night,'' the cardinal told several hundred people who attended
the morning service.
   ``It is for their souls I will be offering this Mass, as well as
for the purification of the cathedral,'' the cardinal said.
   Wednesday evening, the man tore off all his clothes down the
street from the historic midtown cathedral, walked one block to the
church, chanting under his breath and carrying red carnations,
according to witnesses.
   ``He suddenly stopped, stripped, and headed up the street. He
was obviously disturbed,'' said a witness, Scott Lucas, 56. ``He
was not aware of anybody else.''
   Upon entering the church he repeatedly struck a woman praying in
a pew, ripped the prayer book stanchion from the marble floor where
it was bolted near the front altar, and then used it to strike and
kill the 77-year-old usher, John Winters, and wound officer James
McMann, police and witnesses said.
   ``Everyone backed away. Then the cops rushed in. (The woman) was
screaming very loud that she was getting hit and needed help. But
everyone was running away from her. We ran,'' said another witness,
Luis Gonzalez of Brooklyn.
   About six or seven people were present as the man began to
attack the woman, said Thomas Clark of Queens. ``He starts hitting
her with his hand and he starts punching her.''
   Clark said that after the woman ran out of the church he told
the police officer that ```a man is running around nude in the
church, by the altar now and he's unarmed.' And the cop tries to
convince him to leave.'''
   Meanwhile, the attacker ``picks up a metal stand and starts
swinging it around, go wild crazy, and he hits the cop a couple of
times,'' Clark said.
   A backup police unit arrived and shot the attacker once in the
chest, killing him, said Sgt. Raymond O'Donnell, a police
spokesman. He fell to the floor in a center aisle, police said.
   The 3-foot-long metal stanchion was found about 7 feet away from
him, said Detective Joseph Gallagher.
   Winters, a Queens resident, died inside the front rail of the
altar near the pulpit, police said. He suffered a large gash to the
head, Gallagher said.
   McMann, 50, suffered a head injury that did not appear to be
life-threatening, said Police Capt. Richard Valentine. He was in
serious but stable condition early today at Bellevue Hospital, said
Nick Marletta, a hospital administrator.
   The woman's identity and her injuries were not immediately
known, police said.
   The cardinal said the man allegedly had committed acts of minor
vandalism in and around the church in the past.
   ``Two people are dead and a police officer is seriously
wounded,'' the cardinal said. ``There is no tragedy comparable to
that. It's very serious to me and all Catholics.''
   Mayor Edward I. Koch, who embraced O'Connor at the conclusion of
a news conference outside the cathedral, said, ``We are very lucky
he didn't assault the cardinal.''
</TEXT>
