<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Korea-Protests     09-22 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Protests,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radical Students Burn U.S. Effigies In Olympic Protests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By C.W. LIM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Student demonstrators today burned
effigies of Americans and persisted with demands that the Olympic
Games be shared with rival North Korea.
   About 1,700 students from 12 universities in the capital took
part in the demonstration at Yonsei University to demand the
communist north be allowed to co-host the Games, which began
Saturday and end Oct. 2
   The International Olympic Committee has ruled the Games cannot
be shared because they are given to a single city.
   The students also called for expulsion of U.S. forces from South
Korea. The United States has 42,000 troops based in South Korea
under a mutual defense treaty. The Korean peninsula has been
divided since 1945.
   ``Oppose dictatorial Olympics!'' the students yelled.
   Two thousand riot police wearing combat fatigues and black
visored helmets blocked the way when the students marched to the
school gate and appeared ready to move to the streets. The
students, however, stayed inside the campus, and no confrontation
occurred.
   Chanting slogans and raising their fists in the air, the
students marched around the campus as speakers called for a drive
to force out the U.S. soldiers stationed in South Korea.
   Protesters burned figures with U.S. and Japanese flags painted
on them. ``Yankee go home!'' students yelled. They charge the
United States and Japan are helping strengthen authoritarian rule
in South Korea.
   Speakers also claimed the Olympics heightened the risk of war on
the divided Korean peninsula. U.S. forces in South Korea are on
increased alert against possible threats from North Korea during
the Games, and U.S. and Japanese naval forces are helping patrol
the surrounding seas.
   Huge placards hanging down the sides school buildings read
``Oppose the Olympics, which perpetuate the national division'' and
``No war and no nuclear bombs.''
   In a related development, President Roh Tae-woo said today he
has not decided yet whether to accept North Korean President Kim Il
Sung's proposal for talks with him because the proposal contains
``something unclear and ambiguous.''
   ``I will have my position known after scrutinizing the real
intention of North Korea,'' Roh said in an interview with The
Joongang Daily News, a Korean language national newspaper.
   The summit, if held, would be the first between the two Koreas.
</TEXT>
