<2ND_LINE>PM-SF Fire,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five-Alarm Fire In San Francisco</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spectacular five-alarm fire roared
through a drug store under construction in the Haight-Ashbury
District today with heat so intense that paint on buildings across
the street caught fire, officials said.
   The blaze two blocks from Golden Gate Park sent flames and
embers into the pre-dawn sky and forced residents of several
apartments to flee. No injuries were reported.
   ``The wind was blowing so hard the fire was hopping the
street,'' said Jim Tonn, who lives a block from the fire. Tonn said
he fled about 4:30 a.m. when the heat and smoke awoke him.
   Two hours later, firefighters had reduced the blaze
considerably, with only spots of fire and heavy smoke remaining.
Arson investigators were at the scene, police said.
   The fire burned part of the I-Beam, a nightclub next to the drug
store. The buildings across the street whose paint caught fire had
broken windows but were not seriously damaged.
   A pickup truck and a car parked next to the three-story,
partially constructed drug store were also destroyed, said police
Sgt. Joyce Watkins.
   ``It was so hot we couldn't stand here,'' said Watkins,
referring to an area half a block from the blaze. Policemen who
arrived to evacuate nearby residents reported hairs on their arms
were burned.
   ``It (the fire) must have been going 40 to 50 feet in the air,''
said Jody Spencer, who liveslections
would be held as soon as peace was restored. Saw Maung seized power
in a coup Sunday, toppling civilian President Maung Maung, and
became prime minister Wednesday.
   ``We urge the government not to arrest people including the
monks, students, artists ... in connection with the recent unrest
and also to release those already under detention,'' said the
letter from opposition leaders Aung Gyi, Tin Oo, and Aung San Suu
Kyi.
   Since the coup, security forces have broken up protest centers
manned mostly by monks and students in at least 95 towns.
Government spokesman Kyaw San said Wednesday authorities arrested
100 looters in northern Rangoon on Tuesday but had no knowledge of
a reported roundup of student leaders.
   The opposition figures also urged Saw Maung to end his ban on
newspapers and announce a list of those killed by soldiers since
the coup.
   By official count, troops have killed at least 144 people since
the coup. A Western ambassador said the actual death toll may be as
high as 400.
   Rangoon was calm today, with no street demonstrations for the
third consecutive day after daily demonstrations the past two
months.
   More roadside shops were open than the previous day, but larger
markets remained closed. Government offices were open but
unstaffed, with most public employees continuing pro-democracy
strikes begun Aug. 8.
   Sketchy reports received today from Mandalay, the second-largest
city, and other towns said there had also been fighting between
security forces and protesters, though not as fierce as those in
the capital.
   The opposition leaders first wrote to Saw Maung Tuesday, calling
for dialogue to resolve the crisis. The next day they received Saw
Maung's letter, his first contact with the opposition figures.
   In his letter, Saw Maung did not directly respond to the call
for dialogue. He asked the opposition leaders' help in achieving
what he said were his government's objectives of restoring law and
order, improving living conditions and holding a general election.
   ``The army has no intention to retain the duties of state power
for a long time,'' said the letter, a copy of which was shown to
The Associated Press today. ``We had to step in unavoidably because
of the deteriorating general conditions in the country.''
   ``We promise you,'' the letter continued, ``that free and fair
general elections will be held as soon as peace and tranquility are
restored.''
   Saw Maung also said political parties will be allowed to use
radio and television for campaigning. He has not set a date for
elections.
   Burma has been ruled with an iron fist by the sole legal party,
the military-dominated Burma Socialist Program Party, since the
1962 coup that toppled an elected government. On Sept. 10, Maung
Maung bowed to massive street protests and agreed to hold
multiparty elections as soon as early October.
   But the opposition rejected that and continued street
demonstrations demanding that an interim government be formed to
conduct the balloting.
   A Western diplomat following events from Bangkok, Thailand, said
Saw Maung's letter may be an attempt ``to blunt the opposition by
taking them in.'' But he said it was significant that the general
had established dialogue with the opposition.
   Opposition leaders had succeeded in keeping the protests
peaceful, but that changed after Sunday's coup.
   Mobs have attacked government targets with weapons seized from
police stations and other places. One group opened fire with a
grenade launcher and automatic weapons late Tuesday at soldiers
guarding the City Hall and the main government administration
building in downtown Rangoon.
   The past two months of turmoil began after long-time strongman
Ne Win resigned in late July and widespread riots flared against
hard-liner Sein Lwin, his successor. Sein Lwin resigned Aug. 12.
   On Aug. 19, Maung Maung became the first civilian leader since
1962.
   Diplomats say Saw Maung, like Sein Lwin and Maung Maung, is a
close associate of Ne Win and the coup may have been staged to
preserve the ruling military autocracy.
   Ne Win's coup ended Burma's brief experiment with democracy and
began a quarter century of rigid, inept central planning that
ruined the economy of one of the Asian countries most richly
endowed in natural resources.
</TEXT>
