<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FondaTapes     09-22 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fonda Tapes,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fonda Tapes Back On Navy Store's Shelves</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GROTON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jane Fonda's exercise videotapes are back
on the shelves of a Naval submarine base store after the commanding
officer reversed a decision to remove them, a base spokesman said.
   Declaring that the tapes are not prejudicial to good order and
discipline, Capt. John Cox ordered that the store could again sell
them, Lt. Cmdr. John Ward said Wednesday.
   The tapes had been removed from the military store's shelves
after complaints about Fonda's anti-Vietnam War activities, Ward
said.
   Ward said while Cox was on leave, an officer ordered the tapes
removed from the shelves. When the captain returned, he ordered the
tapes put back. The tapes are not big sellers at the base, Ward
said.
   Groton resident John W. Pillar, who complained to Navy
authorities about the sale of the tapes, said he was ``very, very
disappointed'' by the decision.
   ``We don't feel she (Fonda) should be making money on the bodies
of the men who were lost over there, that is what it amounts to,''
Pillar said.
   This summer, Fonda apologized on national television to veterans
who may have been hurt by her actions during a 1972 visit to Hanoi
in which she was photographed with a North Vietnamese anti-aircraft
gun.
   Fonda's publicist, Stephen M. Rivers, declined comment Wednesday
night on the tapes.
</TEXT>
