<2ND_LINE>PM-Campaign Spending, 1st-Ld Writethru, a0481,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Spending Record Amount On Television</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with Bush aide confirming TV budget; no
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush's campaign will spend a
modern record of about 60 percent of its $54 million budget for
television advertising this fall, a Bush aide said today.
   Presidential campaigns traditionally set aside about half of
their federally restricted funds for paid media and the other half
for campaign organization.
   The Bush aide, who spoke only on condition that he not be
identified, said 60 percent or $32.4 million is ``a pretty accurate
figure, which would make it the largest television expenditure in
modern history.''
   The Washington Post, quoting an unnamed Bush aide, said the GOP
campaign is benefiting so much from the use of money raised by the
Republican Party for political activities that it can use a far
larger share for advertising.
   Both campaigns are limited by federal law to a $54 budget, with
$46 million coming from the federal treasury.
   Mark Gearan, a spokesman for Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis,
said Wednesday, ``I think we'll be competitive with the Bush
campaign, but beyond that we don't detail our spending.''
   He said the high amount spent by the Bush campaign is not
surprising ``in this market.''
</TEXT>
