<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PullmanSuit     09-22 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pullman Suit,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Actions Nearing End In 23-Year-Old Racial Bias Lawsuit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CURT ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new court decision may finally end a
23-year-old racial discrimination case filed by black workers at an
Alabama railroad car manufacturing plant.
   The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals issued a ruling Wednesday
in the workers' case against Pullman-Standard Division of
Chicago-based Pullman Inc. The court gave a partial victory to the
workers, ordering a lower court to determine damages for workers
who suffered discrimination between 1965 and 1974 but ruling in
favor of the company in other aspects of the case.
   ``Few cases better represent the idea that the road to justice
can be a long and tortured one,'' Circuit Judge Thomas A. Clark
wrote in a prologue to the decision.
   Complaints of racial discrimination were first brought by the
workers shortly after President Lyndon Johnson signed legislation
that accommodated such claims.
   At the time, according to court documents, the factory in
Bessemer, Ala., was divided into 28 departments, some of them
integrated but many either all-white or all-black. The black jobs
paid less.
   In 1965, an arbitration decision opened up some jobs to blacks,
but Pullman stopped its on-the-job training program that enabled
many blacks to attain the skills needed to work at the plant.
   Four years later, Pullman entered into an agreement with the
Department of Labor to encourage blacks to move into the previously
all-white departments and develop a program of outside vocational
development.
   But several complaints of racial discrimination were filed with
the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission between 1966 and 1969.
In 1972 the commission consolidated all the complaints and found
that Pullman had discriminated in hiring, promotion and job
assignments.
   Just before the commission's ruling, worker Louis Swint filed a
class-action lawsuit contending that Pullman practiced racial
discrimination, and the case went to trial in 1974. Swint won,
kicking off a litany of appeals, cross-appeals, trials and
reversals.
   In the meantime, Pullman closed its Bessemer plant in 1982,
putting some 3,500 people out of work. It was later purchased by
Trinity Industries and still makes railroad cars, employing about
600 people, said plant safety director Festus Pierce.
   Many of the original workers have since died, according to court
documents.
   Four trials were held on Swint's lawsuit, and the case made it
to the U.S. Supreme Court in 1982. After the fourth trial, in 1986,
both sides appealed once again to the 11th Circuit.
   Wednesday, the appeals court upheld a lower court's ruling that
Pullman's seniority system was not created or maintained in order
to further discrimination. The appeals court also said evidence
showed that discrimination in departmental assignments ended in
February 1969.
   But one issue was reversed in the workers' favor and sent back
to U.S. District Court in Birmingham, Ala., to determine damages.
The appeals court said Pullman should be held liable for any
discrimination occurring between October 1965 and January 1969 on
job assignments.
   In addition, it said Pullman is liable for discrimination in
promotions that happened between September 1966 and August 1974.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
