<DOCNO> AP880922-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 1131EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-MinisterTrial     09-22 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Minister Trial,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minister Convicted In Beheading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A minister was convicted today of
killing and beheading a church handyman and setting the church on
fire in a bid to leave Nashville and establish a new identity.
   The Circuit Court jury deliberated three hours Wednesday night
and an hour this morning before finding John David Terry guilty of
murder and arson. The sentencing portion of the trial was to begin
later today.
   Terry, 43, looked calm as the verdict was read.
   He was accused of killing handyman James Chester Matheny,
cutting off the man's head and other parts of his body to make
identification difficult, and leaving the body in his Emmanuel
Church of Christ Oneness Pentecostal, which he then set on fire.
   Prosecutors said Terry killed Matheny, 32, in June 1987 in an
attempt to make it look as though he himself had been slain, so
that he could adopt a new identity and start a new life.
   Matheny's headless body was found in the ruins of the church,
but the head was never found. The exact cause of death was never
determined.
   In his closing argument, Assistant District Attorney General
John Zimmermann called Terry a calculating killer ``with ice in his
veins, not blood.''
   ``You may never hear of a more cold-blooded, brutal murder than
this one,'' Zimmermann said.
   Defense lawyer Lionel Barrett presented no witnesses on Terry's
behalf and did not make a closing statement, saying ``the real
trial will begin'' if the jury is asked to impose the death
sentence. Barrett said he planned to argue that Terry was suffering
from some sort of ``mental condition'' when Matheny was killed.
   Zimmermann argued that Terry began planning the crime early last
year, after receiving $50,700 from the sale of church property,
unknown to other church officials, and after learning that he would
not get a promotion he had expected.
   The prosecutor told the jury that Terry picked a name ``off a
tombstone'' of a child who died in 1951 and began assembling
identification papers in that person's name. The child had been
born three days before Terry in 1944.
</TEXT>
