<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GayRodeo     09-22 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gay Rodeo,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ACLU Blasts University for Discriminatory Practices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Civil Liberties Union has accused
University of Nevada-Reno officials of persistent discrimination
and said its refusal to allow a gay rodeo at a campus arena is just
the latest example.
   ``Face it, if you're not a friend of the university and if
you're in some minority group, you don't have a chance there,''
state ACLU Executive Director Shelley Chase said.
   Her office is working on six discrimination cases against the
school _ involving complaints based on sex, age, race and handicap
_ and has joined one lawsuit.
   Ms. Chase held a news conference Wednesday in front of the
Lawlor Events Center to protest the school's refusal to allow the
national gay rodeo championship finals to be held there Oct. 22-23,
despite organizers' successful efforts to raise an extra $9,600 to
cover expenses in advance.
   Donald Klasic, general counsel for the state university system,
denied the school and Lawlor wrongfully reneged on a verbal deal in
which officials agreed to hold the event if backers presented the
$9,600.
   ``The dates are taken for the basketball team to practice,''
Klasic said. ``This agreement was reached on Aug. 31 after it
appeared that the rodeo wouldn't be taking place.''
   ``There's not a word of truth (to the discrimination charges),''
he added. ``The coaches simply feel that the more time spent
practicing in Lawlor, the better the home court advantage.''
   Ms. Chase, however, said the basketball team normally defers to
scheduled events and practices elsewhere.
   ``It's just too much of a coincidence,'' she said. ``And we've
been trying to talk to them and they won't even return our calls
now.''
   On Monday, the International Gay Rodeo and Silver State Gay
Rodeo associations lost a court battle against Lawlor.
   A Washoe District Court judge ruled that the groups had verbally
modified a February written contract by agreeing to meet a
pre-payment schedule to cover expenses for parking, security and
other operating costs.
   But the rodeo organizers, who already had paid $7,300 to rent
the arena, could only raise about $2,200 of the expense money and
thus broke the contract, Judge William Forman said.
   Lawlor director Richard Linio told Forman the Oct. 22-23 dates
were still open. And Rod Sumpter, the attorney for the
associations, said Lawlo officials later said the stadium would
still hold the rodeo if the expense money were presented in advance.
   But when Sumpter told the university Tuesday that an anonymous
businessman had written a check for the additional money, officials
told him the stadium was booked, he said.
   Klasic said it was a simple mistake and Linio wasn't aware the
dates had already been taken by the team.
   Sumpter said his clients were continuing to look for a place in
Reno to hold the October finals, in which the top riders and ropers
from regional events compete.
</TEXT>
