<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RoadRace     09-22 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Road Race,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vintage Autos And Sports Cars Set For Unique Speed Contest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rodger in 2nd graf is cq</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixty-year-old sedans and newer Porsches,
Maseratis and Corvettes will open their throttles along a 93-mile
stretch of remote Nevada highway this weekend in the nation's first
legal open-road race in decades.
   But the first Silver State Classic has no prize money, no ticket
sales and spectators are not encouraged, said race organizer and
two-time Indianapolis 500 winner Rodger Ward, president of Vintage
Racing Club in Redondo Beach, Calif.
   ``This is not a spectator event,'' said Ward, who won the 500
and the U.S. Auto Club championship in 1959 and 1962. ``This is a
speed event all the way and is made so people with vintage cars can
get them on the road and test them.
   ``No one will be allowed along the highways. Well, if people
want they can watch the race start or wait at the finish line.''
   ``There's really not much along the highway, mostly dirt roads,
some driveways and farms,'' Ward said. ``We'll have guards at all
32 highway access roads, though, so nobody gets it into their head
to get in the way.''
   That shouldn't be too difficult since the affected section of
Nevada 318 through the mostly flat White River Valley crosses no
other highways. Irrigation fields and distant ranch houses are the
only signs of human life.
   The Nevada State Department of Transportation, the Nevada
Highway Patrol and the Nye, Lincoln and White Pine county
commissions all had to give permission for the race, with the
access guards as a condition, Ward said. The federal government
didn't become involved because it is a state highway.
   Drivers are to start out at one-minute intervals Sunday from
Lund, a tiny eastern Nevada farming town best known for producing
one or two high school graduates each year.
   The faster cars racing southward will arrive about 45 minutes
later at the finish line in Hiko, the Lincoln County seat in the
late 1860s but now reduced to a ghost town 100 miles north of Las
Vegas.
   ``I don't anticipate the cars running flat out, but some will
get up there, going 160, 170,'' Ward said. ``These cars are made
for speed.''
   The older vehicles will travel more sedately and arrive a little
later. The cars will compete in five categories so the older ones
are not outclassed.
   ``A lot of the drivers are people who just have an interest in
vintage cars,'' said Ted Roberts of Burbank, Calif. ``Others, with
the faster cars, can take them out and really drive them. This is
the ultimate high-speed run down a public highway. And it's legal.''
   Roberts, music supervisor for the ``Matlock'' television series,
planned to drive the 1968 Javelin he drove in the Trans-Am series
in 1969 and 1970.
   Ward, who is not driving Sunday, said he would like to make the
race an annual event. It is financed by entry fees from $100 to
$250 depending on the type of car.
</TEXT>
