<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0474,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Vows to `Stop Attack on Social Security'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 7 grafs new with Dukakis speech; picks up pvs 6th graf
bgng, Dukakis aides.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis chided Republican rival
George Bush today for once referring to Social Security as
``largely a welfare program,'' and promised never to use Social
Security trust funds to help balance the federal budget.
   ``You know, when election time rolls around, Mr. Bush likes to
say he is a great friend of older Americans,'' Dukakis told a
lunchtime crowd at a senior citizens center in Boston.
   ``Maybe he thinks we all have amnesia,'' the Democratic nominee
said. ``Because it was just over three years ago _ May 10, 1985 _
that George Bush cast the tie-breaking vote in the Senate to deny
you a cost-of-living increase in your Social Security and to make
you pay more for your medical benefits. And Dan Quayle voted with
him and against you.''
   If elected, Dukakis said, he and vice presidential running mate
Lloyd Bentsen would ``stop the attack on Social Security and
Medicare and we'll stop it cold.''
   Accompanied by his 85-year-old mother, Euterpe, and New York
Gov. Mario Cuomo, the Massachusetts governor said the National
Economic Commission studying ways to reduce the budget deficit
``won't get to first base'' in a Dukakis administration if it
recommends cuts in Social Security benefits.
   ``I am committed to maintaining full benefits and cost-of-living
increases,'' Dukakis said. ``No matter what the commission
recommends, as president I will ensure that the nation honors its
commitments so that current and future beneficiaries can count on
the promise of Social Security.''
   Dukakis took time out from preparations for his nationally
televised debate with Bush on Sunday at Winston-Salem, N.C., to
promise guaranteed health care for children and pregnant women, and
to accuse the vice president of ignoring the needs of poor families.
   Dukakis aides said Cuomo also may return to Boston on Friday,
when a campaign source said Dukakis is scheduled to take part in a
mock debate. Washington attorney Bob Barnett is standing in for
Bush, a role he played in 1984 when Geraldine Ferraro was preparing
for her debate with Bush.
   Dukakis spent much of Wednesday studying for the debate and has
rented a meeting room in a Boston hotel for practice sessions. New
Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley was in town to offer advice Wednesday and
is expected back Friday. Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton also is to
visit Dukakis in advance of the debate.
   Bradley also attended Dukakis' only public appearance, his visit
to Brigham & Women's Hospital to outline his ``Healthy Start''
program, which is modeled after a Massachusetts program that has
provided services to 16,000 mothers since 1985. Dukakis visited
with two of them before delivering his speech.
   ``Today, more than 12 million children in this country grow up
in families without a dime's worth of health insurance,'' Dukakis
said. ``Too many of these children don't get checkups. They aren't
treated when they are sick, and they've never seen a dentist.''
   Dukakis said the Healthy Start program would provide money to
states that adopt efforts similar to a Massachusetts program that
has been cited as a factor in the state's declining infant
mortality rate.
   It offers doctors' and hospital care to pregnant women who are
uninsured or underinsured and also provides basic coverage for
their babies. Aides said the federal program would cost $100
million in the first year but that the money would be saved within
12 months because the government would not have to pick up the tab
for more expensive treatment of preventable childhood illnesses.
   Dukakis contrasted his proposal with Bush's record, listing
programs affecting poor families that have been targeted for cuts
by the Reagan administration.
   ``He was there when his administration conducted an annual
assault on immunization programs,'' Dukakis said. ``He was there
when they cut maternal and child health programs.''
</TEXT>
