<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Dog     09-22 0154</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Dog,0158</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Dog Identification Rejected By Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ringo the police dog used his nose to sniff out
a robbery suspect in a lineup, but a judge rejected the
identification paws down, a court spokesman said Thursday.
   The German shepherd picked a suspect from a police lineup after
smelling a coat discovered in a jeep used as the getaway car from a
jewelry store robbery in Lod, a suburb of Tel Aviv.
   Gems worth about $50,000 were stolen in the robbery, the
national Itim news agency said.
   On Tuesday, Tel Aviv District Court Judge Arye Evenari threw
Ringo's identification out of court, ruling a dog's ``testimony''
could be used only to back up other evidence and could not stand
alone, the court spokesman said.
   Evenari also said a dog's identification had to be accompanied
by proof of the animal's qualifications, including its previous
experience in accurately identifying suspects, Itim said.
</TEXT>
