<DOCNO> AP880922-0101 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 1301EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Georgia     09-22 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Georgia,0611</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Break Up Protest In Southern Soviet City</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Unrest, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TBILISI, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of uniformed police manhandled a
group of Georgian nationalists Thursday when they tried to protest
near the site of a U.S.-Soviet citizens conference.
   Georgian activists said at least 15 demonstrators were detained
after police hauled them away from the Georgian Academy of Sciences
building on Rustaveli Street, the main thoroughfare of the capital
of the southern republic.
   Around the corner from the columned academy entrance, at the
Georgian Filmmakers Union building, representatives of both
superpowers were discussing environmental problems.
   Former New York Times Moscow correspondent Hedrick Smith and
former deputy chief of mission at the U.S. Embassy in Moscow,
Richard Combs, were among those who looked on as police dragged off
women demonstrators by the hair and pushed others into cars.
   Tbilisi, in the Caucasus Mountains about 1,000 miles south of
Moscow, is hosting a six-day program ending Saturday for nearly 300
U.S. officials, cultural figures, businessmen and citizens and
their Soviet counterparts.
   The fourth annual exchange is co-sponsored by the
state-sanctioned Soviet Friendship Society and the Chautauqua
Institution of upstate New York.
   Some Georgians used the conference's two-day debate on human
rights at the filmmakers building to urge their own government to
safeguard a historic monastery and the Georgian language.
   The demonstrators at the Georgian academy exceeded 100 and made
the same demands, including a call to scrap the Soviet army
artillery range they say is damaging a nearby cultural treasure,
the monastery of David Garija.
   Preserving the monastery, 50 miles outside Tbilisi, has become a
crusade for many Georgians who regard it as a symbol of the people
and their Christian religion.
   The unrest was part of widespread protests in the area. Troops
patrolled the streets of Yerevan, Armenia's capital, and
Stepanakert, the main city of the disputed Azerbaijan territory of
Nagorno-Karabakh. One man has died and 48 have been injured in
clashes between Armenians and Azerbaijanis, officials say.
   Before noon Thursday, uniformed police rushed the square in
front of the House of Film, forcing protesters to group instead on
the steps of the Academy of Science building.
   Zviad Gomsakhurdjia, one of the protest's organizers, accused
police of detaining well-known Georgian nationalists and human
rights activists at home so they could not take part.
   Most of the protesters sat in the afternoon sun at the academy's
entrance. Fights and scuffles broke out between protesters and
plainclothes officers who circulated in the crowd.
   One American witness said she saw a policeman take a shovel from
a nearby construction site and hurl it into the mass of protesters.
   Gomsakhurdjia said policemen trying to arrest him and others
ripped his coat to shreds.
   The protesters then moved to other sites in this city of more
than 1 million people, and their ranks grew.
   About 275 staged a sit-in on the steps of Tbilisi State
University, and as dusk fell, an estimated 750 were gathered
outside the offices of Georgia's Supreme Soviet, the nominal
parliament.
   Fourteen people who said they were arrested at the academy
showed up later at the university and told the crowd they were
released. They accused authorities of beating them.
   The crowd outside the university's main building sang the
Georgian national anthem and 19th century songs about their
homeland.
   No violence was reported at the Georgian Supreme Soviet or at
the university. At the university, 70 to 80 uniformed policemen
stood guard along with 25 officers from the regular armed forces,
or Interior Ministry troops.
</TEXT>
