<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     09-22 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Burn US, Japanese Effigies At Anti-Olympic Protest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,700 students chanted slogans
at an anti-Olympic rally Thursday and burned figures representing
the United States and Japan, which they charge are bolstering
authoritarian rule in South Korea.
   The students from 12 schools in Seoul demonstrated at Yonsei
University to demand that the Olympics in Seoul be shared with
communist North Korea. They also called for an end to the U.S.
military presence in South Korea.
   ``Oppose dictatorial Olympics,'' the students shouted.
   After the rally, the protesters marched to the school's main
gate, where they faced about 2,000 riot police blocking the way.
The students did not try to march out and there was no
confrontation.
   The protesters, chanting slogans and singing, marched around the
campus as speakers called for a struggle to drive out the 42,000
U.S. troops stationed in South Korea under a defense treaty.
   Protesters burned effigies of figures with U.S. and Japanese
flags painted on them. ``Yankee go home,'' students yelled.
   Huge placards hanging down the sides of school buildings read
``Oppose the Olympics, which perpetuate the national division'' and
``No war and no nuclear bombs.''
   Radical students condend that the ``half Olympics,'' boycotted
by North Korea, raises the risk of war on the Korean peninsula.
   Most of the demonstrations have been small and peaceful with
just a handful of students taking part. The great majority of South
Koreans want the Games to be a success and oppose the
demonstrations.
   Protesters denounced the United States and Japan for helping to
guard the Olympics from possible threats from North Korea. U.S.
forces in South Korea are on increased alert and U.S. and Japanese
naval forces are helping patrol the surrounding seas.
   North Korea is boycotting the Games because its demand to
co-host the Games was rejected. The International Olympic Committee
said the Olympics could not be shared because they are awarded to a
singl city.
</TEXT>
