<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     09-22 0873</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0910</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Jackie Mason went for broke Thursday
with some of New York City's power brokers in a breakfast-time
Monopoly game to benefit a homeless program.
   ``I just collected rent from people who've been robbing me all
my life,'' Mason joked as he took the play money from the likes of
developers Lewis Rudin and Leonard Stern, also chairman of The
Hartz Group Inc.
   The game was held at the Regency Hotel, birthplace of the
``power breakfast,'' to raise money for ``Homes for the Homeless,''
a non-profit organization providing families with temporary shelter.
   Loews Hotels President Jonathan M. Tisch said more than $10,000
was raised.
   Parker Brothers customized its game of wheeling and dealing for
the benefit, and said it was the first time real-life real estate
moguls faced each other across the board. The other players were
former Postmaster General Preston Robert Tisch, now president of
Loews Corp. financial company, and New York Times architecture
critic Paul Goldberger. The banker was the 1987 U.S. Monopoly
champion, Gary Peters.
   The 200 or so people who attended the $50-a-plate breakfast also
pledged real donations to the homeless program against the players'
phony earnings.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Far-out news on the creator of ``The Far
Side'' comic strip: ``They've stolen Gary Larson,'' says the
curator of astronomy at the Dayton Museum of Natural History, ``a
life-sized, enormous photo of Gary Larson.''
   Art Goss says the photo of the cartoonist, which belongs with an
exhibit at the museum of Larson's work, was taken this week.
   The photo ``was standing there in the glassed-in entryway of the
museum, and some college-age guys stole it,'' Goss says.
   The exhibit includes more than 400 framed enlargements of ``Far
Side'' cartoons.
   Despite the theft, Larson's image remains. Two other life-sized
photos show Larson sitting on the floor and leaning against an
exhibit.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country singer Johnny Paycheck, facing a
prison sentence for a barroom shooting, is donating his royalties
from a new gospel music album to fight AIDS in children, a
spokesman said Thursday.
   Billy D. Burns, executive producer of the album ``Outlaw at the
Cross,'' said Paycheck will give the money to a Los Angeles-based
agency that helps children with AIDS.
   The album, on Damascus to the Cross Records, will be available
next week. Paycheck's royalties amount to $1.10 per record sold,
Burns said.
   Paycheck faces up to 9{ years in prison in Ohio for his 1986
conviction for wounding a man at a tavern. He is free on bond while
the case is under appeal. He is best known for his 1978 hit ``Take
This Job and Shove It.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Crawford, who is leaving the hit
Broadway musical ``The Phantom of the Opera'' next month, says he
needs a rest after two years with the show.
   ``It's like being an athlete,'' he said on CBS's ``This
Morning'' in a program for broadcast Friday. ``You have to have a
rest period and then start up again. I mean I'm not finished with
the Phantom. I want to come back and do it again.''
   Crawford, who won a Tony Award for his portrayal of the Phantom,
says the lavish musical has been an emotional experience.
   ``I cry every night. I cry every single night in the show. It
makes me weep at the end. ... Because I'm no longer performing for
the audience and so I just turn around and, for myself, I cry for
him, because he's a wonderful character,'' he said.
   His last show is Oct. 8. Opera singer Timothy Nolen replaces
Crawford.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Mets left-hander Bob Ojeda won't be on
the mound at least until spring training after severing part of the
middle finger of his pitching hand with an electric hedge clipper,
doctors say.
   The Mets said Ojeda underwent five hours of successful
microsurgery Wednesday at Roosevelt Hospital. Doctors said the tip
of the finger was reattached, but recovery is expected to take four
to six months.
   The accident Wednesday at Ojeda's Long Island home nearly
severed the finger at the joint after the clippers slipped.
   ``It is a blow,'' Mets general manager Frank Cashen said. Hours
after the accident, the team clinched at least a tie in the
National League's East Division.
   Ojeda, 30, who missed most of last season after elbow surgery,
was 10-13 for the Mets this season with a 2.88 earned run average.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Anne Murray says she will perform
at a concert and hold a reception on behalf of a group that lobbies
for songwriters' legal rights.
   ``I guess it's pretty obvious how grateful we are to writers,''
Ms. Murray said Wednesday as she announced the Nov. 16 concert for
the Nashville Songwriters Association International. ``Without
them, I wouldn't be here.''
   Association President Bob DiPiero said the showcase will be an
exhibit to educate the public about the contributions of
songwriters to the entertainment industry.
   Ms. Murray noted the long list of hits she has had from the pens
of Nashville songwriters. Those numbers include ``A Little Good
News,'' ``Could I Have This Dance,'' and ``Hey Baby.''
</TEXT>
