<DOCNO> AP880922-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 1350EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-DebateExperts     09-22 0647</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Debate Experts,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Debate Coaches Unimpressed by Dukakis, Bush Debating Abilities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Debate experts say that neither George Bush
nor Michael Dukakis is any great shakes as a public speaker, and
the winner of their first face-to-face showdown Sunday night may be
whoever exceeds low expectations.
   Veteran forensic judges also agree that the candidates will try
their utmost to observe the cardinal rule of presidential debates:
avoid calamitous mistakes.
   That may be good politics, but it can make for dull debating,
said members of the Associated Press presidential debate judges
panel.
   James J. Unger, executive director of the National Forensics
Institute at American University in Washington, D.C., and chairman
of the judges' panel, said these high-stakes debates ``are
exercises in error-avoidance by the candidates.''
   Unger, who also chaired AP panels that judged the presidential
debates in 1976, 1980 and 1984, said it is rare for a candidate to
make a major gaffe like Gerald Ford's in 1976 when he insisted that
Eastern Europe was not dominated by the Soviet Union.
   All too often, he added, ``the candidates just sit there with
their prepared answers desperately seeking out a question to which
they can attach the answer.''
   William Southworth, director of forensics and speech professor
at the University of Redlands in California, said, ``I'm not
convinced either one of them is going to be dynamic confronting
each other. ... A lot will depend on how willing they are to take
risks.''
   Frank Sferra, debate coach at J.K. Mullen High School in Denver
and president of the National Forensic League, said, ``Neither one
is a terribly exciting speaker.''
   ``I get the feeling they're too programmed to be debaters. You
bring up an issue and they know where they're supposed to run and
what to say,'' said Sferra. ``They're all so afraid they're going
to say something wrong.''
   Dukakis engaged in 21 debates during the primaries with his
rivals for the Democratic nomination, and he once moderated a
public television debate series called ``The Advocates.''
   Bush faced off with his Republican rivals seven times. He also
has a 1984 vice presidential debate with Democrat Geraldine Ferraro
under his belt _ the one about which he boasted afterwards that he
``tried to kick a little ass.''
   Melissa Maxey Wade, director of forensics at Emory University in
Atlanta, said that in the primary debates, ``Bush demonstrated more
range, positive and negative. He had very strong, persuasive
responses when he was being attacked by (Al) Haig and (Jack) Kemp
in the early debates.''
   Dukakis was ``real consistent. He doesn't seem to make major
goofs. He doesn't have big highs or big lows,'' she said.
   Lanny D. Naegelin, a speech-theater arts specialist for the
North East Independent School District in San Antonio, Texas, said
both Bush and Dukakis lack ``pizzazz'' as speakers, but ``Dukakis
is easier when he talks than Bush. It's more obvious when Bush
speaks that he's working at what he's doing.''
   James M. Copeland, national executive secretary of the National
Forensic League, Ripon, Wis., said Dukakis ``has great debate
skills, but he tends to be very monotone and flat in his
presentation.'' He said Bush ``is a very strained speaker. His
voice tends to get a little screechy when he's excited.''
   Sherry Hall, debate coach at Harvard University in Cambridge,
Mass., said that in collegiate debates, content wins more points
than style. But in these presidential debates, ``the emphasis is
much more on style,'' she said.
   ``That's what people remember. With (President) Reagan four
years ago, people remember how he looked, not what he said,'' she
said.
   The seven-member panel will use a scorecard similar to that
employed in collegiate and scholastic debates to determine a winner
of the Sept. 25 Bush-Dukakis debate. It will also evaluate their
second debate on Oct. 13 or 14, and their running mates' Oct. 5
encounter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880922-0106 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 1302EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Iran-Mines     09-22 0681</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Mines,0703</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Says It Is Clearing Mines From Persian Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Iranian navy began mine-clearing
operations in the Persian Gulf on Thursday, Iran's official news
agency reported as Iran marked the eighth anniversary of Iraq's
invasion.
   The Islamic Republic news Agency, monitored in Nicosia, quoted
the unidentified commander of Iran's naval mine sweepers as saying
that helicopters and frogmen also were involved in the
mine-clearing.
   The Iranian navy can defuse magnetic, contact and other types of
mines, the officer was quoted as saying.
   He said the operations underlined ``the Islamic Republic's
commitment to maintaining security and guaranteeing the safety of
shipping in the region.''
   The report could not be confirmed independently.
   A United Nations-sponsored cease-fire in the Iran-Iraq war began
Aug. 20.
   When Iran's naval commander, Rear Adm. Mohammad-Hussein
Malekzadegan, announced last week that his forces would begin
mine-clearing operations, a U.S. official said that was
``tantamount to admitting that they laid the mines'' during the
8-year-old war.
   Iran has never admitted it laid mines in the waterway's shipping
lane, but said it did so in its coastal waters for defense. But
Tehran boasted last year that it could sow mines ``like seeds'' in
the gulf.
   The U.S. Navy captured the Iran Ajr, an Iranian naval vessel, in
the gulf a year ago while it was allegedly laying mines at night.
Several mines were found aboard the ship and others it had laid
were found nearby.
   IRNA gave no other details on the mine-clearing or specify where
it was being carried out. The naval officer said only that the
operation was being conducted in ``international waters'' in the
600-mile-long gulf.
   The U.S. and other Western navies that sent forces to the gulf
to protect neutral shipping have found dozens of mines, mainly in
the northern and central sectors of the waterway, since July 1987.
   IRNA said Iranian ships detected and destroyed four mines last
year in the Gulf of Oman off the United Arab Emirates port of Khor
Fakkan. Western naval officials believe the Iranians had planted
the mines in the first place.
   At least eight ships, including the reflagged Kuwaiti tanker
Bridgeton and the U.S. missile frigate Samuel B. Roberts, have been
sunk or damaged by mines in the last 16 months. Western officials
said all were apparently laid by the Iranians.
   U.S. Navy officers estimate that as many as 200 mines, mainly
contact-type devices moored to the seabed, are still in the gulf.
Most are believed to be in shallow waters of the Iraqi coast in the
northern end of the gulf.
   Iraq is believed to have laid some, but most are believed to be
Iranian.
   Iran's navy had four coastal and two inshore mine sweepers when
the war broke out in September 1980, along with a squadron of six
U.S.-built RH-53D mine helicopters.
   Western analysts believe that only two of the Iranian mine
sweepers remain operational, while the two surviving RH-53D
helicopters are no longer able to function as mine sweepers.
   In Tehran, ``Sacred Defense Week,'' organized to mark the eighth
anniversary of the war, opened with a military parade in Azadi
Square, IRNA reported.
   The Iranians and most military historians say the war began when
the Iraqi army stormed across the border Sept. 22, 1980. Iraq says
the conflict began Sept. 4, when the Iranians shelled border towns
after weeks of skirmishing.
   Iran's President, Ali Khamenei, reviewed the parade and
declared, ``Although we have no practical war at the fronts ... yet
we do not feel the enemy's threat any less than before,'' IRNA said.
   He called on Iran's forces to remain on alert because ``the
enemy intends to again plot against this nation and the Islamic
Revolution.''
   He charged that the Iraqis were massing troops along the border
and warned Baghdad against ``renewed aggression.''
   IRNA, in a separate commentary, termed Sept. 22, 1980, ``the
blackest day in contemporary history ... the day the army of
pagandom launched a war against Islam ... the day the hordes of
ignorance charged against the citadel of wisdom.''
</TEXT>
