<HEAD>Reagan Undergoes Medical Exam Before Meeting Astronauts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WACO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan was pronounced disease-free
today after undergoing a second medical examination before meeting
the Discovery space shuttle astronauts at the Johnson Space Center
in Houston.
   ``I'm fine,'' Reagan called out to reporters as he left Air
Force One en route to a speaking engagement at Baylor University
before visiting the astronauts.
   As if to dramatize the opinion of the White House physician, Dr.
Lawrence C. Mohr, that he is free of disease, the president danced
a little jig before entering his armored limousine.
   Spokesman Marlin Fitzwater told reporters during the flight to
Waco that Reagan was examined first on Tuesday as a precaution for
his meeting with the astronauts, who are under a modified
quarantine before their scheduled Sept. 29 launch.
   ``The main thing is to check for a cold or a virus that can be
easily transmitted,'' Fitzwater said.
   He said Reagan's senior aides and Secret Service detail were
required to complete medical data forms before they were cleared to
enter the space center with the president. Only Reagan will have
direct contact with the five astronauts.
   ``We're all clean,'' Fitzwater quipped about the presidential
staff.
