<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Tredici     09-22 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Tredici,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NY Philharmonic Names Composer In Residence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Del Tredici, composer of ``Final Alice''
and winner of the 1980 Pulitzer Prize for his ``In Memory of a
Summer Day,'' has been named composer in residence of the New York
Philharmonic.
   Del Tredici's two-year appointment begins with this season. His
activities will include writing a work to be premiered next season,
reviewing scores for possible performance, advising on programming
and formulating plans for a new music series.
   The composer's ``Tattoo'' will be performed in November, with
Leonard Bernstein conducting the New York Philharmonic. He also
will write a work for the 150th birthday of the New York
Philharmonic in 1992, a commission shared with the Royal
Philharmonic of London. Del Tredici, 51, is a native of Cloverdale,
Calif.
   The appointment is part of the Meet the Composer Orchestra
Residencies Program. Other composers joining the residencies
program this year are Robert Beaser, American Composers Orchestra;
Donald Erb, St. Louis Symphony; Stephen Paulus, Atlanta Symphony,
and Steven Stucky, Los Angeles Philharmonic.
