<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Diplomats     09-22 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Diplomats,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain Orders Czechoslovak Diplomats Expelled For Spying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain accused three Czechoslovak diplomats
Thursday of spying and ordered them to leave the country within two
weeks.
   A Foreign Office announcement said the three envoys, including
two military attaches, ``engaged in activities incompatible with
their status'' _ diplomatic parlance for espionage.
   The diplomats are Maj. Bedrich Kramar, the assistant military
and air attache; Maj. Vlastmil Netolicky, a member of the military
attache's staff, and Paval Moudry, a member of the commercial
section.
   The expulsions prompted speculation the envoys were linked with
a London-based art dealer, Erwin van Haarlem, who says he is
Czechoslovakian and who is awaiting trial on charges of preparing
to set up a spy ring.
   Britain also has complained this year about supplies of
Czechoslovak-made explosives reaching the outlawed Irish Republican
Army, which is waging a bombing and shooting campaign to drive the
British from Northern Ireland.
   The Foreign Office refused to elaborate on its terse
announcement. At the Czechoslovak Embassy, a telephone receptionist
told reporters after the 12:45 p.m. announcement that the embassy
was closed for lunch and said later it was closed for the day.
   In Prague, Czechoslovak Foreign Ministry spokesman Dusan
Rovensky said he had no comment.
   Czechoslovak Ambassador Jan Fidler was summoned to the Foreign
Office on Thursday morning and given the expulsion order.
   ``The Foreign Secretary (Sir Geoffrey Howe) wishes it to be
clearly understood that, while we wish to build up our relations
with Czechoslovakia, we are not prepared to relax our policy on the
sort of activities in which Maj. Kramar, Maj. Netolicky and Mr.
Moudry have engaged,'' the statement said.
   Kramar and Moudry have been in Britain since 1984, and Netolicky
arrived in September 1985, the Foreign Office said.
   They brought to seven the number of Czechoslovak diplomats
Britain has expelled since 1983, usually amid speculation the
envoys were suspected of spying on behalf of the Soviet Union.
   ``There are certain instances, for example, where the KGB (the
Soviet secret police) or the GRU (Soviet military intelligence) has
not wanted to get directly involved and has used Czech intelligence
to do so,'' Christopher Lee, a defense analyst at Emmanuel College,
Cambridge, said in a radio interview Thursday.
   Van Haarlem, who has a Dutch passport, was arrested last April
at his London apartment. Police burst in and said they caught him
using radio equipment to transmit signals ``to a foreign power.''
   He has been indicted for trial at London's Old Bailey Central
Criminal Court. No date has been set.
   Britain last expelled Soviet diplomats in September 1985. A
total of 31 Soviets and 31 Britons, including businessmen and
journalists, were ordered out of London and Moscow in a series of
retaliatory expulsions.
   Britain has expelled four other diplomats in the past month: a
Tunisian who refused to pay hundreds of dollars of parking fines, a
Vietnamese who brandished a gun at demonstrators, a Cuban who fired
a gun in a street, and the Cuban ambassador.
</TEXT>
