<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NaomiCloud     09-22 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Naomi Cloud,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Pleads Guilty Eight Years Later</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAYETTEVILLE, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman accused of seducing her lover
into killing her husband has been sentenced to five to 18 years in
prison after the long-time fugitive pleaded guilty to second-degree
murder.
   Naomi Cloud, 45, entered her plea Wednesday in the 1980 shooting
death of her husband, 54-year-old David Cloud, who was shot outside
their Princeton home when the couple returned from a party.
   She had been charged with first-degree murder and faced a
possible life sentence.
   Fayette County Circuit Judge J. Zane Summerfield said Mrs. Cloud
did not confess during her court appearance.
   ``She simply insisted on her constitutional right to enter a
guilty plea rather than run the risk of a jury trial and conviction
on a charge of first-degree murder,'' Summerfield said.
   Her trial had been scheduled to start Monday. The trial had been
moved to Fayette County from Mercer County because of pretrial
publicity.
   Authorities allege Mrs. Cloud lured her boyfriend at the time,
John Elmer Corprew Jr. of Roanoke, Va., into the plot to kill her
husband, and Corprew in turn paid George Guthrie II of Roanoke
$2,500 to be the triggerman.
   Corprew pleaded guilty to a charge that he arranged the killing,
and Guthrie twice was convicted of being the triggerman.
   Prosecutors portrayed Mrs. Cloud as a temptress. Corprew
testified he was Mrs. Cloud's lover and that she was ``a spider and
I was caught in her web. I couldn't get out.''
   Mrs. Cloud jumped bail and fled the state in 1982 just before
she was to stand trial. She was recaptured April 21 in Kennewick,
Wash., after authorities received a tip. She has been held in the
Fayette County Jail without bond since her return to West Virginia.
   Mrs. Cloud contended that her husband was murdered by a masked
assailant who emerged from the darkness outside their home and
demanded money, then fired one shotgun blast.
   Mercer County Prosecutor David Knight questioned why the man
hadn't robbed the house while the Clouds were at the dinner party,
why Mrs. Cloud's life was spared, and why the assailant took no
valuables.
   Corprew was sentenced to five years in prison after pleading
guilty to voluntary manslaughter. Guthrie is serving a life
sentence for first-degree murder.
</TEXT>
