<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BU-Chelsea     09-22 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BU-Chelsea,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BU Changes Some Plans to Help Chelsea Schools</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boston University has backed down in its quest for
near-total control over Chelsea's schools by agreeing to let the
city's School Committee retain some power.
   BU's decision to modify its proposal for a contract to manage
the troubled 3,300-student Chelsea system came after failing to win
a 10-year management pact this summer.
   The university agreed Wednesday night that committee members
could override any of their management decisions by a two-thirds
majority.
   ``This is our best shot,'' said Peter R. Greer, dean of BU's
School of Education.
   But some School Committee members were still reluctant to enter
into a contract with the university. Some felt rushed by the
university's push for a vote.
   ``You expect us to do all this in a week?'' committee member
Elizabeth McBride said after hearing the proposal. ``I think it's a
little much.''
   Chelsea, which is near bankruptcy, has had problems running its
schools efficiently. It also has had trouble raising the average of
students' standardized test scores, which are lower than the state
average.
   Under BU's latest proposal, the university would take over all
aspects of the school system, including negotiating union
contracts, hiring, setting curriculum and developing educational
policy.
   It allows parents and community leaders to serve on two advisory
boards established to aid university representatives, but the
primary governing body would be a BU-controlled board.
   BU and the committee would have the right to terminate the
contract.
   If the committee agrees to the BU proposal, it must be approved
by the city's Board of Aldermen and the state Legislature.
</TEXT>
