<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Refugee'sDeath     09-22 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Refugee's Death,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Refugee Dies of Liver Cancer After Reunion With Family</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DILLON, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Vietnamese refugee who battled liver
cancer for nine months got his last wish to see his family emigrate
safely from Vietnam before he died.
   Ton Anh Huynh, 25, had clung to life, hoping for a reunion with
the family he had left behind when he fled Vietnam with his father
and brother in 1979.
   He died Wednesday at the Summit Medical Center in Frisco, just a
week after his mother, two other brothers and two sisters arrived
in Dillon from Vietnam.
   ``I think he kind of held on until the family came. That was
all,'' said Long Anh Huynh, the brother who left Vietnam with
Huynh. ``He was really ill and was getting weaker every day.''
   ``He was very happy and he was still pretty good. He could still
talk and was very happy,'' Long Anh Huynh said.
   Huynh's mother had not been told of her son's illness until she
arrived in Denver. She ``was very upset, but I told her there's not
much we can do,'' Long Anh Huynh said.
   The family spent a ``very good week'' together in the house that
Ton's father bought just two weeks ago, he said.
   Long Anh Huynh said that when his brother's condition worsened
Tuesday night, the family took him to Summit Medical Center.
   Huynh's illness had spurred a long effort by a French
restaurateur in Dillon, Jean Pierre Tournier, to reunite his family.
   Tournier had sponsored Huynh and his father as U.S. citizens,
gave them a place to live and taught them the restaurant business.
By the time Tournier returned to Paris last June, the Vietnamese
government had approved the Huynhs' emigration but set no date for
it.
</TEXT>
