<DOCNO> AP880922-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 1404EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Reagan 2ndLd-Writethru a0533 09-22 0909</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0533,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Blasts Democratic `Born-Again George Pattons' on Defense</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 5 grafs new with color, new Reagan quote; picks up pvs
4th graf bgng, Reagan was stumping; SUBS pvs 6th graf bgng, ``But
lately,'' to read ``Gen. George Pattons'' as delivered.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WACO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan hit the campaign trail for
George Bush today with ridicule for ``born-again Gen. George
Pattons'' in the Democratic Party who say they support a strong
national defense.
   Without mentioning the name of Democratic candidate Michael
Dukakis, the president told a Republican ``Texas Victory '88''
rally that liberal Democrats have had ``a deathbed conversion'' to
GOP positions supporting the submarine-based Trident missile and
the Stealth bomber.
   Reagan was interrupted repeatedly by deafening screams and
applause from about 9,000 Baylor University students who hissed at
the president's frequent mention of liberal Democrats. Signs on the
wall read ``Rock `Em Ron'' and ``Push For Bush.''
   ``When the liberals say `family,' they mean `big brother in
Washington.' When we say `family' we mean `honor thy father and
mother','' Reagan said. The crowd went wild.
   Reagan declared that under his and the vice president's
leadership, ``our nation is again respected in the world, our armed
forces are strong and America is at peace.''
   Reagan was stumping for Bush and Rep. Beau Boulter, R-Texas, who
is seeking the Senate seat of Democratic vice presidential
candidate Lloyd Bentsen, before joining the vice president at
fund-raising dinner in Houston tonight.
   Reagan said he recently vetoed a $299.5 billion defense
authorization bill because he was convinced it would have harmed
U.S. military strength. He then invoked the name of Gen. George
Patton, a crusty and venerable World War II combat hero, in
lambasting the Democratic ticket.
   ``But lately, some liberal leaders have seen what was happening
to them in the polls and had a deathbed conversion,'' he said.
``They'd have you believe that they're born-again Gen. George
Pattons. But if we go the way they want to go, our defenses will
run out of gas in no time.''
   Bush has charged repeatedly that his Democratic rival, the
governor of Massachusetts, was soft on defense issues and would
weaken the national security. Dukakis has said he opposes the
rail-based MX missile and has voiced concerns about how far the
United States should go in deploying B-1 bombers.
   But in an effort to deflect the vice president's criticism,
Dukakis donned a military helmet and took a ride in an M-1 battle
tank last week at a defense contractor's plant in Michigan to
underscore his argument that he believes in a strong military.
   The president said that when Democratic liberals talk of
supporting new weapons systems, ``they whisper that they're also
for delaying deployment of both systems (the Trident and the
Stealth bomber) pending the outcome of arms talks, which could drag
on for years, while the Soviets could be deploying new systems of
their own.''
   Said Reagan: ``They shout loudly that the're for maintaining the
effectiveness of the land-based leg of our strategic (missile)
triad. But they're against the modern missile systems that will be
available for years to come and would like to see an end to the
flight testing needed to develop new systems.''
   On Wednesday, Reagan offered Bush some advice on the vice
president's first nationally televised debate with Dukakis on
Sunday in Winston-Salem, N.C.
   The president told reporters he advised Bush to ``take no
prisoners'' in the face-off at Wake Forest University.
   During today's trip, Reagan also planned to visit the Johnson
Space Center in Houston, where he was to meet with the five
Discovery space shuttle astronauts who are preparing for a Sept. 29
launch.
   His joint appearance with Bush is their second since the vice
president won the GOP presidential nomination in mid-August. Texas,
with its 29 electoral votes and status as Bentsen's home state, is
a pivotal campaign battleground for Bush and Dukakis.
   After Dukakis tapped Bentsen as his running mate, the senator
was allowed to remain on the Texas ballot in his bid for a fourth
Senate term under the so-called ``Lyndon Law,'' which was passed to
allow Lyndon B. Johnson to run simultaneously for re-election to
the Senate and for the vice presidency with John F. Kennedy in 1960.
   Reagan's last visit to the space center was a grim one, coming
only days after the disastrous explosion of the Challenger space
shuttle on Jan. 28, 1986. The Challenger's seven crew members
perished when their spacecraft erupted in a giant fireball only 73
seconds after liftoff.
   At the time, Reagan mourned the loss of ``our seven star
voyagers'' and pledged that America would forge ahead with an
effective and safe space program.
   The president also said Wednesday that he supported Bush's
criticism of Dukakis for vetoing a 1977 bill in Massachusetts that
would have required public school teachers to lead students in
reciting the Pledge of Allegiance. Dukakis has cited an advisory
opinion of the state Supreme Court that the bill was
unconstitutional.
   ``I've seen many children today who don't know what they're
supposed to do when the national anthem is played or when the flag
goes by,'' Reagan told reporters. ``I remember that I learned all
that in school. Why shouldn't they?''
   The president was asked whether teachers should be forced to
lead students in the pledge.
   ``That's what they're there for,'' he shot back. ``Their job is
to teach something.''
</TEXT>
