<1ST_LINE>r p AM-LouisianaCongressional 1stLd-Writethru a0601 09-22 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Louisiana Congressional, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0601,0665</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governor's Mother Challenging Incumbent For Son's Former Seat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 13th graf, ``Mrs. McCrery,'' to CORRECT ``Mrs. McCrery''
to ``Mrs. Roemer.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Jim McCrery got the backing of
Gov. Buddy Roemer when he ran for Roemer's former congressional
seat, but now that he's seeking re-election his major opponent is
Roemer's mother.
   Adeline Roemer says she entered the race because she's
disappointed with the incumbent's brief performance in Congress.
   McCrery, a Republican who formerly worked as a top aide to
Roemer when Roemer was congressman, called the challenge in the
Oct. 1 open primary ``quite awkward and quite uncomfortable,'' but
said he's confident of winning his first full two-year term.
   McCrery won a runoff in April to fill the rest of Roemer's
unexpired term. Roemer, a Democrat who was elected four times to
the 4th District seat, took office as governor on March 15.
   ``I voted for Jim McCrery in the runoff,'' said Mrs. Roemer, 64,
a Democrat.
   ``While I felt there were two good people in the runoff, I felt
I knew Jim better. ... I thought he would vote across party lines
in the best interests of the people of the district. I do not feel
that has been the case,'' she said.
   A third primary candidate, Robert Briggs, has only a small
political base. If neither Mrs. Roemer nor McCrery wins a majority
the two top vote-getters will be forced into a runoff.
   Name recognition in Mrs. Roemer's favor hasn't hurt his
campaign, McCrery said.
   ``I have lost a few of the Roemer people who voted for me last
time because of their allegiance to Buddy and his mother. But they
are few in number,'' he said.
   Mrs. Roemer, who described herself as a lifelong political
activist most concerned with persuading qualified people to run for
office, said McCrery cast a couple of votes ``that put up little
red flags'' _ including opposition to a 60-day notification for
plant closings and a catastrophic health care bill.
   ``I felt like he has cast a straight party line vote even when
it hurt his district and it would not have hurt his standing in the
Republican Party for him to have voted differently,'' she said.
   The incumbent said he voted against the plant closing provision
because it could have pushed small businesses into bankruptcy and
would have discouraged expansion. He said the health care bill
``was not in the best interest of the district.''
   Mrs. Roemer said she decided to enter the race because no strong
candidate was emerging to challenge McCrery. ``I walked down the
levee and through the cotton fields and decided I would run.''
   It certainly wasn't the governor's idea, she said.
   ``When I called him up on that Saturday morning and told him I
planned to run for Congress and asked him if that would cause him
any problems, there was dead silence,'' she said. ``When he came
back on, he said `Mom, are you serious?'''
   Roemer and his wife, Patti, recently appeared at a $1,000 per
couple fund-raiser for his mother. Last spring, the governor drew
the ire of state Democrats when he supported McCrery.
   McCrery, whose campaign raised about $80,000 with a fundraiser
featuring retired Marine Lt. Col. Oliver North, a major figure in
the Iran-Contra controversy, said he has done in Congress exactly
what he promised to do.
   ``No. 1 is what is in the best interest of the United States.
No. 2 is what is in the best interest of the district. I said that
during the last campaign,'' he said.
   McCrery, 38, said he hopes the race will not have negative
effects on the district.
   ``I have supported Buddy Roemer for a number of years and hope
to continue to support his efforts to turn around the economy of
Louisiana,'' he said.
</TEXT>
