<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SovietDefector     09-22 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Defector,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moscow Opera Conductor Tells Reasons for Defecting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A conductor of Moscow's Bolshoi Opera said
Thursday he defected to America because his outspoken doubts about
Soviet politics made him a second-class citizen and hampered his
work in his own country.
   ``While we were trying to build one type of society in the
Soviet Union, we were in fact building one very different, one in
which it was very difficult to live and in which there was little
hope for the future,'' said Ruben Z. Vartanyan, who sought asylum
at the U.S. embassy in Bolivia last week while visiting that nation.
   ``I am an outspoken person,'' Vartanyan told a Washington news
conference. ``I could not disguise my feelings,'' Vartanyan said,
and he believes that ``informers reported back to the authorities.''
   Vartanyan said he first experienced trouble on his return to
Moscow in 1976 after a stay of nearly six years in Bolivia, where
he was the principal conductor of the National Symphonic Orchestra
in La Paz.
   Although he was never charged or openly accused of disloyalty to
the Soviet Union, he was unable to find a permanent post for four
years after his return.
   The situation improved slightly after he wrote a letter to
Leonid I. Brezhnev, who was then the Soviet president, and from
1980 until his defection Vartanyan was one of several conductors at
the Bolshoi Opera in Moscow, conducting more that 500 performances.
   Vartanyan met last week with Mstislav Rostropovich, another
Soviet defector, who is now director of the National Symphony in
Washington. The two were acquainted years ago in the Soviet Union,
when Vartanyan was principal conductor of the Armenian State
Symphony in Yerevan.
   Rostropovich was unfamiliar with Vartanyan's work and had no
comment on the defection, said a spokeswoman for Rostropovich.
   ``They had been very much out of touch and Mr. Rostropovich did
not know that Mr. Vartanyan was conducting at the Bolshoi. He did,
however, recognize his face,'' said the spokeswoman, Nadya Efremov.
   Vartanyan, whose defection was disclosed Wednesday, has not
received any invitations to work in the United States, but told
reporters: ``I am an optimist.''
   The Soviet conductor said that he had great respect for Kremlin
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev and his attempts to reform Soviet
society. Although there have been improvements in literature, film
and theater, ``in music, things are the opposite,'' said Vartanyan.
   ``The political leadership is not as interested in music as they
are in literature and film,'' he said.
   The world of Soviet music is run by ``the same people in the
ministries and the (Communist Party) Central Committee who have sat
there for the past 20 years. It is impossible for them to change,''
he said.
   The Bolshoi Theater, which includes an opera and a ballet
company, remains a political fiefdom where the level of artistic
discussion ``can be compared to any graveyard in Moscow,'' and the
director fires those who disagree with him, he said.
   ``I do not consider myself a traitor or a defector,'' he said.
But ``I felt I was under suspicion and did not have the confidence
of the people who ran the musical world. They did not have
confidence in my political views.''
   Because of that, he said, he was considered ``a second class
citizen'' and ``a member of the lowest category'' of society.
   Vartanyan said that his only close relative in the Soviet Union
was a sister. His wife died two years ago, they had no children,
and his parents are deceased, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
