<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 1420EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Yellowstone-HamiltonStores Bjt   09-22 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yellowstone-Hamilton Stores, Bjt,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fires Leave Yellowstone Concessionaire Stocked with Tourist Items</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAD BARTIMUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST YELLOWSTONE, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Terry Povah is up to his
warehouse ceiling in sweatshirts, coffee mugs, fishing tackle and
thousands of other items normally carted home by tourists during a
typical Yellowstone summer.
   But the summer of '88 was far from typical in the country's
first national park.
   Forest fires that raged over half of Yellowstone National Park's
2.2 million acres meant evacuation and early closure of many
facilities. It also meant the hasty exit of thousands of visitors
who ordinarily would crowd the aisles of Povah's 15 retail stores
past Labor Day.
   ``Will I have to re-order inventory for next year? God, I hope
not!'' said Povah, 43, president of his family's Hamilton Stores
Inc., the oldest concessioner under the jurisdiction of the
National Park Service.
   ``First we had the Great Depression, then World War II, then the
'59 earthquake, then the Arab oil embargo, then the '76 Teton Dam
disaster, and now the fires. There are always hurdles in the road.
This is just another one. I try to be philosophical.
   ``Wanna buy a T-shirt cheap?''
   Povah's quip is typical of the kind of humor he says has helped
his family cope with Mother Nature and Washington bureaucrats
during the nearly three quarters of a century Hamilton Stores has
been in Yellowstone.
   ``We basically fly with one eye open anyway,'' said Povah.
``Who's to say in August of '88 that we won't have a gas shortage
in July of '89 and the tourists won't come anyway? The company
philosophy is conservative. That means we have a 72-year history of
annual crapshoots.''
   Povah's grandfather, Charles Ashworth Hamilton, arrived in
Montana by train in 1905 from St. Paul, Minn., and went to work for
the Yellowstone Park Association, which then ran the commissary.
   Through three generations of its owners' grit, hunches, neck
protrusion and luck, Hamilton Stores, which formally began in 1915
when its founder bought out a retiring storekeeper at Old Faithful,
has grown into a multimillion-dollar operation.
   Today Hamilton Stores concessions are scattered throughout the
park. They include service stations, snack bars, grocery and
general merchandise stores, and camera shops. They also provide 12
dormitories for their 800 summer employees.
   Povah says his family will remember this year for a long time.
   ``It was wild,'' he said, shaking his head. ``In May and June we
were doing a tremendous business, so in July we heavily re-ordered.
Then the fires came.
   ``We didn't lose any facilities but we had smoke-damaged
merchandise and a helluva lot of inconvenience.''
   He even spent a few days helping fight fires with his company's
two fire trucks.
   ``There'd be a power outage and we'd be running around trying to
save ice cream. Then Old Faithful was threatened and we were
shuffling all the merchandise around,'' Povah said.
   Povah recalled the night he and his three children, headed home
to West Yellowstone from the park, got cut off and had to wait it
out while hundreds of firefighters fought one of the biggest blazes.
   ``The kids were saying `Uh, Dad, I think you should turn around'
and I looked to see flames everywhere,'' said Povah. ``I tried to
say `No problem' but I was a little worried.''
   So how's Povah going to relax after such a stressful summer?
   ``I'm going to take a bus from Tibet to Nepal over
18,000-foot-high mountain passes,'' he said. ``That should prepare
me for next summer in Yellowstone.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880922-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 1426EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-SchoolShooting 5thLd-Writethru a0632 09-22 0667</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School Shooting, 5th Ld - Writethru, a0632,0684</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Killed, At Least 2 Wounded In Shooting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with hospital reporting second
wounded person; no evidence of second gunman; social workers sent
to school, other detail. Picks up 8th graf pvs, `The second...'.
SUBS last graf with 4 grafs with names of some victims, other
detail. Will be led after police briefing, set to begin shortly.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A shooting that began in an auto parts store and
ended at a school nearby left five dead today and at least two
wounded, authorities said.
   A woman police officer, two employees of the store and a school
janitor died, and the gunman also was killed, said fire department
spokesman Tom Sheppard.
   ``We had a shootout,'' said Thelma Catto, a payroll clerk at the
Montefiore School. ``Right now, my office is a pool of blood.''
   Officials said the shooting was not school-related, though the
West Side school is a special one for troubled boys. It is about a
half-block from the store.
   Scott LaGreca, a spokesman for the Chicago fire department, said
the incident began with an attempted holdup at the store and the
gunman was chased into the school.
   But police said later that robbery was not the motive. ``It
appears to be somebody who has a grudge,'' said police Commander
James Maurer.
   Classes at the school, which has an enrollment of about 135,
were in session at the time of the shooting but no students or
teachers were injured, said school Superintendent Manford Byrd.
Social workers were sent to the school to help students cope with
the incident.
   Detective Riccardo Abreu said there was no evidence that anyone
was involved in the incident except for the gunman who died.
   In addition to the five dead, a second police officer was
injured, said deputy chief John Walsh of the Chicago Police
Department. And a hospital reported treating a man whose occupation
was not immediately determined.
   The second police officer was shot in both legs, Sheppard said.
A spokesman for Mount Sinai Hospital said the officer was in
serious but stable condition at the hospital.
   The shooting began at the Comet Auto Parts store, witnesses and
officials said.
   ``Shots apparently happened outside the school,'' said Chicago
School Board spokesman Bob Saigh. ``I understand the individual was
pursued into the building and more shots were fired.
   ``It is not school-related,'' Saigh said.
   Ms. Catto said she heard shots and ducked under her desk. One
school employee, whom she would only describe as a custodian, was
shot and came into her office.
   ``I hid in the storeroom,'' she said.
   A man who lives near the school, Kenny McBroom, 26, said he
witnessed much of the incident trough the window of his home.
   ``After the shots had been fired, I went to the window,''
McBroom said. ``I saw one cop laying down. He was shot but not
dead.''
   Other police officers arrived and ``came out with one policeman
who had been shot in the head and another one with bloodstains on
his chest. They were not moving,'' McBroom said.
   Four victims were brought to Cook County Hospital, according to
Wanda Robertson, a hospital spokeswoman. Three were taken
immediately to the trauma unit, which handles the most serious
medical emergencies.
   All three died at the trauma unit, she said. The Cook County
medical examiner's office said the other two dead persons
apparently died at the scene.
   Saigh identified the dead custodian as Arthur Baker. Ms.
Robertson said he was 33, and said the other two who died at the
hospital were Irma Ruiz, no age or occupation, and an unidentified
man.
   The wounded officer at Mount Sinai was identified as Greg
Jaglowski, 38. The other wounded person, brought to Cook County,
was Leplace Chestnut, 34, who was shot in the hand and was in good
condition, Ms. Robertson said.
   She didn't know if Ms. Ruiz or Chestnut were police officers.
</TEXT>
