<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Greece     09-22 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Greece,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Minister Reported Confident of New Accord on Bases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greek Foreign Minister Karolos Papoulias told
Congress Thursday he was confident his government and the United
States can reach agreement on U.S. military bases in Greece, a
congressional source said.
   The foreign minister also said Greek authorities would not free
a Palestinian they are holding on false passport charges until it
settles a U.S. extradition request for him to face murder charges
arising from a 1982 airliner bombing near Hawaii, said the source.
   Papoulias spoke in a closed session of the House Foreign Affairs
Committee, and the source discussed the meeting on condition he not
be identified.
   Papoulias reiterated Prime Minister Andreas Papandreou's terms
for a new military base agreement that include ending U.S.
operations at Hellenikon and not transferring them to any of the 23
other American installations in Greece, the source said.
   Hellenikon is a logistics base at Athens International Airport
and U.S. officials have called it a central issue in the
negotiations that Greece says will restart in two weeks in Athens.
The existing five-year agreement gives U.S. forces 18 months to
leave if a new accord is not reached by Dec. 21.
   Rep. Gus Yatron, D-Ohio, told Papoulias the American public
would be upset if Greece frees Mohammed Rashid, an admitted
Palestine Liberation Organization operative. Rashid is serving a
seven-month sentence for entering Greece May 30 using a forged
Syrian passport that he said was provided by PLO superiors.
   Rashid, 34, has denied U.S. charge of planting a bomb on a Pan
American World Airways jetliner in 1982, causing an explosion over
Hawaii that killed a Japanese teenager and injured 15 other people.
</TEXT>
