<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon 8thLd-Writethru a0588 09-22 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon, 8th Ld - Writethru, a0588,0614</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gemayel Says He Will Step Down at Midnight</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Gemayel saying he'll step
down, interim government to take over. Pick up 4th graf pvs: `Daoud
Daoud...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FAROUK NASSAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Amin Gemayel said he was
leaving office at the end of his 6-year-term at midnight tonight
and would hand power to an interim government. Parliament failed
today to elect a new head of state.
   Gemayel did not name members of the new interim cabinet.
Presidential palace sources said the cabinet will be announced
later in a presidential decree.
   ``I leave the presidency today worried and filled with
anxiety,'' Gemayel told the nation in a five-minute farewell
address televised nationwide.
   ``The constitutional authority should have passed through the
free will of parliament members to a president who enjoys the
confidence of the people,'' he said.
   Gemayel's delegation of power to an interim government defies a
warning by the nation's Moslem religious leaders that such a move
would partition Lebanon.
   Earlier today, fighting broke out along the city's dividing
Green Line, and state radio said gunmen killed two senior
commanders of the mainstream Shiite Moslem Amal militia.
   Christians and Moslems have been fighting a civil war for the
past 13 years, ravaging the once prosperous economy of this nation
and dividing the country into factions controlled by bands of
guerrillas.
   Under an unwritten national covenant dating from independence in
1943, the Lebanese president must be a Maronite Christian, the
prime minister a Sunni Moslem and the Parliament speaker a Shiite
Moslem.
   Daoud Daoud and Mahmoud Fakih, top Amal officers for southern
Lebanon, were killed ``instantly'' when a rocket-propelled grenade
hit the car they were riding in on the Ouzai highway, the broadcast
said. The highway is in Syrian-policed south Beirut.
   Daoud and Fakih, whose Amal Shiite movement is backed by Syria,
led a crackdown on pro-Iranian Shiite fundamentalists in south
Lebanon earlier this year. That operation ousted the extremist
Hezbollah, or Party of God, from most of the southern villages.
   Shell explosions and bursts of gunfire echoed across Beirut
after the Parliament speaker Hussein Husseini, a Shiite Moslem, put
off voting for 24 hours.
   Police said one Christian militiaman was killed and two soldiers
of the regular army's predominantly Shiite Moslem 6th Brigade were
wounded in mortar and machine gun duels near the old Parliament
headquarters.
   Moslems have said that if Gemayel appoints a Christian to be
prime minister, they will declare their own republic in territory
they control. That would formalize the breakup of Lebanon into
rival sectarian mini-states.
   Former President Charles Helou said after meeting with Gemayel
the new prime minister would probably be ``a member of the Helou
clan.'' It was an apparent reference to his cousin, Pierre Helou, a
Maronite Catholic businessman who maintains close ties with several
Moslem leaders.
   Three Christians are standing for election to replace the
Maronite president. Syria backs two of them: former President
Suleiman Franjieh, 78, and 58-year-old Parliament Deputy Mikhail
Daher.
   The third, veteran politician Raymond Edde, has been living in
self-imposed exile in Paris for 12 years after escaping three
assassination attempts in Lebanon.
   Edde, 75, is the most popular in public opinion polls. But
Daher's chances appear stronger in Parliament because he is backed
by the United States as well as Syria, Lebanon's main power broker.
Damascus has 40,000 troops in the country.
   Militant Christians have rejected both Daher and Franjieh,
charging they would allow Lebanon to become a Syrian satellite and
give Moslems too much power in the government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
