<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Drugs     09-22 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drugs,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baltimore Mayor Says Legalize Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH J. HARPAZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Decriminalizing heroin and crack would remove
the profit from the drug trade, reduce street crime, and ease the
burden on the legal system, Baltimore Mayor Kurt L. Schmoke said
Thursday.
   ``I'd like to see leading the war on drugs, the surgeon general,
not the attorney general,'' Schmoke said at a debate sponsored by
the New York Board of Trade and held before 100 business
executives, students, and journalists.
   Schmoke, whose support of decriminalization caused a stir at the
U.S. Conference of Mayors in April, plans to testify Sept. 29 at a
congressional hearing on the issue.
   ``I was a prosecutor for 7{ years and I know what I'm talking
about,'' Schmoke said. ``As long as we continue doing what we're
doing, children are going to be lured into the drug trade and dirty
needles are going to kill people. I want to treat people with the
disease called addiction as patients, not as criminals.
   ``You have to reallocate those resources to the public health
system, toward education, treatment and prevention,'' he added.
   He also called for a national commission that would examine
prescription and illegal drugs, alcohol and cigarettes to determine
the most effective way to regulate each.
   Schmoke shared the dais with Georgette Bennett, a
decriminalization advocate whose 1987 book ``Crimewarps'' about
future crime trends was nominated for a Pulitzer Prize.
   Opposing them were Robert A. Stutman, a special agent with the
Drug Enforcement Agency, and the New York State Director of
Substance Abuse Services, Julio A. Martinez, who founded the
Phoenix House drug rehabilitation program.
   Martinez showed the audience a bottle of multicolored pills, a
container of liquid methadone and a bottle of brandy as examples of
substances that are widely abused even though they are legal.
   Stutman disagreed with Schmoke's assertion that Prohibition was
a failure. Stutman noted a decline in alcoholism and cirrhosis of
the liver during the Prohibition years, while Schmoke said making
alcohol illegal gave rise to organized crime and deprived the
government of tax revenue.
</TEXT>
