<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 1601EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ShootingProtest Bjt   09-22 0715</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shooting Protest, Bjt,0736</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Uneasy Calm Prevails in Riot-Torn Louisiana Community</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN McGILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SHREVEPORT, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Decades of racism and black unemployment
made it inevitable that Shreveport would see an outbreak of
violence like this week's rock-throwing and arson following the
killing of a black man, a civil rights leader says.
   ``Shreveport's been dodging the bullet for 25 years,'' said
Larry English of the local NAACP chapter.
   The violence Tuesday and Wednesday nights, set off when a white
woman shot a black man, was confined to a few blocks in Cedar
Grove, a mostly residential neighborhood of modest houses and small
businesses about six miles from downtown.
   Police spokeswoman Cindy Chadwick said no problems were reported
in Cedar Grove after dozens of heavily armed Special Response Team
officers left the area early Thursday.
   Police took down roadblocks that sealed off the area for about
four hours Wednesday night, but Chadwick said beefed up patrols
were ready to seal off the area again if violence resumed.
   The rioting was set off by the killing Tuesday night of William
David McKinney, 22. A 17-year-old white girl was arrested and
officials said the shooting followed a drug deal that went bad,
with the victim an innocent bystander.
   Black leaders said another factor was anger over the killing of
a black teen-ager by a white teen-ager at a restaurant last month.
   And, they said, there was lingering frustration over the recent
acquittal in west Texas of three law officers accused in the
beating death of a Florien, La., black man arrested last Christmas
Day on suspicion of drunk driving.
   But those three incidents were only catalysts, black leaders
said.
   The Rev. E. Edward Jones, president of the National Baptist
Convention and a long-time Shreveport civil rights leader, blamed
long-standing ``institutional racism'' for the trouble. But he
warned blacks against violence.
   ``Destruction is not the way. We need reasoning and logic,''
said Jones.
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson blamed the unrest on poverty and
illiteracy.
   ``They've had too much access to guns and drugs and too little
access to jobs, to scholarships,'' Jackson said in Baton Rouge.
   ``In that city today, we must make the appeal for the haves and
the have nots, the black and the white to come together and study
war no more,'' Jackson said.
   Classes at Caddo Parish schools near the riot area continued
without interruption, although Assistant Superintendent Ealie
Thornton said absences would be excused if parents decided to keep
their children home.
   The School Board said security would be beefed up at this
weekend's high school football games, where there have been
occasional race-related problems over the years. But board official
David Barr said the security was planned before the Cedar Grove
incident because of a rash of minor stadium crimes.
   Tuesday's violence centered around a small grocery where the
white shooting suspect and her companion fled after McKinney was
shot. The grocery and a neighboring liquor store were gutted by
fire and a television news team's car was burned while hundreds of
people rampaged, breaking store windows and looting.
   Five arrests were reported in connection with the rioting and
Tamala Vergo, 17, was booked with second-degree murder. Official
police reports contain few details but individual officers, city
officials and one witness indicated McKinney was an innocent
bystander felled after a drug deal went sour.
   Wednesday night's violence was on a much smaller, less intense
scale.
   There were reports of sporadic gunfire and at least one fire.
But no injuries or arrests were reported as police let the
troublemakers disperse by themselves.
   Residents say Cedar Grove once was a quiet, racially mixed
suburb that has deteriorated for a variety of reasons. The area is
now predominantly black, the apparent result of ``white flight''
during the civil rights years.
   One police officer called the small area where most of the
violence occurred a ``curb-service crack store.''
   Buddy Chamness, a former resident who moved away five years ago,
said people of both races have left because of crime, particularly
the drug trade.
   ``At one time it was peaceful,'' said Chamness. ``When I was
young, children could walk up and down the streets without fear.
Our moms could walk to the store. I don't know what happened to the
neighborhood.''
</TEXT>
