<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 1611EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CampaignAds     09-22 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Campaign Ads,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Will Spend $32 Million on Ads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush's plan to spend a
record amount on TV advertising continues a trend toward
presidential campaign budgets dominated by paid media expenditures,
political analysts said Thursday.
   Four years ago, Democratic nominee Walter Mondale spent more
than $20 million on media and President Reagan spent about $25
million.
   This fall, Vice President George Bush expects to mount a $32
million-plus TV blitz. That's at least 60 percent of the combined
$54 million that the candidate and his national party can spend
directly.
   A Bush aide, who spoke only on condition of anonymity, said 60
percent, or $32.4 million, is ``a pretty accurate figure, which
would make it the largest television expenditure in modern
history.''
   Mark Gearan, a spokesman for Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis,
the Democratic nominee, said Dukakis would be competitive on the
airwaves but declined to be specific.
   Both candidates are relying on their parties to raise tens of
millions of dollars in unrestricted ``soft money'' for political
activities at the state and national levels, enabling them to
divert a greater percentage of their own limited campaign resources
to media.
   The soft money is available for party-building activities
including lawn signs, phone banks, generic TV ads, voter
registration and get-out-the-vote drives. Such expenditures do not
count toward the candidates' overall spending ceiling.
   Bay Buchanan, Reagan's campaign treasurer in both 1980 and 1984,
said the Reagan campaign forked over several million dollars for
get-out-the-vote activities four years ago.
   ``If you can get the party to raise it... that's $3 million to
$4 million dollars you'd obviously put to media time,'' she said.
``It's a very effective way to be running an organization. Usually
the states know better how to raise and spend the money.''
   The Bush game plan represents the increasingly critical role
played by TV advertising.
   ``The very first thing I did (in 1984) was take 50 percent of
the total amount we were allocated and put it to media,'' said
Buchanan. ``Then if any money could be picked up (from other
areas), we moved that money to media. That's where any loose money
went because we felt it was the most effective way to reach
voters.''
   Democrats and Republicans alike say they are not surprised by
this year's heavy tilt toward media spending, given the increasing
importance of TV ads and the high cost of buying air time,
particularly during widely watched events such as the Olympics and
the World Series.
   But they caution against treating it as a revolutionary
development.
   ``It's not a dramatic escalation of media dollars,'' said
Republican consultant John Buckley. ``It shouldn't be overstated.
It's just incrementally more than has been spent before, in real
terms and in percentage of the overall budget.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
