<DOCNO> AP880922-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 1624EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis     09-22 0828</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Calls Bush ``Fugitive From Truth''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis struck back forcefully after
George Bush's visit to his home grounds Thursday, accusing his
Republican rival of being a ``fugitive from the truth'' in
portraying himself as a crimefighter and advocate of the
environment, education and elderly.
   ``We're here today to investigate a felony _ assault and battery
on the truth,'' the Democratic presidential nominee told a
boisterous rally outside the Massachusetts Statehouse shortly after
Bush came to Boston to pick up an endorsement from the leaders of a
Boston police union.
   ``What George Bush is doing to the truth in this campaign is a
crime,'' Dukakis said in his harshest attack yet on Bush. He spoke
to hundreds of cheering supporters and law enforcement officials
called in from around the nation to counter Bush's endorsement by
the police group.
   Dukakis also spent considerable time Thursday preparing for his
Sunday debate with Bush, meeting with New York Gov. Mario Cuomo to
discuss strategy and also attending a morning meeting with staff at
a Boston hotel where he is scheduled to take part in a mock debate
Friday.
   At the rally, recalling Bush's visit earlier this month to tour
polluted Boston Harbor, Dukakis said the vice president ``came here
to Boston to impersonate an environmentalist.'' He portrayed the
Reagan administration as an enemy of the Clean Water Act and
programs to clean up toxic waste.
   ``That's not the only time Mr. Bush has been a fugitive from the
truth,'' Dukakis said, ridiculing his rival's pledge to be the
education president and saying that when Bush has criticized the
Massachusetts economy, ``he's mugged the truth every time he's
opened his mouth.''
   Surrounded by police officers from several Massachusetts
departments as well as by law enforcement officials from Texas,
Florida, Michigan, Ohio, Connecticut, Rhode Island, Maine and two
nationwide police associations, representing more than 100,000
officers in all, Dukakis said of Bush: ``Now he's here in Boston
impersonating a law enforcement officer.
   ``We're here to give George Bush what Joe Friday used to ask
for: just the facts ma'am, just the facts,'' Dukakis said, invoking
the name of the fictional character in the popular ``Dragnet''
television series.
   ``His administration has waged not a war on crime but a war on
crime programs,'' Dukakis said.
   He then launched a scathing attack on Bush's crimefighting
record, saying drug task forces the vice president headed were
dismal failures.
   Dukakis also attacked Reagan administration ethical standards
and lashed back at Bush's frequent criticism of a Massachusetts
furlough program that, until amended earlier this year, allowed
weekend passes to first-degree murderers.
   ``For the past eight years George Bush has been running with a
crowd that wouldn't know the rule of law if it hit them in the
face,'' Dukakis said to rousing applause.
   As for furloughs, Dukakis said the federal government furloughed
nearly 16,000 inmates last year for up to 45 days at a time, among
them ``hundreds and hundreds of drug pushers and drug traffickers.''
   And he said the suspect in the murder of a Boston police officer
was a repeat violent offender who had been paroled from federal
prison after serving less than half of a prison term for bank
robbery.
   ``That's what's going on in the federal system these days, my
friends,'' Dukakis said.
   Dukakis had an energetic supporting cast for his rally,
including New York Gov. Cuomo and Ron DeLord, president of the
Combined Law Enforcement Associations of Texas, the largest police
organization in Bush's adopted home state.
   ``I'm tired of this pandering,'' Cuomo said of the Bush
campaign. ``I'm tired of the simplistics and the distortions by
people like the vice president.''
   DeLord, who gave Dukakis a 10-gallon hat after the rally, fired
up the crowd with an impassioned attack on Bush delivered in the
style of a preacher.
   ``I'm the only damn Texan in this town today representing police
officers, not George Bush,'' DeLord said. DeLord said he has been
president of the Texas organization for 12 years and, ``I've never
seen George Bush in person.''
   The rhetorical flogging of Bush by Dukakis and his supporters
overshadowed Dukakis' only planned event of the day _ a visit to a
Boston senior citizens center to reiterate his support for Social
Security while attacking Bush for breaking a tie in the Senate in
1985 with his vote to deny cost-of-living adjustments to Social
Security recipients.
   ``When election time rolls around, Mr. Bush says he wants to be
a great friend of older Americans,'' Dukakis said. ``Maybe he
thinks we all have amnesia.'' Dukakis also noted that Bush's
running mate, Indiana Sen. Dan Quayle, was among the Republicans
voting to block the cost-of-living adjustments.
   ``Lloyd Bentsen and I have a very different view,'' Dukakis said
in touting his running mate, the Texas senator. ``We're going to
stop this attack on Social Security and Medicare and we'll stop it
cold.''
</TEXT>
