<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 1655EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CathedralAttack     09-22 0679</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cathedral Attack,0698</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cardinal Prays for Slain Cathedral Usher, Deranged Attacker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDIE GLAVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Violence in St. Patrick's Cathedral that left an
usher and his deranged attacker dead was a ``special sacrilege and
tragedy,'' Cardinal John O'Connor said Thursday as he resanctified
the church and prayed for the assailant and victim alike.
   It was the first time in the 109-year history of the church that
the rite to purify a profaned sacred place was performed.
   The attack occurred about 8 p.m. Wednesday, an hour before the
church would close, when a man ran naked through the cathedral and
bludgeoned part-time usher John Winters, 77, to death with an iron
stanchion. He also injured a worshiper and a police officer before
being shot to death by police.
   The cardinal had seen the man, Jorge DelGado, 32, at morning
Mass that day when Delgado joined the line for communion.
   ``It was clear instantly there was something seriously wrong,''
O'Connor said. ``I looked up and there he is, standing before me, a
very big man, a very powerful looking man, bizarrely dressed.''
   ``He rolled his eyes. He opened and closed his eyes. He rolled
his head and the priest who was standing next to me whispered, `Be
careful. He gets violent,''' the cardinal said.
   DelGado, a vagrant who was born on St. Patrick's Day in 1956 had
pleaded guilty 11 times since 1982 to charges including assault,
attempted robbery and burglary. He had been in the cathedral many
times and had committed minor acts of vandalism there before.
   Many homeless people enter the church to avoid the heat or cold
or to find a place to sleep. Despite the attack, the archdiocese
will not change its open-door policy, O'Connor said. ``I would hate
to see us now get defensive.''
   O'Connor was not in the cathedral when DelGado, naked and
carrying red carnations and his sneakers, came into the church
Wednesday night. DelGado had stripped off his dirty shorts and
shirt minutes before in front of the RCA Building at Rockefeller
Plaza, a block away from the Fifth Avenue cathedral.
   When he first entered the church, DelGado hit a man sitting in a
back pew with the flowers and screamed, ``Get out! Get out!'' said
Chief of Detectives Robert Colangelo.
   He continued walking up the center aisle of the church to the
pew in which Linda Lawson, 39, was praying and repeatedly struck
her in the face, Colangelo said.
   The 6-foot-4, 250-pound DelGado then went to the altar of the
shrine of St. Elizabeth and pulled from the marble floor a bolted,
wrought-iron stanchion that held a prayer plaque.
   Officer James McMann, 50, who is assigned to the cathedral,
spotted DelGado and ordered him to put down the weapon. As DelGado
advanced on McMann, the officer radioed for help.
   DelGado attacked the officer, striking him in the head. He then
went to the main altar, where he found Winters, and struck him
seven or eight times in the head, killing him istantly, Colangelo
said.
   By then, three other officers arrived and repeatedly ordered
DelGado to stop. When DelGado started to lunge toward one, the
officer fired once, fatally striking DelGado in the chest, the
chief said.
   The entire incident was over in 10 minutes.
   Ms. Lawson was treated for facial injuries at the scene and
McMann was in stable condition Thursday at Bellevue Hospital.
   Before performing the resanctification rite, O'Connor spoke
about DelGado, saying he believed the attacker didn't ``have the
slightest idea what he was doing.''
   ``For it to have happened here is a special sacrilege and
tragedy,'' O'Connor said, adding that St. Patrick's was a ``magnet
for Catholics everywhere.''
   ``While the cathedral has been desecrated, while this
magnificent temple of almighty God, famous throughout the world,
has been violated, we must not forget that two men were killed here
last night,'' O'Connor told several hundred people attending the
first Mass of the day.
   ``It is for their souls I will be offering this Mass, as well as
for the purification of the cathedral.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
