<1ST_LINE>u p AM-ColoradoCongressional     09-22 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colorado Congressional,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats May Disavow Congressional Candidate For TWA Squabble</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HILLIARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional candidate being sued by TWA for
allegedly distributing posters accusing the airline of spreading
AIDS may be disavowed by his party, the state Democratic chairman
said Thursday.
   ``He was a realtor, an educator and seemed like a nice guy,''
state party Chairman Buie Seawell said of John J. Mitchell, 53, of
Colorado Springs.
   Mitchell was nominated without opposition in the heavily
Republican 5th District to run against freshman Rep. Joel Hefley,
the GOP candidate. The district encompasses the Colorado Springs
area south of Denver, and it never has sent a Democrat to Congress.
   Seawell compared Mitchell to a ``walk-on candidate'' and said
the party nominated him ``with the best of intentions.''
   ``But we were not tough-minded enough _ almost nobody is under
these circumstances _ and we've got to begin to get that way,'' he
said.
   Neither Democratic Party officials nor reporters have been able
to reach Mitchell for comment by telephone or in person since his
name surfaced in the lawsuit filed Monday by TWA.
   The Denver federal court suit accuses Mitchell of libeling the
airline and seeks $500,000 damages.
   Seawell said the 5th District Central Committee will meet Oct. 2
to consider the Mitchell case. The State Centays, read:
``AIDS is Spread Through TWA,'' ``Today's TWA Means AIDS'' and TWA:
Travel With AIDS.''
   TWA claims Mitchell sent a poster to the airline's New York
office on July 26 with a note that said: ``Thousands of these have
been sent around the country. Our staff is working on a new poster.
They will continue to be sent until TWA corrects the hurt you have
caused-cost me.''
   If Mitchell does not remove himself as a candidate, the party
may move to disavow itself from Mitchell, said Seawell.
   ``The Democratic Party does not, in any way, endorse or condone
alleged statements made by Mr. Mitchell regarding Trans World
Airlines,'' he said.
   Seawell said it may take a court action to actually remove
Mitchell's name from the ballot. ``We will do everything necessary
to provide a fair hearing before any action is taken by the 5th
District, the chairman or the central committee,'' he added.
   Mitchell, who has no previous political experience, has operated
J. Mitchell Realty in Colorado Springs since 1984, according to his
resume. He was a teacher in Massachusetts from 1962 to 1981 before
moving to Colorado. He once served as a waiter in the Air Force
Academy dining hall before receiving his real estate license.
</TEXT>
