<DOCNO> AP880922-0148 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 2058EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     09-22 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>THIEF RIVER FALLS, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's not as cheap as a string
around the finger, but a new gadget for the forgetful gives a
gentle nudge at the waistline as a reminder of whatever it is the
wearer wants to be reminded.
   A psychologist invented the vibrating gadget named the
MotivAider.
   The invention is based on what psychologist Steve Levinson of
Thief River Falls says is obvious _ that the human brain does a
poor job of making sure its owner does all the things that a person
has firmly resolved to do.
   The gadget he calls an ``intention arousing device,'' is about 2
inches square and hangs like a beeper from the user's belt.
   Set for intervals of one minute to 24 hours, it flutters
silently against the waistline.
   The wearer has programmed in his or her memory what the reminder
means, says Levinson.
   Ros Fairbank, who lost to Martina Navratilova in the Wimbledon
quarterfinals this year, told the Star Tribune of Minneapolis that
it helped improve her backhand. Her problem was failing to get her
racquet back early enough and to ``hit over the ball,'' she said in
a phone interview.
   She set the MotivAider at three-minute intervals and wore it
during practice. When it vibrated, she said to herself ``Early
preparation!'' and that's what she focused on.
   ``I wouldn't say it made me win a match,'' she said, ``but it
developed my backhand and my confidence in my backhand.''
   Bill Priedeman, a Deephaven sales manager, says he improved his
golf game. When the $79.95 battery-operated device fluttered at
three-minute intervals he told himself: ``Keep your head down, slow
on the backswing and stop before you come down again.'' The result:
``I shot 10 strokes less than I ever had before.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRUNSWICK, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The battle over which Brunswick holds
title to the original Brunswick stew moves on as a losing team from
Georgia heads for Virginia in November for a rematch.
   Woody Woodside, executive director of the Brunswick-Golden Isles
Chamber of Commerce, said the Georgia residents weren't surprised
they came up on the short end of last week's contest, held in
Brunswick County, Va.
   ``How could we win on their turf?'' he said.
   The Virginians will defend their title during Brunswick's Main
Street Jubilee on Nov. 19.
   Phyllis Taunton, head of the Georgia cooking team, said when
Brunswick County, Va., announced plans to hold a stew cook-off
during its Heritage Festival, ``we felt we had to be there to
defend our honor.''
   The debate over which of the two communities can rightfully
claim the original Brunswick stew recipe began when the Georgia
town challenged other Brunswicks in the nation to a cook-off, said
Woodside.
   The Virginia county accepted the challenge, but was unable to
attend last year's cook-off in Georgia, he said.
   ``They even went so far as to approach their Commonwealth to get
a resolution claiming they had the original Brunswick Stew,''
Woodside said. So, in the spirit of competition, the Brunswick
legislative delegation approached the Georgia General Assembly and
received a similar resolution.
   Chef Dan Dickerson said Virginia's version of Brunswick stew
uses a chicken base instead of the pork or beef used by the
Georgians and is not as spicy as the Georgia version.
</TEXT>
