<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Wright-Ethics     09-22 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wright-Ethics,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-CIA-Wright</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House committee on Thursday approved a
$550,000 budget increase for the ethics committee to cover mounting
costs of an investigation into allegations of financial
improprieties by House Speaker Jim Wright.
   The chairman of the ethics panel, Rep. Julian Dixon, D-Calif.,
said the outside counsel hired to conduct the investigation has
been costing $150,000 a month and by the end of this month would
exhaust the $300,000 earlier earmarked for the probe.
   ``It's taking a lot of time,'' said Rep. John T. Myers, R-Ind.,
the senior minority member of the ethics committee, formally known
as the Committee on Standards of Official Conduct. ``It takes a lot
more in-depth investigation than we ever anticipated.''
   But he added: ``We have a commitment to the Congress'' to be
thorough. ``This is necessary. I don't think we have any choice.''
   The counsel, Chicago attorney Richard J. Phelan, has assigned
six or seven attorneys to work on the case, which involves
allegations that Wright, D-Texas, abused his congressional office
for personal gain and improperly intervened with federal regulators
on behalf of constituents.
   The attorneys together are spending an average of 1,200 to 1,300
hours monthly on the probe, Dixon said.
   Dixon told the Committee on House Administration, the chamber's
housekeeping panel, that the $550,000 funding boost would enable
the probe to extend through the end of the year, if needed. It also
is possible the investigation could extend into 1989, Dixon said.
   Wright, who appeared before the panel for more than five hours
last week to present his defense, has said repeatedly that he wants
the investigation completed before Congress adjourns for the year
in mid-October.
   Dixon declined to comment on why the probe was taking longer
than expected.
   On a separate matter relating to the speaker, Dixon told
reporters that a new request from the House Republican leadership
for an ethics probe of Wright, concerning his disclosure of a
purported CIA covert action in Nicaragua, would be dealt with
separately from the current probe.
   ``That would be done independent of this,'' he said. ``I think
it would be done in a whole different manner,'' perhaps with the
cooperation of the Intelligence Committee, he added.
</TEXT>
