<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 1809EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-FAA-WindShear     09-22 0721</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FAA-Wind Shear,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airlines Told To Equip Aircraft With Devices To Detect Wind Shear</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration on
Thursday ordered airlines to equip all their aircraft with devices
that will help pilots detect and escape from deadly wind shears.
   Powerful shears called microbursts have been called the No. 1
killer of airline passengers and have been responsible for at least
five fatal airline crashes and 500 deaths in the last decade,
according to aviation safety experts.
   The FAA regulation was announced by the Transportation
Department, which said the devices, to be phased into operation in
all aircraft of 30 or more seats over the next four years, will
cost $40,000 to $50,000 per airplane.
   About 3,600 commercial jet transport planes also will be
required to have the devices, department officials said.
   A microburst is a powerful downburst of air caused by a sudden
change in wind direction. Such a downburst struck a Delta Air Lines
L-1011 as it was attempting to land at Dallas-Fort Worth in 1985
and literally forced the plane into the ground, killing 134 people.
   The accident focused increased attention on developing and
installing sophisticated ground radar that would provide advanced
warning of shears along departure and approach lanes, but the radar
is not expected to be available until the early 1990s.
   At the same time, the FAA and industry began taking a closer
look at devices for the cockpit that would provide pilots with a
clear indication when their plane is facing wind shear conditions.
   Piedmont Airlines two years ago began installing the equipment
being required by the FAA and today has the devices in 112 of its
191 aircraft, according to Piedmont spokesman Mike Clark.
   It could not immediately be determined whether other airlines
have bought similar equipment.
   Under the FAA regulation the airlines will be allowed to phase
in installation of the equipment over about four years. Half of an
airline's fleet must have the devices within 27 months,
three-fourths of the fleet within 39 months and the rest of the
fleet within 51 months.
   Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley said the equipment ``will
enhance safety by giving pilots a valuable tool for coping with the
dangerous wind shear phenomenon.''
   ``Experience has shown that pilots can recover successfully from
wind shear encounters if they can recognize the situation quickly
enough and have sufficient information to execute escape
maneuvers,'' Burnley said in a statement.
   But the aviation industry has been divided on the value of the
cockpit devices. Some experts note that the equipment is not a
radar that would give advance warning of a shear.
   Instead, the system consists of sensitive equipment that
calculates airspeed and other factors and tells a pilot when the
plane is in the midst of wind shear conditions. Critics of the
equipment have suggested that by then it may already be too late to
fly through a microburst, especially if the plane is close to the
ground, as in a takeoff or landing.
   The FAA rule also requires airlines to provide pilots with
increased training on wind shear recognition and recovery
procedures while using the new equipment.
   Pilots are divided as to how best to fly through a shear. Many
insist that a powerful microburst such as the one that struck the
Delta plane in Dallas or the one encountered by a Pan American
World Airways jetliner that crashed as it was taking off from New
Orleans in 1982 is virtually impossible to escape. The Pan Am crash
left 154 people dead.
   The airlines as well as the pilots union have urged speedy
development and installation of so-called Doppler radar at major
airports so that shears can be detected in advance and pilots can
maneuver around them or not depart. The first of 17 such Doppler
radars are scheduled to be installed at airports between 1990 and
1992. About 30 additional radars would be installed at other
airports later under an FAA contract scheduled to be awarded later
this year.
   The FAA and the National Aeronautics and Space Administration
also have under way a five-year research program aimed at
eventually developing a more advanced wind shear detection device
for the cockpit that would be able to warn a pilot in advance when
it is about to encounter shear conditions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880922-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 1812EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-House-Iraq     09-22 0710</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-House-Iraq,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Approves Sanctions Over Use Of Poison Gas Against
Kurds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brushing aside Reagan administration
objections, the House Foreign Affairs Committee approved on
Thursday legislation imposing sanctions on Iraq for its alleged use
of poison gas ``against Kurdish insurgents and unarmed Kurdish
civilians.''
   The committee acted after senior Republican members told
administration officials that there is strong bipartisan support
for the measure in the House and urged them to reconsider their
opposition.
   One official, Peter Burley, deputy assistant secretary of state
for Middle Eastern Affairs, told the panel the Reagan
administration believes the sanctions legislation is `'premature''
and ``counterproductive'' because it is likely to undercut intense
diplomatic efforts aimed at preventing the future use of chemical
weapons by Iraq.
   ``I am very disappointed in the statement that you read,'' said
Rep. William S. Broomfield, R-Mich., the panel's senior GOP member.
``A lot of effort has gone into making this a bipartisan effort. I
think this is a very measured response and I think the
administration will see when it hits the floor the large bipartisan
support it will have.''
   Unlike sanctions legislation approved earlier by the Senate, the
House resolution does not accuse Iraq of waging a war of genocide
against the country's Kurdish minority. And the sanctions it would
impose, at least initially, are generally less severe.
   The resolution declares that the Iraqi army has destroyed
Kurdish villages in northern Iraq and adds: ``Substantial evidence
exists that the Iraqi army has been using chemical weapons against
Kurdish insurgents and unarmed Kurdish civilians.''
   It calls that ``a gross violation of international law.''
   In a series of initial steps, the resolution would prohibit
government-to-government or commercial arms sales to Iraq as well
as sensitive high technology items.
   It authorizes the president, after consultation with Congress,
to take a series of other punitive actions against Iraq including
barring Iraqi exports, including petroleum products, from entering
the United States, barring or restricting U.S. exports to Iraq,
denying U.S. financial credits or financial guarantees and opposing
loans to Iraq by international financial institutions.
   The resolution authorizes the president to waive any or all of
the sanctions if he certifies to Congress that Iraq is not using
chemical weapons in violation of international law, that Iraq has
provided ``reliable assurances'' that it will not use chemical
weapons in the future and that it is willing to permit on-site
inspection by impartial observers.
   The committee approved the measure on a voice vote after acting
to include a prohibition against the export to Iraq of any chemical
that might be used to produce chemical weapons and to authorize the
president to bar the sale of an entire steel plant in Texas to Iraq.
   The House committee's action follows the issuance on Wednesday
of a Senate staff report based on interviews with more than 200 of
the 65,000 Kurdish refugees who fled into Turkey following the
alleged poison gas attacks on their villages by Iraqi aircraft.
   The report concludes that ``overwhelming evidence exists'' that
Iraq used chemical weapons against the Kurds and that hundreds,
perhaps thousands, of people likely were killed.
   The only committee member to oppose the House resolution was
Rep. Toby Roth, R-Wis., who said that while the use of poison gas
is ``despicable,'' sanctions against Iraq will only hurt U.S.
exporters.
   But Rep. James Bilbray, D-Nev., said that to do nothing is
unacceptable.
   ``If we don't do something we are going to have tell our own
children and grandchildren that we sat by while an entire people
was exterminated,'' he said.
   Burley said the State Department is encouraged by a recent
statement by the foreign minister of Iraq which he said U.S.
diplomats interpret as meaning that ``there will be no future use
of chemical weapons.''
   Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., told Burley: ``I am intrigued by your
logic which looks at a criminal act, sweeps it aside and takes the
word of a criminal that he will not take criminal actions in the
future.''
   Burley replied: ``We believe enacting these sanctions now will
lessen our influence ... We do not believe that sanctions now would
bring us closer to the objective we both share, ending the use of
chemical weapons by Iraq.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
