<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 2122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Iran-Contra     09-22 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Sets Hearing on Whether Former CIA Agent Can Be Indicted
Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Thursday granted a defense
request for a hearing on whether Iran-Contra prosecutors could
re-indict former CIA agent Joseph F. Fernandez in Virginia if
charges filed here were dismissed.
   U.S. District Judge Aubrey E. Robinson Jr. scheduled an Oct. 6
hearing on a motion by independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh to
dismiss five criminal charges against Fernandez so that prosecutors
could seek a new indictment from a federal grand jury in nearby
Alexandria, Va.
   Lawyers for Fernandez, who is charged with helping direct a
secret arms supply network for the Nicaraguan rebels in defiance of
a congressional ban on such aid, urged the judge to dismiss the
case altogether rather than give prosecutors a chance to bring
fresh charges.
   The dispute stems from Fernandez's refusal to waive his right to
be tried in the Eastern District of Virginia on charges that he
lied about his role in the arms-supply network to his CIA superiors
and to the presidential commission headed by former Sen. John
Tower, R-Texas, that investigated the Iran-Contra affair.
   Four counts of the indictment alleging Fernandez obstructed the
commission's work and made false statements charge the alleged
offenses occurred at CIA headquarters in Langley, Va.
   The conspiracy charge, which is the fifth count of the
indictment, alleges that Fernandez, former National Security
Council aide Oliver North and arms dealer Richard V. Secord,
operated an illegal arms supply network. Part of the conspiracy
occurred in Washington, according to the indictment.
   Last week, Fernandez moved to dismiss the four other charges
because the federal court in Washington lacked jurisdiction over
them.
   Rather than face the prospect of two trials, Walsh asked
Robinson for permission to dismiss all five charges against
Fernandez so that he could seek a new indictment from a federal
grand jury in Alexandria.
   Defense attorney Thomas E. Wilson argued in court papers earlier
this week that prosecutors should not be allowed to bring the case
in Virginia because they already have been given a preview of
Fernandez's defense in motions filed before Robinson.
</TEXT>
