<DOCNO> AP880922-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 1816EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Reagan-Space 1stLd-Writethru a0659 09-22 0925</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Space, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0659,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Relishes Return To Space</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 4th graf, Two days, to correct to three days; SUBS 6th
graf, In a speech, to update with speech delivered; SUBS 8th graf,
Reagan's itinerary, with seven grafs to update and add color; SUBS
12th graf, The flight, to correct months to 32; also fixes category
code in header</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven days before the U.S. hopes to return to
manned space flight, President Reagan lauded the ``seven heroes''
of the Challenger on Thursday and pledged, ``You can delay our long
trek to greatness, but you cannot halt it.''
   Returning to the scene of one of his most emotional times as
president, Reagan told workers at the Johnson Space Center:
   ``Soon the world will be watching as five brave Americans lift
off from Earth. America is going to space again _ and we are going
there to stay.''
   Three days after the Challenger blew apart on Jan. 28, 1986,
little more than a minute after liftoff, Reagan went to the Johnson
Space Center to console the relatives and friends of the seven crew
members who died.
   America's worst space tragedy shook the nation and threw the
space program into disarray.
   In a speech to NASA employees a week before Discovery's
blast-off, Reagan said, ``Our early settlers knew great risks and
made great sacrifices, but with their sacrifices, they moved the
frontier forward and built a great nation.''
   ``Neither can we stand still, nor be content, and we are not
afraid,'' Reagan said. ``Ill fortune can slow us down, but it
cannot stop us.''
   Upon his arrival in Houston, Reagan was asked if he wanted to go
up in space. ``I've been there for several years,'' the president
chuckled as he climbed into his limousine.
   At the sprawling space center, Reagan greeted the five Discovery
crewmen: commander Frederick Hauck, co-pilot Richard Covey and
mission specialists John Lounge, George ``Pinky'' Nelson and David
Hilmers.
   The president was treated to a brief tour of a mockup of a space
shuttle. The crew, clad in royal blue jumpsuits, led Reagan up the
stairs to peer through an open hatch in the two-story-high mockup
of the shuttle.
   Reagan, queried after his brief tour whether he wished he
committed more money to the space program, replied, ``I've tried to
do all that's possible. We've had some problems,'' he added,
apparently referring to the Challenger tragedy.
   ``This program is the highest priority,'' Reagan said.
   The president then walked toward the end of the mock shuttle,
where he addressed 8,000 to 10,000 NASA employees, contractors and
their families, many of whom waved tiny American flags under the
bright Texas sun and roared their approval during Reagan's speech.
   At the end of his speech, Hauck presented Reagan with a royal
blue jacket and told him that the insignia patch from the Discovery
mission would be flown into space with the shuttle crew and
returned and presented to Reagan at the end of the mission.
   Before meeting the astronauts, who are under a modified
quarantine before their scheduled launch, Reagan underwent a
medical examination in which he was pronounced free of any disease
that could be easily transmitted.
   Reagan's senior aides and Secret Service detail were required to
complete medical data forms before they were cleared to enter the
space center with the president. Only Reagan was to have direct
contact with the astronauts.
   Next Thursday, the shuttle is scheduled to blast off from Cape
Canaveral, Fla., on a four-day stay in orbit _ a mission that will
include the launching of a $100 million communications satellite.
   The flight will be the first in 32 months _ a wrenching period
in which NASA underwent a series of management and other changes,
including a redesign of the shuttle boosters, emanating from a
presidential commission's findings resulting from the accident.
   The tragedy was a monumental setback to the space program, which
was the first to put a man on the moon and which had led the world
in exploration after initially playing catchup with the Soviet
Union in the late 1960s.
   Reagan's space-center stop came on a day in which the president
was making campaign appearances in Texas for Republican
presidential candidate George Bush and Rep. Beau Boulter, R-Texas,
who is trying to wrest Sen. Lloyd Bentsen's seat from him. Bentsen
is running for both the Senate and the vice presidency under a
Texas law that permits such a dual candidacy.
   The president was wrapping up his campaign day by sharing the
stage with Bush at a $1,000-a-plate fund-raising dinner for some
2,500 Republicans.
   In the Johnson Space Center pep talk, Reagan said that ``when we
launch the space shuttle Discovery, even more than the thrust of
Discovery's great engines, it will be the inspiring courage of our
heroes, and the hopes and dreams of every American, that will lift
the shuttle into the heavens. And may the hand of God bring it
safely back to Earth.''
   ``And when the Discovery takes off, seven precious souls will
soar beside it, the seven heroes of the Challenger,'' he added.
``With their lives, they moved a nation, they summoned America to
reach higher still, as they wrote man's destiny into the stars.''
   Reagan recalled how he had joined Americans in mourning the loss
of the Challenger crew members ``one cold January day'' in 1986,
and said:
   ``We are a nation born of pioneers, and we will always create
our future on the frontier. America can live no other way.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
