<DOCNO> AP880922-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 2127EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Banks-Securities     09-22 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Banks-Securities,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panels Approve Banking Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two House committees approved legislation
Thursday that grants banks broad new powers to affiliate through
holding companies with securities firms.
   The House Energy and Commerce and Judiciary committees, racing a
deadline, approved amendments to a bill passed by the House Banking
Committee last month. The Senate also has completed work on a
separate measure.
   The Energy and Commerce Committee, under Chairman John D.
Dingell, D-Mich., hastily approved amendments drafted by the panel
late Wednesday night and early Thursday morning.
   One amendment, which was being reproduced for members, arrived
at the committee at 11:55 a.m. and was approved at 12:01 p.m.
   Nevertheless, Dingell said in a statement after 23 committee
members voted to send the measure to the floor, with only Rep.
Ralph M. Hall, D-Tex., asking that he be recorded against the bill:
``The committee today restored balance and equity to the
restructuring of the financial services industry.
   ``The real winners today were the nation's depositors, investors
and taxpayers,'' he said. ``If everyone with an interest in this
legislation, both inside and outside the Congress, can come
together in a spirit of harmony and compromise, it will be possible
to work out a bill.''
   Treasury Undersecretary George D. Gould issued a statement
expressing ``strong opposition'' to the Energy and Commerce
Committee's action.
   It ``demonstrates that the House of Representatives is not
prepared to move forward into the modern financial world ... (and
is) retreating into a protectionist, anti-competitive regime left
over from the 1930s,'' he said.
   The administration favors the bank-securities bill passed by the
Senate because it permits banks to enter into a greater number of
securities activities.
   Donald G. Ogilvie, executive vice president of the American
Bankers Association, said, however, his organization is extremely
disappointed by the action taken by the Dingell committee.
   ``At a time when positive legislation is badly needed to
modernize the banking laws so bankers can fully meet their
customers' needs, the committee's action removes the only positive
feature contained in the House bill _ new securities authorities,''
he said. ``Their action also makes the limited bank insurance
authorities even more restrictive. If passed, the bill would be a
dramatic step backwards for American consumers and U.S. banking.''
   The Judiciary Committee also approved the measure after removing
mandatory prison sentences for individuals who breach the so-called
``firewalls'' constructed between banking and securities functions,
an amendment introduced by Rep. William J. Hughes, D-N.J.
   The full House is expected to take up the measure next week.
   In his opening statement, Dingell said any relaxation of the
Depression-era Glass-Steagall Act, designed to preclude virtually
all securities activities by banks and their affiliates, ``must
carry with it the creation of strong firewalls, functional
regulation, and effective prohibitions against conflicts of
interest in order to repeat the abuses which necessitated the
creation of the Glass-Steagall wall.'' He said he believes his
amendments do that.
   Among other things, the amendments would:
   _Prohibit loans between banks and their securities affiliates to
prop up a failing affiliate or purchase securities underwritten by
the affiliate.
   _Strictly limit transfer of confidential customer information
between banks and securities affiliates.
   _Prohibit illegal tie-ins so that all dealings are arms-length.
   _Prohibit a bank from stuffing its trust department accounts
with unsound securities underwritten by its securities affiliate.
   _Prohibit shared name, premises, log and advertising.
   _Prohibit shared officers, directors and employees, with
rulemaking authority to make exceptions for smaller banks.
</TEXT>
