<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Homeless-Housing     09-22 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Homeless-Housing,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sales Resume for 27,000 HUD-Owned Houses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government expects to sell about 2,500
single-family homes within the next couple of days, following a
federal judge's decision lifting a three-week ban on such sales,
federal housing officials said Thursday.
   More than 27,000 homes owned by HUD went back on the market
Thursday morning after U.S. District Judge Oliver Gasch refused to
issue a preliminary injunction in a suit by homeless advocates who
say more of the government-owned houses should be made available to
people living in the streets.
   Government lawyers argued that stopping the sales would bankrupt
the Federal Housing Administration's home mortgage insurance fund.
All of the houses were obtained after buyers defaulted on
FHA-backed loans.
   HUD had more than 47,000 such houses when Gasch issued a
temporary restraining order Aug. 30, but about 20,000 of them were
not affected because contracts already had been signed for their
sale.
   Jim Nistler, HUD deputy assistant secretary, said field offices
around the country to expect about 2,500 sales contracts to be
signed right away for the houses that were off the market since
Gasch issued the order in a suit by the National Housing Law
Project.
   Project lawyer Florence Roisman said Thursday that homeless
advocates were ``deeply disappointed'' with the oon's
resources.''
   Ruder also said it would be difficult to determine who was
responsible for ``deficiencies'' in the bond's disclosure reports.
He noted, too, that bondholders were already trying to recover
their investments through a civil trial in Tucson, Ariz.
   In a 376-page report that brought to a close what had been
described as the largest single investigation in SEC history, the
commission's staff found that WPPSS tried to put the best spin
possible on the construction and financial problems that led up to
the default in 1983 and in some cases ``avoided disclosure of
negative developments.''
   Others, including the bond underwriters, bond counsel and the
rating agencies, weren't agressive enough in asking questions and
exercising ``due diligence'' to ensure that investors were aware of
the supply system's mounting problems, the report said.
   The report, however, drew no legal conclusions.
   While taking no enforcement action, the commission decided to
seek public comment on a proposed rule that would impose stricter
disclosure requirements on issuers of municipal bonds and the
securities firms that sell them.
   The SEC's decision drew criticism from some members of Congress.
   ``It sends a message that if you mess up, mess up big because
the principal regulatory agency doesn't have the resources to
pursue enforcement action,'' said Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore.
   Wyden said the report ``dances around the key issues'' and he
would ask Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of the House Energy
and Commerce Committee, to hold a hearing on the SEC's decision to
drop the WPPSS case.
   Dingell, who had previously said it would be a ``outrage'' if
the SEC failed to act against those responsible for the default,
said in a statement that his committee would look at the SEC's
decision ``at the earliest possible time.
   ``The decision to terminate the SEC's WPPSS investigation
without enforcement is not well received by the WPPSS bondholders
or by me,'' Dingell said.
   The report concluded that the default resulted from extensive
cost overruns and construction delays at WPPSS Project No. 4 at the
Hanford nuclear reservation in southeastern Washington state and
No. 5 at Satsop, west of Olympia, Wash.
   Cost of the projects had soared from an initial estimate of
slightly over $2 billion to almost $12 billion before construction
was halted in 1981.
   Both projects were abandoned in January 1982 and in 1983 WPPSS
quit making payments on the bonds after the Washington state
Supreme Court held that the utilities' contracts with the
consortium were illegal and thus unenforceable. Without payments
from the 88 participating utilities, many in other states, WPPSS
defaulted.
   As early as 1978, the report said WPPSS recognized it could face
long-term financing problems.
   Top supply system officials told the 88 utilities participating
in the projects in late 1980 that WPPSS' ``cash flow coverage was
so low that there was almost none at times,'' the report said.
   They warned that the projects might be terminated as a result of
the cash flow situation.
   The report said the participants, also in late 1980, asked the
supply system to study the possibility of slowing down construction
or terminating the two projects.
   The request was kept confidential because of its possible impact
on the financial markets and WPPSS continued to sell bonds, more
than $400 million worth, before the projects were eventually
scrubbed, the report said.
   The report found that WPPSS also failed to adquately disclose in
the official bond statements that forecasts showed a drop in the
demand for electricity in the Northwest.
</TEXT>
