<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ChambersTrial     09-22 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chambers Trial,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Accused Detroit Crack Kingpins Go on Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Small-town youths awed by easy money were used to
build a major big-city drug empire in what a federal prosecutor
Thursday called ``A Tale of Two Cities'' _ rural Marianna, Ark.,
and cocaine-infested Detroit.
   Cocaine, processed in ``cook-up houses'' by 14-year-old girls
into crack, its smokeable form, was sold by boys, many under 16, in
crack houses run by the Chambers ring, which once accounted for
half of Detroit's crack trade, prosecutors charge.
   Four Chambers brothers _ Billy Joe, Larry Marlowe, Otis Bernard
and Willie Lee _ and 10 other people are on trial on federal
charges including cocaine conspiracy, firearms and tax evasion
counts.
   U.S. Attorney Roy Hayes said in opening arguments that Billy Joe
and Larry Chambers came from Marianna in 1982 and built their
empire on three secrets of success: recruiting, organization and
discipline.
   Hayes' first witness, former organization member Patricia
Middleton, backed his descriptions of an expanding network of
trusted lieutenants and child drug dealers, kept in line by a
no-holds-barred ``wrecking crew or beat-up crew.''
   Fourteen defendants, their attorneys, prosecutors and reporters
outnumbered spectators in a small federal courtroom for the opening
day of an expected six-week trial. Jury selection took four days.
   People passed through a metal detector to enter, and U.S.
marshals sat at both ends of the hallway in Detroit's federal
building.
   William Coonce, agent in charge of the U.S. Drug Enforcement
Administration's Detroit office, had pledged tight security to
avoid any possible reprisals against more than 50 government
witnesses.
   Forty-one cars, including Mercedes-Benz, Cadillac and Jeep
models; 250 weapons; $500,000 in cash and $500,000 in jewelry were
seized in serving 107 search warrants that led to federal
indictments, Coonce said earlier.
   Authorities described a drug ring that had as many as 400
employees, operated up to 300 crack houses and, at its peak in
1987, sold up to $3 million worth of cocaine a day.
   That ended with the indictments of 22 people in March. Four
entered guilty pleas earlier and four remain fugitives.
   Defense attorneys, in their opening arguments, attacked Hayes'
case and ``Tale of Two Cities'' analogy, saying he is relying on
shaky witnesses, many of whom are testifying to avoid prosecution
for their own offenses.
   David Harris, attorney for defendant Morris Hampton, told jurors
that by the time the trial is finished, ``You will be reading a
different book: `Much Ado About Nothing.'''
   Middleton, who was to take the stand again Friday, said she made
money pickups for the organization for about six months under
threats from Larry Chambers that the man she lived with would be
hurt.
   She said she saw crack cocaine made and sold, saw organization
members get paid up to $800 a week and saw people beaten who
crossed the Chambers brothers. ``I got pulled into it. That's not
me,'' said Middleton, who finally went to police and who testified
in return for immunity from prosecution.
   She pointed out Eric Lamar Wilkins in the courtroom, identifying
him as a ``wrecking crew'' member she knew as Fats. She said she
once saw him carry a body out of an apartment building where the
organization sold crack and put it in a garbage bin in a field
across the street.
</TEXT>
