<1ST_LINE>u w AM-SovietDissident 1stLd-Writethru a0757 09-22 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Dissident, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0757,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shevardnadze Hears Appeal From Armenian Seeking To Visit Dying
Mother</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: UPDATES throughout with additional details, including
protestor running into the street, being wrestled to the ground by
security agents, additional quote from Shevardnadze</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze
was stopped as he left the State Department on Thursday to hear an
appeal from an Armenian dissident who wants to visit his ailing
mother.
   Amvarsam Khlgatian, 61, had been waiting for two hours across
the street carrying a placard that read, ``Gorbachev, Let Me Visit
My Dying Mother,'' while Shevardnadze met inside with Secretary of
State George P. Shultz.
   As the motorcade started for the Soviet embassy, Khlgatian
dashed into the street carrying his placard. The motorcade stopped
and startled security agents wrestled Khlgatian to the ground.
   Shevardnadze left his limousine to talk to the demonstrator for
a few minutes.
   ``He said, `Don't worry, I`ll take care of it','' Khlgatian said
afterward. ``But he can do nothing. It's up to the KGB.''
   Khlgatian said he made a similar appeal to Shevardnadze in New
York a few months ago ``and he said the same thing.''
   The protester said he was exiled from the Soviet Union in 1979
after serving 15 years in labor camps for attempting to escape to
the West. He said he works as a machinist in New York.
   Khlgatian gave Shevardnadze a leaflet in which he described his
mother as 80 years old and fatally ill. It said General Secretary
Mikhail S. Gorbachev, despite promises of humanization, had kept
him from visiting her in Yerevan, the Armenian capital.
   ``For me, no matter who was and who is on the top, there wasn't
and isn't justice on the bottom,'' the leaflet said. It concluded
with an appeal for help.
   Later, returning for another session with Secretary of State
George P. Shultz, the Soviet foreign minister said he had never met
the demonstrator before.
   Asked about his appeal, Shevardnadze said: ``I am looking into
it. ... This is the human approach.''
</TEXT>
