<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-22 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Summer Goes into Overtime on Gulf Coast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The northern border states had a chilly afternoon Thursday, but
summer remained in full throttle across the Gulf Coast region, even
as fall officially began at 3:29 p.m. EDT.
   Temperatures of 90 to 95 degrees with high humidity extended
across Florida Alabama and the lower Mississippi Valley to eastern
portions of Kansas, Oklahoma and Texas.
   A cooler air mass along the Canadian border kept afternoon
temperatures in the 50s and 60s in northern states.
   Dividing the two air masses, a frontal system extended across
Illinois, Iowa, the central Plains and the central Rockies. Showers
and thunderstorms were scattered to the north of the front from the
southern Great Lakes to the upper Mississippi Valley.
   The strongest thunderstorms early Thursday afternoon were
developing over northern Iowa and in parts of southern Wisconsin
and northern Illinois. A few showers also occurred over the
northern and central Plains, Mississippi and Florida.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included
about a half-inch at Milwaukee and at Muskegon, Mich.; and about a
third of an inch at Lansing, Mich.; Madison, Wis.; and Grand
Rapids, Mich..
   Across the front in the central Plains, there were sharp
temperature contrasts. At 2 p.m. CDT, Lincoln, Neb., had 67 degrees
while Topeka, Kan., about 150 miles away, had 93 degrees.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 47
degrees at Port Angeles, Wash., to 95 degrees at Jacksonville Naval
Air Station in Florida and Fort Polk, La. The low in the nation
Thursday morning was 22 degrees at Truckee, Calif.
   For Friday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from New England across the northern and central Appalachians, the
Ohio Valley and southern Missouri to Oklahoma. Showers and
thunderstorms should be most numerous in northern New England and
portions of New York state and western Pennsylvania. Widely
scattered showers and thunderstorms were expected in central and
southern Florida and from the central Rockies to the central high
Plains. Light rain was predicted near the Washington and Oregon
coast.
   High temperatures were forecast to be in the 70s and 80s across
most of the nation. Highs should be in the 90s in much of Oklahoma,
Texas, the lower Mississippi and Tennessee Valleys, the Gulf Coast
states, the southern Atlantic Coastal states and in the desert
Southwest. Temperatures should only reach the 60s in the Pacific
Northwest and from northern Minnesota to northern Michigan and in
Maine.
</TEXT>
