<HEAD>Precede JERUSALEM</HEAD>
<HEAD>Troops Wound 24 Palestinian Rioters; Cement Hurled At Rabin</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-4 UPDATING Palestinian casualties. Picks up 4th
graf pvs, Also Thursday ...; SUBS grafs 9-10, Twelve Palestinians
... with 3 grafs of detail. Picks up 11th graf pvs, Rabin credited
... with minor editing to trim. ADDS byline</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHAN YUNIS, Occupied Gaza Strip (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops fired live
ammunition and plastic bullets to put down widespread Palestinian
demonstrations Thursday, including an attack by masked, ax-wielding
youths. Twenty-four Palestinians were wounded, Arab hospital
officials said.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin escaped injury during a tour of
the Gaza Strip town of Khan Yunis when a Palestinian assailant
hurled a chunk of cement from a nearby rooftop. Soldiers rushed to
the site but made no arrests.
   Rabin said mass arrests of grass-roots activists in Gaza
succeeded in curbing large-scale riots, but added: ``Have we
succeeded in bringing stone throwing to a standstill? Not yet.''
   Rabin said he did not see the rock hurled Thursday but said
about 80 percent of the violence in Gaza involved stone-throwing.
   Also Thursday, the army said four soldiers would face trial in
the beating death of an elderly Palestinian man, Khader Al Tarazi,
in Gaza's Jabaliya refugee camp.
   Israel radio said they were to be charged with manslaughter. It
said the soldiers struck the man with clubs after they broke into
his home Aug. 22 to arrest Palestinian youths suspected of throwing
stones.
   In the West Bank city of Nablus, dozens of Palestinian youths
marched through the casbah, or market, chanting anti-Israeli
slogans, waving Palestinian flags and holding pictures of PLO chief
Yasser Arafat, an army spokesman said.
   The youths wore Arab headscarves wrapped around their faces and
garbage bags over their clothes to hide their identities.
   They attacked troops with rocks and axes. Soldiers responded
with plastic bullets and live ammunition, an army spokeswoman said.
   Sixteen Palestinians were wounded in the clash, including a
12-year-old shot in the right hand and two 16-year-olds hit in the
stomach, officials at Nablus' Al Ittihad Hospital said. They said
four other Palestinians were wounded in clashes in villages near
Nablus.
   Other Arab hospital officials said four Palestinians were
wounded in the Gaza Strip, including a 13-year-old boy who was shot
in the chest and rushed to Tel Aviv's Tel Hashomer hospital in
serious condition.
   Acording to the army and to a military spokesman, 11
Palestinians were wounded in Nablus and nearby Burka village and
three were wounded in Gaza, including one listed in serious
condition.
   Rabin credited the use of plastic bullets against stone throwers
for a recent upsurge in casualties and said they reduced violence
in the territories.
   According to army orders, troops can fire plastic bullets at the
legs of stone throwers even if soldiers' lives are not in danger.
   Unlike live ammunition, Israeli officials say plastic bullets
are not generally lethal when fired at a distance of 20 yards or
more.
   Rabin also said Israel would never relinquish control over the
occupied territories to the United Nations before peace
negotiations as demanded by Arafat last week in France.
   ``I would like to clarify that all the PLO talk about the
possibility that some international entity will come here is mere
chatter,'' Rabin said.
   A think tank, the independent Jerusalem Center for Public
Affairs, on Thursday reported 191,700 Jews live on captured Arab
land, about two-thirds in Israeli-annexed Arab east Jerusalem.
   After the 1967 war, Israel occupied the West Bank and Gaza Strip
and annexed Arab east Jerusalem.
   Also Thursday, six Americans whose passports were seized by the
army for allegedly participating in an anti-Israeli demonstration
said they refused to submit to Israeli questioning.
   ``We have neither committed or been charged with a crime,'' said
one of the Americans, Bill Doares of New York.
   A Foreign Ministry official said the six, who are on a tour
sponsored by a pro-Palestinian lobby group in San Francisco, were
``very active'' in an illegal demonstration in the West Bank town
of Ramallah.
   The Americans contend they were observing a march by Palestinian
women from a distance when their passports were seized Monday.
</TEXT>
