<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 1949EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-DebatePanel     09-22 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Debate Panel,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, Dukakis Camps Agree On Debate Panel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The presidential campaigns of Democrat Michael
Dukakis and Republican George Bush on Thursday settled their
squabble over the composition of the panel of journalists for their
Sunday night debate.
   Janet Brown, a spokeswoman for the Commission on Presidential
Debates, a group set up by both major political parties to organize
the debate, said the agreement was reached early Thursday evening.
   Jim Lehrer of public television's ``The McNeil-Lehrer Report''
will serve as moderator for the Sunday showdown in Winston-Salem,
N.C., Ms. Brown said.
   The panel of three journalists will be anchorman Peter Jennings
of ABC News, Anne Groer of The Orlando Sentinal and John Mashek of
The Atlanta Constitution, she said.
   The camps have not yet resolved who will serve on the panel for
the second debate next month in Los Angeles, Ms. Brown said.
   The resolution came a day after the two camps agreed that the
candidates will use lecterns of different heights for the debate.
   As for the panel of journalists, Dukakis aides had originally
suggested that it consist of the anchors from ABC, NBC, CBS and CNN.
   The Bush camp said that would be unfair to print journalists and
it submitted to the commission a list of 10 reporters it said it
would accept as members of the panel.
   Meanwhile, the Fox Broadcasting Co. announced that it will
broadcast the debate on a delayed basis. The network's 122
affiliated stations will show the debate in its entirety at 11
p.m., following regular Sunday night programming.
</TEXT>
