<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 2039EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Salvador     09-22 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Lift Transport Ban Then Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels lifted a
crippling transport ban on Thursday, then killed at least 15
soldiers in an attack on an army post with mortars and
catapult-launched dynamite, officials said.
   Eleven guerrillas were killed and 11 soldiers were wounded in
the attack in eastern Morazan province, according to a communique
issued by the Armed Forces Press Office.
   The raid lasted two to three hours and appeared to be one of the
most successful guerrilla operations in recent months.
   Marxist-led rebels of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation
Front have fought the the U.S.-backed centrist government for
nearly nine years. About 65,000 people, mostly civilians, have been
killed.
   Lt. Salvador Gonzalez said the attack began at 1 a.m. (3 a.m.
EDT) with rebels firing mortar rounds and charges of TNT into a
communications post on Avocado Hill, north of Corinto, 120 miles
northeast of San Salvador.
   Gonzalez, spokesman for the 3rd Army Brigade, spoke by telephone
from San Miguel, headquarters for military operations in the
eastern third of this small Central American country.
   He said the rebels used catapults, similar to those used in
medieval times, to launch explosives into the base defended by
about 50 men. The guerrillas then attacked with rifle fire, he said.
   The raid began an hour after the end of a guerrilla-imposed road
traffic ban that paralyzed most transportation nationwide since
Monday. In lifting the ban, the rebels called on supporters to step
up sabotage of vehicles that ignored the measure.
   The guerrillas also stepped up sabotaging power transmission
lines in several of El Salvador's 14 provinces.
   Bus and truck traffic returned to normal during morning rush
hour. The rebels' clandestine Radio Venceremos said the ban _ the
fifth this year _ was lifted as of midnight Wednesday.
   At least three vehicles were burned during the ban, which
reduced bus and truck traffic in the capital by about 70 percent.
Traffic on provincial highways was almost completely paralyzed.
   Some buses and trucks that operated since Monday covered their
license plates trying to avoid reprisals.
   The guerrillas blew up about 35 utility posts or high-tension
wire towers after the transport ban began, military sources said.
Four eastern provinces were without electricity early Thursday
because of overnight sabotage.
</TEXT>
