<1ST_LINE>u a AM-GangRape 1stLd-Writethru a0726 09-22 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gang Rape, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0726,0659</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Testifies She Screamed, Resisted</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 5th graf `She testified' with with 7 grafs to UPDATE
with cross-examination. Picks up 6th graf: `The woman ...; DELETES
outdated 8th graf, `The defense ...; Note contents throughout;
grafs 14-20, `The woman ... may be offensive to some readers.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tearful 19-year-old woman hugging a
stuffed animal broke down on the witness stand Thursday while
testifying that a group of men took turns raping her on the hood of
a car as she tried to resist.
   ``I was screaming and telling him to stop,'' she said Thursday
of 23-year-old Orlando Garza, the first of 10 men indicted in the
case to stand trial. ``He was holding my legs. I was trying to push
him off.''
   Garza is being tried in District Court in Duval County on a
charge of sexual assault. He also faces a charge of aggravated
kidnapping.
   Later during her testimony, the woman was overcome with tears
and said she was about to faint. Counselors from Crisis Services of
Corpus Christi escorted her from the small courtroom packed with a
standing-room-only crowd of about 150.
   She resumed testifying Thursday afternoon, and faced
cross-examination by defense attorney Albert Pena, who is
attempting to show that the woman was involved in an affair with
the defendant and was a consenting sexual partner that night.
   The woman testified she had never been romantically involved
with Garza.
   Pena asked the woman if she was drunk the night of the alleged
gang rape, and she responded that she drank only half a beer.
   Pena asked why she waited several hours to report the incident
to the police. ``Because we didn't have a phone and I didn't know
where to go,'' she said.
   ``How many other times did Orlando Garza rape you?'' Pena asked.
   She testified earlier that Garza had raped her at her house
three days before the gang rape, but that she had been afraid to
tell anyone, including her husband.
   The woman, a mother of two, said the gang rape began while she
walked a short distance home from a relative's home about midnight
on March 26, after her husband had gone to a party.
   During the walk, she said, she declined to ``go riding'' with
Garza and three other men indicted in the case, and, ``They grabbed
me and pushed me in the car.'' She said Garza and the others were
her neighbors in this South Texas town of 5,000 people.
   The men took her north of town, outside a shed where an illegal
cockfight was taking place, the woman testified.
   The woman said Garza stayed in the back seat with her and forced
her to perform oral sex on him, while the others went to see the
roosters fight.
   ``I was trying to pull myself up, but I couldn't because his
hands were real heavy and he was pushing me down,'' she said.
   After that, she said Corando Perez walked back to the car and
told Garza, ``to save him some.''
   Perez, 26, of San Diego, also faces sexual assault and
aggravated kidnapping trials in connection with the alleged gang
rape.
   Perez pulled her head by the hair and forced her to perform oral
sex while he stood outside the car, she said.
   Then she said he climbed in the back seat and told her, ``You're
going to like this,'' before forcing her to have anal intercourse.
   The woman named at least two other men who she said took turns
raping and and sodomizing her simultaneously.
   Jose Carlos Briones, 29, also facing a sexual assault charge,
only fondled her, she said, because he was impotent. Briones
testified for the prosecution ealier in the trial, and was offered
a recommendation for probation in return for his testimony.
</TEXT>
