<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush-PoliceUnion 2ndLd-Writethru a0750-a0724 09-22 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-Police Union, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0750-a0724,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Comes to Boston to Accept Patrolmen's Endorsement</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Patrolmen's throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush came to his rival's
back yard Thursday to accept the endorsement of the Boston Police
Patrolmen's Association, New England's largest police union.
   It was the second visit by the Republican presidential nominee
to Boston this month.
   The vote was viewed by Democratic presidential nominee Michael
Dukakis as ``personally devastating,'' according to the attorney
for the union.
   As Dukakis planned a hasty counter-rally outside his governor's
office at the Statehouse, Bush visited a restaurant in East Boston
and criticized Dukakis as being soft on crime.
   ``Who was it said that the police aren't there when you need
them?'' said Bush as he stood flanked by some 50 patrolmen, all of
them elected representatives of the police union.
   ``I'm here to receive this endorsement but also to make it clear
that I'm the one in this race who wants to strengthen law
enforcement,'' Bush told the room full of reporters, about 150
supporters and police. ``Our first priority must be to keep the
criminals away from the people who want to live in peace and
safety.''
   Two hours after the mid-day rally, Dukakis surrounded himself
with scores of law enforcement officials, top elected officials and
New York Gov. Mario Cuomo. Dukakis said: ``We're here today to
investigate a felony: assault and battery on the truth.
   ``What George Bush is doing to the truth in this campaign is a
crime. We're here to give George Bush what Joe Friday used to ask
for: the facts, ma'am, just the facts.''
   The Bush rally stemmed from a 51-0 vote by elected officers of
the patrolmen's association Wednesday to endorse Bush for
president. It was not the first time the union has endorsed a
Republican. In 1980 and 1984 the association supported Ronald
Reagan and in 1984 it endorsed Republican Ray Shamie in his
unsuccessful Senate bid against John Kerry.
   But Dukakis himself, in a conversation with union attorney Frank
McGee on Wednesday afternoon, said according to McGee that the
union endorsement would do him great harm.
   ``I hope these guys realize that if they go ahead and do this,
that I would regard this as personally devastating to me,'' McGee
quoted Dukakis as saying.
   In his rally Thursday, Dukakis said that unlike Bush, he
supports providing federal assistance to local law enforcement
agencies.
   And Dukakis countered criticism of his past support for
furloughs for first-degree murderers by saying that the Reagan-Bush
administration last year gave some 16,000 furloughs, some as long
as 40 days, to convicted drug pushers.
   Patrolmen's Association President Robert Guiney told the crowd
at the Bush rally that Dukakis ``is no friend of police.''
   ``During his term as governor, he has presided over a revolving
door criminal justice system,'' Guiney said. ``We are ever mindful
of his total opposition to capital punishment, especially in view
of our recent tragic loss of three outstanding officers who paid
the supreme sacrifice in the line of duty.''
   One of the patrolmen also criticized Dukakis' absence in the
past year from the funerals of those three officers killed on the
job.
   Earlier this month Bush came to Boston Harbor to spotlight what
he called Dukakis' tolerance of delay in cleaning up polluted
Boston Harbor.
   Dukakis has been endorsed by the Massachusetts Police
Association, the Massachusetts Police Chiefs Association, the state
district attorneys and the 14 county sheriffs, two of whom are
Republican. Dukakis has also won the endorsement of a number of
out-of-state law enforcement groups.
   The Boston police force is the largest in New England as is its
patrolmen's union, which has 1,621 members. Endorsements are made
by 54 patrolmen who are elected representatives. Of those, 51
attended the Wednesday night session and all voted for Bush.
</TEXT>
