<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HurricaneHelene 1stLd-Writethru a0779 09-22 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hurricane Helene, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0779,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hurricane Helene Strengthens, But Still No Threat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to UPDATE with 10:30 p.m. position, track.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hurricane Helene's winds strengthened to 110 mph in
the mid-Atlantic on Thursday, but forecasters said the storm was
still no threat to land.
   At 10:30 p.m. EDT, the center of the 250-mile wide storm was at
latitude 14.1 north and longitude 44.3 west, or about 1,020 miles
east of the Caribbean island of Barbados.
   Helene was moving west-northwest at 10 mph and was expected to
continue that track and speed through Thursday.
   ``This is a very good hurricane _ it's already something to
reckon with,'' National Hurricane Center forecaster Miles Lawrence
said. ``But the currents suggest it is going to turn to the north _
it's just too early to speculate.''
   Air currents from a low pressure trough over the ocean may draw
Helene northward into the open Atlantic, away from the Caribbean
islands and North America, Lawrence said.
   Helene showed signs of northwest movement by late Thursday. But
if it heads into the eastern Caribbean, islands could be affected
by early next week, said Lawrence.
   In the meantime, Helene was growing stronger and more organized
as it moved westward across the Atlantic from its spawning grounds
near the the Cape Verde Islands off the African coast.
   Helene is the eighth named storm of the 1988 Atlantic hurricane
season. Storms become hurricanes when sustained winds reach a
minimum 74 mph.
   Of the season's three previous hurricanes, Gilbert swept across
the Caribbean and Mexico, killing hundreds, but the other two,
Florence and Debby, caused only minor damage in Mexico and the U.S.
Gulf Coast.
</TEXT>
