<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua-UN 1stLd-Writethru a0810 09-22 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-UN, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0810,0574</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega Cancels U.N. Trip Over Delay In U.S. Visas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with State Department comment,
background on earlier expulsions. Pickup 5th graf `The
Sandinista...'; SUBS final two grafs 11-12 `A State...Sandinista
government'' with other background.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega cancelled on
Thursday his scheduled visit to the United Nations because the U.S.
government delayed visas for about two dozen members of his
delegation, a government official announced.
   ``This arbitrary and illegal attitude constitutes a denial of
Nicaraguan rights,'' Deputy Foreign Minister Victor Hugo Tinoco
said in making the announcement at a news conference.
   On Wednesday, Nicaragua's U.N. Ambassador Alejandro Serrano
Caldera said the State Department was blocking visas for most
Nicaraguans who wanted to attend Ortega's speech to the General
Assembly in New York, including Ortega's wife and children.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Rudi Boone said he was
not aware of Ortega's cancellation of the trip. ``We have not seen
those reports yet,'' he said.
   Asked if the visas might be expedited to allow the trip, Boone
said, ``I could not say.''
   A State Department official in Washington earlier denied the
administration was blocking or delaying the visas.
   Earlier this month the State Department criticized the leftist
Nicaragua government for refusing to allow the United States to
replace Ambassador Richard Melton and seven other diplomats the
Sandinista government expelled on July 11. The Sandinista
government accused the diplomats of trying to destabilize the
country.
   The United States in turn expelled Nicaraguan Ambassador Carlos
Tunnerman and seven of his colleagues.
   Ortega family members, his doctor, chief of protocol and many of
his senior advisers were among the 22 to 25 Nicaraguans whose visas
were not processed in time for the Sept. 28 address, Serrano said.
   The Sandinista government protested ``the unjustified delay'' in
issuing the visas, according to a Foreign Ministry communique
broadcast over state-run radio Wednesday night.
   It said Nicaragua's representatives to the U.N. and the
Organization of American States had been instructed to ``intercede
before the State Department so that without major delays the visas
in question are granted.''
   The statement said the state of U.S.-Nicaraguan relations should
not be a factor in the issuance of the visas.
   ``In adopting this type of attitude, the United States clearly
ignores those commitments it has assumed as the host country of
international organizations, specifically violating existing
stipulations in the agreement between the United Nations and the
United States relative to the site of the United Nations,'' the
Foreign Ministry statement said.
   The State Department told the Nicaraguan mission that Ortega and
some senior Nicaraguan officials would have received their visas in
time for their scheduled arrival Friday, Serrano said on Wednesday.
   But he said the State Department also told the Nicaraguan
Mission that the other 22 to 25 visas would not be decided until
Oct. 4, a week after Ortega was to speak to the 159-member General
Assembly.
   The United States since 1981 has supported rebels seeking to
overthrow Nicaragua's Sandinista government.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman has said that in
addition to refusing replacements for Melton and the seven other
expelled diplomats, Nicaragua is not issuing visas to U.S.
diplomats assigned to replace envoys being routinely reassigned or
to personnel seeking to visit the embassy on official business.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
