<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 0256EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   09-22 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0527</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer prices rose at a 5.2 percent annual
rate in August as a result of higher food, shelter and gasoline
prices, the government reports.
   Food and beverage prices rose 0.5 percent for the month,
compared with 0.9 percent in July, when the Labor Department said
the greatest impact of the dry weather in the Farm Belt began
reaching consumer pocketbooks.
   But gasoline prices jumped a whopping 3 percent in August, the
biggest increase in 12 months, the department said Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans' personal income increased only half
as fast as inflation in August, the government says in a new report.
   The numbers released Wednesday by the Commerce Department are
consistent with other recent government reports showing the economy
slowed in August from its vigorous pace during the first half of
the year.
   Personal income grew 0.2 percent, while personal consumption
spending rose 0.5 percent. A price index tied to the personal
income report rose 0.4 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Senate Banking Committee
says taxpayers will have to spend at least $20 billion to bail out
the savings industry.
   ``The cost of the S&L bailout will top the combined cost of all
previous federal bailouts in history,'' including aid to New York
City and Chrysler Corp., Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis., said in a
speech Wednesday prepared for delivery on the Senate floor.
   He said that even if Congress spends the $20 billion, the
healthy portion of the industry would have to contribute another
$30 billion over the next few years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brazil will sign an unprecedented $82 billion
financial package with its international commercial bank creditors.
   The deal to be signed Thursday was billed by Citicorp as a
possible landmark in the Third World debt crisis. A preliminary
accord was reached in July.
   The package includes $5.2 billion in new money to help Brazil
cover its external financing needs for 1987, 1988, and the first
half of 1989.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A South African mining conglomerate has launched
the largest takeover bid in British history, with a $4.9 billion
offer for Consolidated Gold Fields PLC.
   Consolidated, which controls 8 percent of the world's annual
gold production, quickly rejected the bid Wednesday.
   The offer by Minorco SA for the 71 percent of Consolidated that
it doesn't already own sparked concerns about a South African
monopoly in the gold mining business.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp. has filed suit in federal
court to block Roy E. Disney's Shamrock Holdings Inc. from gaining
control of the company.
   The suit filed Tuesday in Delaware seeks to prohibit Burbank,
Calif.-based Shamrock from acquiring any more shares of Polaroid
stock or attempting another tender offer and asks that the company
divest itself of Polaroid stock it now owns.
   The suit was filed after Polaroid urged its stockholders to
reject as inadequate a sweetened takeover bid by Shamrock that
values the company at $2.6 billion.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
