<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   09-22 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0549</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Multimillionaire brothers Nelson Bunker Hunt and
William Herbert Hunt each have filed for personal bankruptcy
protection to avoid having to post a $225 million bond required for
appealing a federal jury verdict against them.
   A Hunt spokesman said Wednesday the brothers decided to seek
Chapter 11 federal bankruptcy protection from creditors to keep
Minpeco SA, which won the verdict against them, from beginning
foreclosure proceedings on their personal assets until the appeal
could be made.
   The jury on Aug. 20 in New York ordered the two Hunts and
brother Lamar Hunt to pay more than $130 million in damages for
conspiring to corner the world's silver market in the late 1970s,
ruining the investments of Minpeco.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines' Machinists union overwhelmingly
has voted down a cost-cutting proposal described by a company
spokeswoman as ``our best offer.''
   There were 7,596 ``no'' ballots, or 98.2 percent, against the
offer that union local President Charles Bryan said would cut
salaries by 56 percent. The tally released Wednesday also showed
nine void votes and 90 ballots favoring the offer.
   The union represents about 9,500 mechanics and ground-support
workers, Bryan said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S.-Soviet venture plans to open 18
print shops and a central printing plant in the Soviet Union,
taking advantage of a recent liberalization of publishing laws.
   The profit-oriented venture will bring the first-ever
publishing, copying, printing and computer services to Soviet
private citizens, according to an announcement Wednesday at the
Soviet Consulate.
   The experimental venture plans to start in Moscow in January,
Leningrad next summer and Kiev a few months later.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment group wants to sell stock in the
nation's largest legal brothel.
   Peter Perry, a Reno lawyer who heads the group along with real
estate developer Donald Clough, said Wednesday his investors hoped
to raise $23.3 million by selling stock.
   This is the second attempt to raise the money needed to buy the
Mustang Ranch through a stock sale. A proposed sale by another
group fell through in 1985.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new four-wheel-drive vehicle and a car are
being brought to the United States in the coming model year by
American Suzuki Motor Corp., stung briefly by reports that its
Samurai vehicle was prone to flipping.
   In addition to the new Sidekick and Swift lines introduced
Wednesday, the Japanese automaker will again sell the Samurai
through its 200 dealers in 39 states.
   Sales of the Samurai plummeted in June after an attack by
Consumers Union, but dealer incentives led to record sales by
August.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were little changed Wednesday. The Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials edged up 3.02 to 2,090.50, but declining
issues slightly outnumbered advances on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Gold prices tumbled worldwide, falling through the
$400-a-troy-ounce level in the United States for the first time
since early last year. The dollar rose slightly against major
foreign currencies.
   Bond prices edged higher.
   In commodities futures trading, other precious metals also
declined, while agricultural products were mixed and oil rose
slightly.
</TEXT>
