<DOCNO> AP880922-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 0259EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     09-22 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inflation Stays At 5.2 Percent In August, Government Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Higher rents and gasoline prices largely replaced food as the
sharpest spurs to higher prices that kept inflation at an
annualized rate of 5.2 percent during August, the government said.
   Separate goverment reports also released Wednesday showed a
modest rise in personal income and a drop in housing construction.
The news had little impact on the financial markets, where stocks,
bonds, oil prices and the dollar were little changed.
   Trading was more dramatic in precious metals. Gold prices
tumbled below the $400-a-troy-ounce level in the United States for
the first time since early last year. On the Commodity Exchange in
New York, gold for current delivery fell $6.90 a troy ounce to
close at $398.40, the first time the metal closed below $400 since
Feb. 18, 1987, when it fetched $392.70.
   Analysts have attributed the recently depressed gold market to
growing investor disillusionment with bullion as a hedge against
inflation.
   In its report on inflation, the Labor Department said food and
beverage prices rose 0.5 percent in August as the effects of the
drought in the Farm Belt began to ease. Prices jumped 0.9 percent
in July when the greatest impact of the dry weather began hitting
consumer pocketbooks.
   But gasoline prices jumped a whopping 3 percent in August, the
biggest increase in 12 months, and despite lower utility bills and
home energy costs, shelter expenses rose 0.6 percent in August,
their largest increase in seven months.
   But analysts agreed there was nothing alarming in the numbers.
   ``The scare that we're off to the races or that an inflationary
sprial is under way has not materialized and it won't
materialize,'' said Larry Chimerine of the WEFA Group, a Bala
Cynwyd, Pa., consulting firm.
   Separately, the Commerce Department said personal income rose a
modest 0.2 percent in August, the smallest gain in eight months,
although much of it represented declines in both farm subsidies and
farm income. Wages and salaries were up just 0.3 percent.
   After adjustments for inflation, the government said, Americans'
average weekly earnings fell 1.3 percent in August. The decline in
workers' buying power was the third in the past four months and the
worst since the government began keeping tabs on real earnings in
1964.
   The decrease stemmed from a 0.9 percent drop in the average
number of hours worked, from 34.9 hours to 34.6 hours, and the 0.4
percent hike in consumer prices. Average hourly earnings were
$9.24, unchanged from July.
   Another Commerce Department report showed housing construction
fell 3.3 percent last month, with a steep drop in new apartments
outweighing a small gain in single-family home building. For the
first eight months of this year, housing starts are running 9.9
percent below the same period in 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880922-0194 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 0303EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     09-22 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The oil futures market remains cautious in
advance of next week's meeting of the OPEC price monitoring
committee, analysts say.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the November contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, settled
19 cents higher at $14.56 a barrel Wednesday. Tuesday was the last
day of the crude contract for October delivery. Other contract
month were mixed at the close.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for October delivery gained 0.92
cent to close at 45.35 cents a gallon, while other contract months
also closed higher.
   The October wholesale heating oil contract lost 0.23 cent to
settle at 41.09 cents a gallon. Other heating oil contracts settled
mixed on the day.
   Skepticism about the outcome of the upcoming meeting of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries' pricing committee
has made traders relucant to sell, analysts said. The meeting is
scheduled for Sunday and Monday.
   ``This is a market that sees considerable storm clouds on the
horizon,'' said Stephen Smith, a research analyst with Bear,
Stearns & Co. ``Crude prices are holding up probably because
there's some chance that OPEC can pull a rabbit out of the hat.''
   There is speculation that such a meeting could lead to a
gathering of all 13 OPEC members and a possible reduction in the
cartel's oil output. Recent reports have suggested that several
OPEC countries are producing far above their assigned quotas,
helping to flood world markets with oil and keeping prices weak.
   Nevertheless, near-month contracts for crude oil and gasoline
continued to gain strength from falling inventories in the face of
strong demand. Oil brokers said demand is up nearly 2 percent from
last year.
   The American Petroleum Institute reported Tuesday that U.S.
crude oil stocks were down by 6.212 million barrels in the week
ended Sept. 16, while gasoline stocks fell by 2.58 million barrels.
   Analysts said the fall in gasoline inventories stemmed from last
week's hurricane in the Gulf of Mexico and the temporary shutdown
of several refineries in the area.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880922-0195 </DOCNO>
