<DOCNO> AP880922-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 0329EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-IMF-WorldBank Bjt   09-22 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-IMF-World Bank, Bjt,0512</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Third World Governments Seek More Aid At World Bank-IMF Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of 24 Third World governments get
together today to discuss ways to win more help from richer
countries, as formal sessions begin for the joint annual meeting of
the World Bank and International Monetary Fund.
   Informal meetings have been going on all week during the arrival
of delegates from the 151 member governments, as well as
representatives of banks and industrial companies.
   At the top of most governments' concerns is the burden of
interest payments on developing countries' debt, due to reach $1.2
billion by the end of this year.
   In New York the biggest debtor _ Brazil, which owes about $120
billion _ is to sign a new $82 billion agreement with its creditor
banks, including $5.2 billion in new loans to help the nation cover
its obligations for 1987, 1988 and the first half of next year.
Brazil suspended interest payments on its debt in February 1987,
but officially ended the moratorium on Wednesday.
   But new money lent by banks goes largely to pay interest on old
debt. Third World governments will ask wealthier governments, and
the bank and fund, to increase their lending.
   Later in the week, the wealthier countries will meet on their
own problems as well as those of the Third World. The most
important session will be by the ``Group of Seven,'' comprising the
United States, Japan, West Germany, France, Britain, Canada and
Italy.
   The Third World debt problem has been getting much vocal
sympathy in Berlin. A ``Counter-Congress'' consisting of critics of
the World Bank and IMF also opens on Thursday.
   On Wednesday, former West German Chancellor Willy Brandt
appealed for debt reductions for developing nations. With President
Reagan's administration taking the lead, the World Bank and IMF
have resisted such pleas as counterproductive. The United States
has the largest share of voting strength in both entities.
   Critics of the IMF and World Bank say the need to make interest
payments, and conditions set by the fund and bank for new loans,
compel governments to raise prices and to reduce wages. Fund and
bank officials argue that such policies are needed to prevent worse
suffering, and to put the debtor countries into better position to
borrow again.
   Mobilizing criticism here has been the left-wing Green party,
whichhas representatives in the Berlin legislature and the West
German parliament.
   The group, which says it disapproves of violence as a political
method, plans a mass demonstration in Berlin on Sunday, when it
hopes to bring 40,000 protesters into the streets.
   The Greens also have taken the lead in organizing a ``Permanent
Peoples' Tribunal'' to meet Monday and accuse the bank and fund of
damaging the environment and violating the United Nations charter.
   Spokesmen for the IMF and World Bank say they will furnish
information to the organizers but will not send representatives to
appear at the four-day session.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880922-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 0332EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-NewBuicks     09-22 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-New Buicks,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Buick Introduces '89s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Buick says its 1989 line further splits
a perception of a few years ago that it was difficult to tell the
automobiles from Oldsmobiles or other General Motors Corp. cars.
   ``When you looked at the (Buick and Oldsmobile) cars on the road
a year or two ago, there wasn't much difference,'' Buick General
Manager Ed Mertz said Wednesday. ``But they're going one way and
we're going another.''
   Buick introduced its new lineup of cars for the coming model
year on Wednesday, saying the decline in the GM division's sales
has ended.
   Oldsmobile, Cadillac and Chevrolet introduced their 1989
versions earlier this month.
   In the early 1980s, GM was criticized for making too many cars
that looked too much alike. But recently, including this month's
introductions of 1989 models, executives from each of GM's car
divisions have stressed the differences between their cars and
those of other divisions.
   Chevrolet has been seen as aiming its new cars, especially
through the new Geo line, at economy-conscious buyers, and
Oldsmobile is shifting its sights to a market that is younger and
more interested in high technology than the segment traditionally
associated with its cars.
   Mertz predicted at a news conference that Buick's sales in the
'89 model year would show slight gains from the previous model year.
   ``We have arrested the (sales) downturn,'' he said. ``November
was the low.''
   He speculated final figures for the model year due early next
month should show Buick held 5.7 percent of the market. That share,
Mertz said, should rise to 6 percent to 6.5 percent during the
coming year.
   Much of the sales gain is expected from the Riviera, a two-door
coupe being lengthened by 11 inches in 1989, mainly in the rear of
the car, to about 16{ feet.
   ``We see an 18,000 to 22,000 range in '89, about twice that of
the current year,'' Mertz said of Riviera sales.
   Buick's two-seater Reatta, with a base price of $26,700, will
return for 1989 after its introduction last January. Buick has sold
2,500 of the cars and production is quickening toward a 1989 goal
of 7,000 to 8,000, Mertz said.
   Reatta is the sixth-shortest but is one of the heaviest of
Buick's 16-car lineup, weighing in at 3,394 pounds. Only the
Riviera coupe and two full-size station wagons are heavier.
   Officials said Buick would continue its Skylark and Skyhawk
models, with base prices starting at $9,285, and ``We will have a
small but steady market in full-size wagons,'' Mertz said.
   In the middle of the model year, Buick will introduce its Park
Avenue Ultra, a luxury sedan with full leather interiors, multiple
seat adjustments and other features. No price has been set.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
