<1ST_LINE>r f PM-NewSuzukis     09-22 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-New Suzukis,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Samurais Coming to United States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Executives of American Suzuki Motor Corp. say the
company has recovered strongly since a private report in June
alleged that its Samurai utility vehicle was prone to flipping.
   ``I think the consumers are reassured,'' Suzuki spokesman James
Weber said at a news conference Wednesday to introduce the '89
Suzuki line of two utility vehicles and a car. ``Right now, we've
sucked the pipeline (for Samurais) dry...
   ``It just shows the consumer confidence in the vehicle,'' Weber
said of the rebound. ``I think we're stronger.''
   Weber predicted selling somewhere around 2,000 Samurais monthly
in the 1989 model year.
   Last June, Suzuki was stung by reports by Consumers Union,
publisher of Consumer Reports, that the Samurai was dangerously
prone to rolling over. The company denied the charges, but watched
its June sales plummet 63.8 percent, to 2,199 from 6,074 in May.
   But by August, aided by a major buyer incentives campaign, sales
had rebounded to 12,208 vehicles.
   This coming model year, the Samurai will be back in Suzuki's 200
dealers in 39 states, joined by two new models: the Swift
automobile and the Sidekick four-wheel-drive vehicle.
   The Swift, to be available in two models, is a companion for
Chevrolet's newly introduced Geo Metro, an economy-minded car built
by Suzuki in Japan. The Sidekick will be linked the Geo Tracker, a
four-wheel drive vehicle also built in Japan.
   In April, production of those Suzukis and Chevrolets will be
moved to Canada.
   Suzuki officials insisted Sidekick and Samurai sales should not
overlap.
   Sidekicks, they said, were aimed for an older market than were
Samurais, which are built a little more for off-road use _ a bit
shorter and narrower, but with more ground clearance than the
Sidekick.
   The Sidekick comes in a number of variations, depending on,
among other things, whether it's equipped with a 1.3- or 1.6-liter
engine and whether it has a cloth or hard top.
   Base price for the Samurai will be $8,495 and the Sidekick will
go for a base of $8,995. The Swift GLX has a base price of $7,495
and the GTi will retail for $8,995.
   Between now and April, Suzuki said, it hoped to sell 30,000
Sidekicks and 10,000 of both Swift models. Like the Samurai, the
Sidekick will be brought to the United States as a truck.
</TEXT>
