<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Polaroid-Shamrock     09-22 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Polaroid-Shamrock,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polaroid Sues To Block Shamrock Buyout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After advising its stockholders to
ignore two hostile takeover attempts, Polaroid Corp. has sued to
block Shamrock Holdings Inc.'s unwanted bid.
   The suit filed Tuesday in Delaware seeks to prohibit the
Burbank, Calif., -based Shamrock from acquiring any shares of
Polaroid stock or attempting another tender offer and asks that the
company divest itself of Polaroid stock it now owns.
   The suit was filed after Polaroid urged its stockholders to
reject as inadequate a sweetened $2.6 billion takeover bid by
Shamrock. Last month, Polaroid's board of directors turned down
Shamrock's first unsolicited offer.
   The complaint alleges Shamrock engaged in a variety of
securities law violations, including fraudulent, deceptive and
manipulative acts. The suit also claims that Shamrock failed to
disclose material information to stockholders.
   ``Polaroid is taking a more aggressive stance,'' said William
Relyea, a photography analyst with Eberstadt Fleming Inc. in New
York.
   Polaroid officials allege in the suit that Shamrock's offer to
buy Polaroid shares at $42 is ``illusory.'' They said the move
either was designed to allow Shamrock to reap a quick premium by
selling its own Polaroid stock, or to allow Shamrock to pressure
Polaroid into a merger at a price that would be detrimental to
other stockholders.
   Relyea said Polaroid may slow Shamrock down with the lawsuit,
echoing what he said was a widely-held view that Shamrock actually
may be paving the way for another company to take over Polaroid
while it makes a tidy profit.
   The suit also claims Shamrock violated the federal reporting
requirements by failing to disclose the identity of all members of
its ownership group.
   And the suit alleges Shamrock is trying to exclude the Polaroid
employee stock ownership plan from its offer, which is contrary to
federal requirements that all stockholders receive equal treatment
in a tender offer.
   Shamrock spokesman John Grimaldi said Wednesday that the company
had not seen the suit and could not comment.
   Polaroid has asked the U.S. District Court to conduct a hearing
on its request for a preliminary injunction against Shamrock's
offer before Oct. 6.
   Last month, Polaroid rejected an unsolicited offer from Shamrock
that would have paid stockholders $40 a share plus 40 percent of
the eventual award in Polaroid's $5.7 billion patent infringement
lawsuit against Eastman Kodak Co. Analysts valued the offer at
about $44 a share given a $1 billion settlement in the Kodak case.
   After advising stockholders Tuesday to reject the sweetened bid,
Polaroid also filed notice with the Securities and Exchange
Commission in Washington that it has begun preliminary negotiations
with third parties about issuing preferred stock to them, a step
that would make the company harder to take over.
   Shamrock, which is owned by the family of Roy E. Disney, nephew
of the late animator Walt Disney, says that if its bid succeeds it
would drop Polaroid's fledgling venture into 35mm film, sell most
of the company's undeveloped real estate, narrow the company's
manufacturing facilities and simplify Polaroid's research and
development activities to focus on the company's core businesses.
   The offer hinged on the invalidation of Polaroid's recent
issuance of 9.7 million shares to a new employee stock ownership
plan, a move Polaroid made early in its attempt to block Shamrock.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
