<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FarmReview-Equipment     09-22 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Review-Equipment,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Equipment Sales Down, But Cautious Optimism For 1989</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER C. KENT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAFAYETTE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financial uncertainty caused by the
drought are forcing farmers to hold off buying new machinery for
their fields, dashing hopes for a banner year in the farm equipment
industry, according to some salesmen.
   ``This year will certainly slow down next year, maybe not as
much, but there wil be a cloud hanging over us. It takes a lot of
years for a farmer to recover a loss,'' said Doug Hennessey, a
territory manager for White New Idea Farm Equipment Co., based in
Coldwater.
   ``Normally, they'll trade it in on a 3-5 year basis, and this
would've been the greatest fall in eight years. But then the
drought hit and delayed their opportunity to buy,'' said B.E.
Miller, southern Ohio marketing manager for Case IH.
   Hennessey and Miller were among approximately 500 commercial
exhibitors at the three-day Farm Science Review, which ends
Thursday. The agricultural exposition included about $40 million
worth of farm equipment.
   The number of hours a farmer uses a tractor varies, but Case's
C.L. Lephart said an average for a cash grain farmer would be about
250 hours a year. Normally, a farmer may trade that in after five
years, but now they are allowing their equipment to depreciate and
trading it in with as many as 7,000 hours on it.
   Miller said this year's drought was a particular letdown because
analysts finally were anticipating a good year after years of a
depressed farm economy.
   ``They'd finally got their debt load paid off, which would've
permitted them to come back and buy, but now...'' said Miller, his
voice trailing off.
   Lephart, Case marketing manager for northwest Ohio, said the
drought led to a new marketing plan. ``Discounts, financing,
leases. We're seeing a lot more of all of these,'' Lephart said.
   John Deere Co. parts marketing manager Bob Hothem said the
company hopes to cash in on a U.S. Department of Agriculture
projection that there will be as many as 25 million new acres to
till next year.
   While equipment sales have been slow, a different type of
machinery has moved out of the storerooms and onto the farms.
   Tillage equipment, such as field cultivators, have sold better
than usual ``because no-tillage didn't work out,'' Hennessey said,
referring to a farming method aimed at soil conservation
   ``Conventional and mechanical tillage is coming back into
play,'' Lepart said.
   Lepart and Miller think 1989 will be a better year for sales,
but say they won't be able to put profits into perspective until
all crops are harvested.
   ``There's certainly a lot of room for optimism,'' Miller said.
   The Farm Science Review, on the 992-acre Molly Caren Agriculture
Center, about 25 miles west of Columbus, included field
demonstrations and exhibits by farm equipment manufacturers and
dealers. The annual agribusiness exposition is sponsored by Ohio
State University.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
