<DOCNO> AP880922-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 0350EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-GMAdPlan     09-22 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GM Ad Plan,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>West Virginia Scuttles GM Plan To Pass On Ad Costs To Buyers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By T.J. SIMONEAUX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W. Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. has agreed to
revise an advertising plan that state authorities say would boost
car prices while illegally forcing dealers to participate,
according to Attorney General Charlie Brown.
   Separately, a group of Ohio auto dealers has sued to block a
similar advertising plan in their state.
   GM's Chevrolet Motors division planned to increase the amount
its dealer franchises pay for their cars by 1 percent _ an average
of $40 to $50 a car _ to finance a dealers association that would
run the automaker's national advertising campaigns.
   The company offered dealers who joined the association a 25
percent discount on the surcharge, but told those who did not join
that they would not receive the discount, Brown said Wednesday in
announcing the settlement.
   Under the plan, the dealers would pass on the surcharge to car
buyers. Chevrolet planned to begin the program with its September
shipments and tacked the 1 percent charge on to its dealers' bills
for this month.
   ``A lot of dealers complained about it,'' Brown said.
   Brown said he learned about the Chevrolet plan in August. Steve
Herndon, solicitor general for the attorney general's office,
investigated the plan, then informed Chevrolet that it violated
West Virginia law.
   Under the law, autmobile dealers cannot be required to
participate in a dealers association.
   ``This type of deceptive business practice is a violation of
fair trade competition, and the consumer is the ultimate victim,''
Brown said.
   ``Obviously, if GM dealers have to compete with other GM dealers
(in advertising), it means better prices for consumers,'' Herndon
said.
   The attorney general's office and Chevrolet last week negotiated
a settlement under which dealers will participate in the ad plan
only if they want, and then pay the discounted fee. Those who don't
participate will be paid an amount equivalent to the 25 percent
discount.
   Dealers did not pay the September charge, Herndon said.
   At least 27 other states have auto dealer laws similar to West
Virginia's, the attorney general said.
   Other automakers _ including Ford Motor Co. _ have tried similar
tactics, Brown said.
   In Ohio, the Ohio Automobile Dealers Association and three Ohio
dealerships sued GM and its GMC Truck and Chevrolet divisions in
U.S. District Court in Columbus, alleging a similar advertising
program in Ohio violates state law prohibiting mandatory
participation in a dealers association.
   They plaintiffs want the court to stop the program and award
them any damages allowed under state law, plus double the amount GM
has collected under the program.
   The Sept. 8 suit has not been scheduled for trial. GM has not
filed a response.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880922-0205 </DOCNO>
