<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 0929EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-US-EuropeTrade     09-22 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-US-Europe Trade,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Official Says United States, EEC Far Apart on Meat Hormones,
Airbus</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and its European
trading partners remain far apart on solving disputes over a ban on
hormone-treated meat and support for civil aircraft development, a
U.S. official said Thursday.
   But Alfred H. Kingon, the U.S. ambassador to the European
Economic Community, told a news conference that trade relations
between the United States and the 12-nation European trading bloc
are ``actually pretty good.''
   ``We have succeeded in the last year and a half of cleaning the
table of most of the troublesome trade issues that existed some two
years ago between the United States and the community,'' he said.
   Trade between the EEC and the United States will likely exceed
more than $160 billion this year, up from $145 billion in 1987 and
$131 billion in 1986, Kingon said.
   Two key disputes remaining, he said, are European enforcement of
a ban on meat from animals treated with growth hormones and U.S.
objections to government support for Airbus Industrie, a
four-nation European consortium that competes with Boeing Co. and
McDonnell Douglas Corp.
   Kingon said little progress has been made on either issue and no
resolution was in sight.
   The meat hormone dispute, he said, ``is perhaps the most
difficult problem on the table.''
   An EEC spokesman, who demanded anonymity, said, ``No new
initiative can be expected from the (community) on hormones. There
is a deadlock.''
   The EEC says it wants to ban imports of all hormone-treated meat
for health reasons. Late last year, it decided to delay
implementation of the ban until Jan. 1, 1989.
   The United States had threatened to take retaliatory action if
the ban was imposed. It contends the use of hormones to fatten
animals, which is a common practice among American farmers, is not
a health risk.
   Kingon predicted the issue would wind up in the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, an international body that solves
disputes between trading partners.
   On the Airbus issue, Kingon said negotiations were continuing.
But, he said, ``I would not want to mislead you to say we are close
to a solution because we're not.''
   A key objective of U.S.-European negotiations has been to set
``effective discipline'' on new infusions of capital and on the
conditions under which government support may be provided to future
civil aircraft programs.
   The four governments involved in the Airbus program are Britain,
France, West Germany and Spain.
   The EEC is made up of Belgium, Britain, Denmark, France,
Germany, Greece, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, Netherlands, Portugal
and Spain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
