<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 0956EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-U.S.Sugar     09-22 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-U.S. Sugar,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Seeks International Trade Inquiry On U.S. Sugar Quotas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community will
ask for an international trade inquiry into U.S. restrictions on
imports of sugar, a spokeswoman for the European Commission said.
   The Commission will make the request at a meeting Thursday of
the Council of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, the
international trade organization meeting in Uruguay and studying
ways to improve world trade relations.
   The panel will be asked to examine the EEC's contention that the
long-standing U.S. import curbs are inconsistent with international
trading rules, said the spokeswoman, who declined to be named.
   The EEC and U.S. officials had two inconclusive rounds of talks
on the issue in July and early in September, she said.
   The United States has imposed import restrictions on sugar,
dairy products, peanuts and cotton for many years ince it was
granted a waiver from international trade rules in 1955.
   The EEC contends that the protection enabled U.S. farmers to
build up their production of the commodities.
   Sugar production in the United States rose to 5.4 million tons
in 1986 from 4.2 million tons in 1955, according to the EEC.
   The spokeswoman said that the U.S. import quota for sugar in
1988 amounted to 700,000 metric tons while the EEC imported 4
million tons of sugar last year.
   The spokeswoman said that the EEC had similar complaints about
the other products covered by the waiver but is still reviewing
those cases.
   She also said that the EEC would express to the GATT Council its
concern about the U.S. trade bill which it believes to be
protectionist and potentially damaging for the Uruguay round of
international trade talks.
</TEXT>
