<HEAD>London Shares Lower At Midday On Profit-Taking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices were lower at midday Thursday, as
players took profits in the wake of two consecutive days of strong
gains.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was down 7
points, or 0.4 percent, at 1,789.8 at about 12:30 p.m.
   The index traded narrowly throughout the morning. At its best,
the index was down 3.1 points, and at its worst it lost 8.7 points.
   Volume was light to moderate, with 231.3 million shares changing
hands by midday, compared with 260.9 million shares at the same
time Wednesday.
   Sentiment was cautious ahead of Tuesday's British trade report
for August, dealers said.
   ``Until we get these trade figures out of the way, I don't think
we're going to roar away,'' said one equity salesman.
   Most of Thursday morning's trading was limited to a few
speculative stocks, dealers said.
   ``The market is at the moment really all about rumors and
takeovers,'' the salesman said. ``It's frankly pretty low quality
business.''
