<1ST_LINE>r f BC-PNC-DelawareMerger     09-22 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-PNC-Delaware Merger,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PNC Financial, Delaware Banks to Merge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   PNC Financial Corp. and the Bank of Delaware
Corp. said Thursday they plan to merge operations in an agreement
valued at $230 million.
   PNC Financial Corp. of Pittsburgh is the nation's 12th largest
bank holding company with assets of $36.8 billion. It has about 475
banking offices in Pennsylvania, Kentucky, Indiana, Ohio and New
Jersey.
   Bank of Delaware Corp. of Wilmington, Del., is the holding
company for the Bank of Delaware, the state's second largest bank,
and has assets of $1.8 billion. The Bank of Delaware has 33 branch
offices in the state.
   The Bank of Delaware will retain its name, existing management
and its headquarters while operating as a group within PNC
Financial Corp., the companies said.
   ``The merger will expand PNC's presence in Philadelphia and New
Jersey to strategic points in Delaware and the Delmarva
Peninsula,'' said Thomas H. O'Brien, chairman of PNC Financial Corp.
   The banks said under the definitive merger agreement each
outstanding share of Bank of Delaware stock will be exchanged for
0.7 shares of PNC Financial Corp.'s common stock.
   In addition, the banks said, the Bank of Delaware Corp. granted
PNC Financial an option to purchase up to 1.6 million shares of
Bank of Delaware stock at 0.7 times the market price of PNC
Financial common stock at the close of business Wednesday.
   PNC Financial Corp. is the holding company of Pittsburgh
National Bank, Provident National Bank of Philadelphia, the Central
Bancorporation Inc. of Cincinnati, Citizens Fidelity Corp. of
Louisville, Ky., The First Bank & Trust Co. of Mechanicsburg, the
Northeastern Bank of Pennsylvania of Scranton, and PNC National
Bank of New Jersey of Cherry Hill.
</TEXT>
