<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 1048EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Northwest-Land     09-22 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Northwest-Land,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Northwest Airlines Rejects $200 Million Offer to Sell Land in
Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAGAN, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines has rejected a $200
million offer from Japanese real estate developers to sell land it
owns in Tokyo, officials of the airline said.
   Northwest officials declined Wednesday to discuss details of the
purchase offer from Koshin Corp. or say why it was rejected.
   ``We don't have any property that's for sale,'' said spokesman
Redmond Tyler.
   But in a letter to the U.S. real estate agent for Koshin,
Northwest Vice Chairman James A. Abbott said the airline believes
the land is worth more than has been offered and said it ``has been
retained for possible further development by us in connection with
our business in Japan.''
   The developers wanted to build high-rise condominiums on the
50,000-square-foot plot, which would have been sold to
property-starved Japa- nese consumers for $10 million to $15
million apiece. Koshin hoped to place 60 to 65 units on the
property.
   KOAR Inc., a Los Angeles-based real estate firm representing
Koshin, said the property sought by Koshin contains five or six
small two-story buildings that the airline uses to house employees,
including flight crews and corporate staff members, on both a
permanent and temporary basis. KOAR officials said the property is
surrounded by exclusive residences, department stores and high-rise
office buildings.
   Because of the scarcity of land and the density of the
population in Japan, developers there are willing to buy property
for $4,000 per square foot, which is the amount turned down by
Northwest.
   Tyler would not describe the property and said Northwest did not
want to discuss its real estate holdings.
   KOAR said Northwest has owned the property for more than 30
years, which would mean that it obtained it at a fraction of the
price it could fetch today.
   KOAR and Koshin together own 366,600 shares of Northwest stock,
which represents about 1.3 percent of outstanding shares. The price
of Northwest stock rose 87.5 cents to $50.125 Wednesday, as news of
the offer by Koshin circulated broadly among brokers.
   KOAR officials said Koshin has been trying to initiate
discussions with Northwest officials about a land deal since May to
no avail.
   Koshin made its most recent all-cash offer two weeks ago, in
which it ``implored NWA to act in its shareholders' best
interests,'' said KOAR officials. Northwest responded Sept. 12 with
a letter from Abbott, which was provided to the Star Tribune of
Minneapolis by KOAR Vice President Bruce Rothman, the newspaper
said.
</TEXT>
