<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 1146EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   09-22 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0008</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened narrowly
mixed today on the Chicago Board of Trade with little news in the
market to influence prices.
   Soybean futures posted slight gains at the opening in reaction
to a Soviet newspaper report that the Soviet Union's grain harvest
this year would be smaller than the relatively good harvests of the
two previous years.
   But soybeans quickly turned lower on reports of beneficial rain
in the soybean-growing region of Argentina and selling linked to
the advancing corn and soybean harvest in the Midwest.
   Harvest pressure is overhanging the grain markets as well,
limiting the potential for strong rallies, analysts said.
   ``There really is not much of a story developing,'' said Ted
Mao, grain specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
``The harvest is progressing and in general the market is a little
bit tired.''
   In early trading, wheat was 1\ cents to 2 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.21\ a bushel; corn was
unchanged to 1{ cents lower with December at $2.86} a bushel; oats
were 1 cent lower to 1 cent higher with December at $2.55 a bushel;
soybeans were 3{ cents lower to \ cent higher with November at
$8.36{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .12 cent lower to .18 cent higher with October
at 69.27 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .35 cent lower to .15
cent higher with September at 79.40 cents a pound; hogs were .35
cent lower to .13 cent higher with October at 38.90 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .20 cent to .55 cent higher with February
at 50.87 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
