<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 0104EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-LongestBid Adv24-25   09-22 1122</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Longest Bid, Adv 24-25,1162</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 24</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions of Sept. 24-25 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Irving, Bank of New York `Celebrate' 1st Anniversary Of Takeover
War</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bank of New York Co.'s $1.2 billion bid for
rival Irving Bank Corp. has staggered to the one-year mark with
neither side ready to throw in the towel, or even call the outcome.
   At first, it had the distinction of being the first-ever hostile
takeover fight between two big American banks. Now it has become
the lengthiest such battle among major U.S. corporations.
   The strain of the bidding marathon clearly has taken its toll at
both large New York institutions by distracting management from
their usual work, confusing stockholders and piling up millions of
dollars in legal and other expenses.
   A third, friendly contender, Milan-based Banca Commerciale
Italiana SpA, recently was forced out of the running due to an
unfavorable ruling by the Federal Reserve Board, which is patiently
overseeing the proposed merger process.
   ``It's the economic equivalent of the Iran-Iraq war because of
the length and the substantial casualties,'' said H. Rodgin Cohen,
an attorney for the Bank of New York.
   ``At least we're not using poison gas,'' the bank's chairman, J.
Carter Bacot, said jokingly in a recent interview. ``Only `poison
pills' are involved.''
   The outcome of the Irving-Bank of New York war, which began on
Sept. 25, 1987, is likely to be decided in a New York state court,
where, among other things, Irving's ``poison pill'' anti-takeover
defense is under attack. Some observers say the entire process
could drag on into the winter.
   In the meantime, the takeover attempt appears to have turned
into a struggle of personalities between Bacot and Irving's equally
strong-minded chairman, Joseph A. Rice.
   Analysts say Bacot is determined to merge the two banks not only
because the two would fit nicely together but because he fears Bank
of New York itself could become a takeover target if a big West
Coast or foreign bank decided to enter the New York market.
   A merger would nearly double Bank of New York's size, making it
the 11th largest banking company in the country and a more elusive
target.
   Rice, analysts say, has his own vision of running his bank and
believes it is worth much more than the Bank of New York's offer,
especially given its past investments in technological advances.
   Both men have held only a handful of face-to-face meetings since
Bacot formally proposed the merger, and each time talks have broken
off without any signs of progress. No new talks are planned
because, Rice said, ``we see absolutely nothing to be gained at
this stage.''
   ``I think the financial issues were certainly important to
Irving early on and now, but ... it clearly has become a personal
issue,'' said Michael Starr, a banking analyst for Duff & Phelps
Inc. in Chicago.
   Cohen, a partner of Sullivan & Cromwell, which has represented
many firms in takeovers, agreed. ``My own judgment is that they
have created this fiction that the Bank of New York is evil and
horrible ... It's almost a crusade.''
   That is an unfortunate turn of events, many analysts contend,
since both banks have similar markets and services and would work
well together.
   Irving has waged a tough defense to Bank of New York's
persistent overtures, from poison pills to proxy fights. A recently
instituted ``flip-in'' provision to its poison pill would make an
unsolicited merger prohibitively expensive by giving all Irving
shareholders, except Bank of New York, the right to buy $400 of
stock for $200 once Bank of New York acquires 20 percent of Irving.
   ``The Irving board has taken enough action of a defensive nature
and the burden is now on them to be able to show that they are not
merely trying to entrench themselves and Irving's management,''
said Abraham Nad, publisher of the monthly newsletter Directorship,
an authority on corporate boards. ``That's a very fine line to
walk.''
   Bacot says he first broached the idea of a merger at a luncheon
with Rice about five years ago. Rice wasn't very receptive then, he
recalled. He conceded that Irving probably ``resents the fact we
put an offer on the table like that'' after it had turned down the
Bank of New York privately.
   What's particularly noteworthy about this battle is that it's
occurring in an industry where hostile takeovers are rare. Even in
the best of circumstances, the complex, time-consuming regulatory
requirements that other industries are spared could make some banks
think twice about a merger.
   When the bid first emerged, some experts predicted hostile bids
could become more commonplace, particularly among aggressive
regional institutions. They're not so sure anymore.
   ``Hostile takeovers have no place in banking,'' Rice said
recently. ``They are a severe threat to the stability of the
banking industry and the soundness of the economy.''
   New ground, though, was broken on the regulatory front. For one
thing, the Fed declined to make any distinction between a friendly
or hostile offer in approving Bank of New York's application in
February.
   And in August, the Fed decided to treat foreign owners of U.S.
banks much the same as domestic owners by requiring Instituto per
la Ricostruzione Industriale, the parent of ``white knight'' Banca
Commerciale, to apply separately to the Fed. IRI, which balked at
the idea, is controlled by the Italian government and accounts for
about a quarter of Italy's gross national product.
   Irving attorney Robert Falise, who says he was forced to devote
all his time to the takeover fight, said Irving is negotiating with
``several'' foreign and domestic banks about a possible merger.
However, analysts say if an offer happens to emerge it must be
extremely attractive to win over shareholders at this late date.
   Banca Commerciale had offered $84 a share for 51 percent of
Irving's approximately 18 million common shares outstanding before
withdrawing its bid. The merger proposal was part of a complex
defensive restructuring plan that included sale of Irving assets,
cost-cutting measures and a special cash dividend.
   Bank of New York, which owns about 4.9 percent of Irving, is
offering $15 in cash and 1.575 shares of its own stock for each of
Irving's roughly 18 million common shares outstanding.
   Bacot maintains his bid is just as attracive now as it was a
year ago, although the cash portion has declined significantly. If
he had to do things over again, he'd still bid for Irving, Bacot
said.
   ``We wouldn't have stuck with it that long unless we felt that
way,'' he said. ``It gets a little frustrating. You have to have a
lot of patience.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Sept. 24-25</NOTE>
