<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 0106EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-LongestBid-Chronology Adv24-25   09-22 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Longest Bid-Chronology, Adv 24-25,0453</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 24</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Sept. 24-25 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>With BC-Longest Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here's a chronological look at some of the key events in the
Bank of New York Co.'s hostile takeover attempt of Irving Bank
Corp.:
   Sept. 25, 1987 _ Bank of New York makes an unsolicited $1.4
billion cash-stock bid for Irving.
   Oct. 9 _ Irving's board rejects the $1.4 billion bid, activates
the company's ``poison pill'' anti-takeover defense.
   Nov. 20 _ Bank of New York lowers its offer to $1.2 billion,
citing the Oct. 19 stock market crash.
   Dec. 15 _ Irving's board rejects Bank of New York's $1.2 billion
bid.
   Jan. 25, 1988 _ Bank of New York lowers its bid to $1.08
billion, citing Irving's decision to increase its fourth-quarter
loan-loss reserve.
   Feb. 16 _ Irving's board rejects Bank of New York's $1.08
billion bid.
   Feb. 25 _ Bank of New York's takeover proposal gets approval
from the Federal Reserve and New York State Banking boards.
   March 15, 28 _ Irving amends its poison pill.
   April 14 _ Bank of New York's shareholders give their blessing
to an Irving merger.
   April 18 _ Banca Commerciale Italiana enters the picture,
offering $65 a share for 51 percent of Irving. Irving announces a
major resturcturing.
   April 20 _ Banca Commerciale offers $75 a share for 45 percent
of Irving.
   May 2 _ Banca Commerciale raises its proposed stake to 51
percent at the same price.
   May 6 _ Irving's shareholders re-elect Irving's directors,
although Bank of New York later challenges the proxy results in
court.
   May 23 _ Banca Commerciale raises its bid for 51 percent of
Irving to $80 a share. The value of the offer is upped to $84 a
share a few weeks later.
   June 15 _ Bank of New York conditionally offers to raise the
stock portion of its bid, valuing the offer at $1.4 billion. Irving
later rejects the proposal. The previous offer, valued at about
$1.2 billion under current market conditions, stands.
   July 6 _ New York State Supreme Court strikes down a provision
of Irving's poison pill. Irving vows to appeal.
   Aug. 19 _ The Fed rules the Italian government agency that owns
most of Banca Commerciale has to supply financial information in
the Irving bid.
   Aug. 29 _ Banca Commerciale withdraws its bid.
   Sept. 7 _ Fed grants Bank of New York another 90-day extension
to complete the Irving merger, pending appeal of the poison pill
case.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Sept. 24-25</NOTE>
</DOC>
