<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Stocks Close Lower in Moderate Trading</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with close.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices fell on the London Stock Exchange Thursday
in modest trading, with activity again focused on takeover rumors
following Wednesday's bid for Consolidated Gold Fields PLC by
Minorco, which would be the largest ever takeover of a British
company.
   Consolidated Gold Fields' shares, whose sharp gains Wednesday
helped pull the entire market higher, were depressed Thursday as
excitement subsided over Minorco's 2.9 billion-pound, or $4.8
billion, bid.
   But takeover speculation in half a dozen other stocks, sparked
by the move on Consolidated Gold Fields, buoyed the market against
an otherwise bearish tone.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index closed 8.1
points, or 0.5 percent, lower at 1,788.7.
   Volume dropped to 393.6 million shares from 438.6 million shares
Wednesday.
   Overall, losers among the market's 100 leading shares far
outnumbered gainers, 61 to 22. The declines mirrored the mood on
Wall Street, though late in the London day the Dow Jones industrial
average recovered and pushed to a slight advance.
   Consolidated Gold Fields ended 55 pence lower at 13.45 pounds, a
relatively modest retreat after its 322-pence gain Wednesday.
</TEXT>
