<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 1332EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Airlines-Deregulation     09-22 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Airlines-Deregulation,0572</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-TWA-Consumers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Senators Say Deregulation a Bad Thing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several senators today criticized airline
deregulation and the rash of mergers it has spawned, complaining
they have given large air carriers monopoly power in some parts of
the country and resulted in higher fares but less service.
   ``Simply stated, people are paying more to fly today because the
airlines have developed monopoly hubs,'' declared Sen. Ernest
Hollings, D-S.C., chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee.
   He complained that a fare from Washington to Charleston, S.C.,
was $120 in 1977, before airline deregulation, but that recently he
paid $510 for the same trip.
   But the committee at a hearing aimed at examining airline
pricing practices were told by Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley
that air travelers have benefited by the deregulation of the
industry with average air fares declining 13 percent in the last
decade.
   He attributed an average 8 percent increase in domestic air
fares during the first six months of the year to increased costs
for fuel, new aircraft and a number of government-required safety
initiatives.
   As an example of competition benefiting air travelers, Burnley
cited a recent decision by Continental Airlines to offer a $39
off-season fare between the Northeast and Florida.
   Airline deregulation has resulted in ``a substantial improvement
in overall competition'' to the benefit of the public, insisted
Burnley.
   But the explanation didn't satisfy a number of the senators
including Hollings; Sen. John Danforth, R-Mo., and Sen. Larry
Pressler, R-S.D., who said fares and service to their parts of the
country have suffered.
   ``It's cheaper to fly across the nation than it is to fly across
South Dakota. That is a very bizarre situation,'' complained
Pressler, who suggested ``some re-regulation'' would be in order
that would require ticket prices to be linked to miles traveled.
   Hollings and Danforth, the ranking Repubican on the committee,
also warned that airline fare and service practices could lead to
some additional government controls on the industry.
   ``In certain airports competition does not exist. Airlines get a
lock on an airport and when they get a lock they can do pretty much
what they please,'' declared Danforth.
   He cited Trans World Airlines dominance at St. Louis where the
airline controls 83 percent of the flights since its merger two
years ago with Ozark Air Line, once its chief competitor. Single
airlines also dominate at Minneapolis, Pittsburgh and Memphis, said
Danforth.
   Burnley, however, defended his department's approval of 21
airline mergers in recent years and maintained that even at the
airports cited by the senators competition has been maintained.
   ``Not only has new entry (by airlines) occurred at each of these
hubs, but competing incumbent carriers continue to provide
competitive service,'' said Burnley.
   But when pressed by Danforth, Burnely said the department has
been disappointed at the level of competition as St. Louis' Lambert
Field since TWA's merger with Ozark.
   He said the department had expected, for example, that Southwest
Airlines would move into the competitive void created by the
TWA-Ozark merger with as many as 60 flights a day instead of the 22
or 23 flights a day it currently operates through St. Louis.
   ``I'd like to know why that has occurred,'' said Burnley,
promising the department would examine the competitive situation at
the airport.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880922-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 1407EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     09-22 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0305</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices gave ground today in selling
apparently prompted by impatience over the market's recent sluggish
performance.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 12.26 to
2,078.24 by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 7 to 4 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 489 up, 836 down and
537 unchanged.
   Analysts said the market's sluggish recent behavior apparently
convinced some investors that stocks were unable to break out of
the trading range in which they have fluctuated for several months
now.
   They also noted an absence of conviction about the business
outlook to encourage any buying.
   Some prominent analysts and policymakers, including Chairman
Alan Greenspan of the Federal Reserve Board, have been warning of
the dangers of revived inflation.
   Yet the price of gold, a primary gauge of inflationary
expectations, has fallen below $400 an ounce this week for the
first time in more than a year and a half.
   Similarly, brokers say, there is widespread confusion and
uncertainty among investors about prospects for continued economic
growth in 1989 under a new administration whose makeup and policies
are not yet known.
   Among actively traded blue chips, International Business
Machines dropped | to 112|; American Express lost \ to 27|, and
American Telephone & Telegraph was down \ at 26\.
   Reebok International, which reported a higher order backlog than
a year ago, rose { to 11[ in active trading.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped .58 to 152.06. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was down .80 at 298.17.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 105.99 million shares with two
hours to go.
</TEXT>
