<1ST_LINE>u f PM-SeabrookLicense 1stLd-Writethru   09-22 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Seabrook License, 1st Ld-Writethru,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NRC Says Owners Must Demonstrate Financial Ability</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs reaction after 3rd graf pvs, Even if</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission ruled today
that the owners of the Seabrook, N.H., nuclear power plant must
prove they could one day pay to shut down the plant if they are to
be allowed to operate.
   The commission voted unanimously to require the owners the
submit a plan within 30 days that shows a ``reasonable assurance
that adequate funding'' would be available for decommissioning the
plant.
   Even if that issue is resolved, the commission still has another
finance-related issue facing it _ whether the owners are
financially qualified to operate the plant.
   Seabrook officials expressed confidence the decommissioning
question would be resolved in their favor.
   ``We're in the process of answering those questions right now
and we're confident this won't be an issue barring us from
low-power testing,'' said Ronald A. Sher, spokesman for the
reactor's owner.
   Two financial problems with Seabrook prompted opponents to
challenge the owners' financial fitness.
   In January, Public Service Company of New Hampshire, the lead
owner of the reactor, filed for bankruptcy reorganization.
   NRC Chairman Lando W. Zech Jr. said last week that the
commission would not approve a low-power license until it was
satisfied Seabrook could run safely despite the bankruptcy
proceedings.
   The second question revolves around the Massachusetts Municipal
Wholesale Electric Co., which in June withdrew from the project and
halted its $2 million-a-month payments. MMWEC owns 12 percent of
the plant and other Seabrook owners are working to secure investors
to cover MMWEC's payments through 1989.
   The idle $5.6 billion reactor is losing $50 million each month
in maintenance and finance costs.
   If granted a low-power license, the reactor could operate at 5
percent of full power and would need to be granted a further permit
to operate at more than 5 percent of capacity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
