<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed mostly higher
Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade on a late rally that could
mark a key reversal in the markets' recent downward trend, analysts
said.
   Soybean prices swung in a 28-cent range and closed at the day's
highs with the contract for delivery in November at $8.43 a bushel,
5{ cents above Wednesday's final price. Corn and wheat futures also
finished moderately higher.
   ``The market has been liquidating and the first half of session
was spent in what appears now in hindsight to have been the end of
the liquidation,'' said Ted Mao, grain specialist with Shearson
Lehman Hutton Inc. in New York.
   Much of the buying apparently was based on indications of
increased global demand for grain and soybeans, particularly by the
Soviet Union. A large purchase this week of U.S. soybean oil by
Pakistan also supported the soybean complex, analysts said.
   ``Today could be a bullish key reversal,'' said Mario Balletto,
soybean market analyst with Merrill Lynch Capital Markets in New
York.
   At the close, wheat was 5{ cents to 7 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.26{ a bushel; corn was }
cent to 3{ cents higher with December at $2.91 a bushel; oats were
unchanged to 4\ cents higher with December at $2.58\ a bushel;
soybeans were { cent lower to 6 cents higher with November at $8.43
a bushel.
</TEXT>
