<FILEID>AP-NR-09-22-88 1708EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Hunts-Bankruptcy Bjt   09-22 0826</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hunts-Bankruptcy, Bjt,0851</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hunts `Upbeat' Despite Filings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY JORDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of three Hunts facing a $134 million federal
court judgment did not follow the lead of his brothers in filing
personal bankruptcy petitions because he did not have as much
potential exposure in the claim, a spokesman said Thursday.
   Heirs to one of the world's greatest fortunes, Nelson Bunker and
William Herbert Hunt, two of the multimillionaire Dallas brothers,
filed bankruptcy Wednesday.
   But attorneys say the filings won't affect previous Chapter 11
bankruptcy proceedings involving the brothers' Placid Oil Co.,
owned by their trust estates.
   Jurors in a New York federal court decided Aug. 20 the two
Hunts, their brother Lamar and three other defendants must pay
damages for conspiring in the late 1970s to corner the world's
silver market, and ruining the investments of Minpeco SA, the
Peruvian government's mineral marketing company.
   ``They (the brothers) are very upbeat. There is not anybody
hanging their head over this,'' said a spokesman, Tom Whitaker,
executive vice president for the Hunt Energy Corp.
   He said Lamar Hunt did not file a personal bankruptcy petition
because he does not have the exposure of the other two brothers.
But the spokesman did not rule out the possibility of a later
filing.
   ``It was his (Lamar's) option not to file,'' said Whitaker. ``He
does not have the involvement in the potential silver litigation
that Bunker and Herbert have. He does have some exposure, but not
nearly as much.''
   Whitaker declined to discuss why Lamar Hunt may be less involved
in silver lawsuits than his brothers.
   The Hunts are optimistic about chances of getting a new trial or
having damages reduced in their legal fight with the Peruvian
government's mining company, said Whitaker.
   ``This (reorganization) was a business decision, but they
realized the decision would be painful to themselves and their
family,'' the spokesman said. ``They are absolutely determined to
fight this, what we are calling the outrageous Minpeco verdict.''
   Meanwhile, the Chapter 11 reorganizations will avoid a ``fire
sale'' in the wake of a required $225 million bond to appeal the
court award to Minpeco, said Whitaker.
   U.S. District Judge Morris E. Lasker of New York allowed a
temporary stay against the bond.
   Herbert Hunt, in a statement, said the personal filing will give
him time ``to continue the fight to correct the injustice of the
jury verdict ... . The thought of even a dime going to the
government of Peru is repugnant.''
   The Hunts maintain that Peru, as the second-largest producer of
silver in the world, could only have profited as the silver price
rose.
   A Fort Worth, Texas, bankruptcy attorney who is general counsel
to Placid Oil said he was not surprised by the personal filings.
   ``The ensuing events in the silver market and their results have
made it clear that the individual brothers would have to take some
action to be able to operate their original businesses,'' said
Henry Simon of Simon, Anisman, Doby, Wilson & Skillern.
   Confirmation hearings for Placid, which begin Monday before U.S.
Bankruptcy Judge Harold Abramson, should be completed by the end of
next week, he said.
   ``I don't think it (the personal bankruptcy petitions) have any
effect on Placid,'' he said. ``I believe Placid's reorganization
will proceed and it will be a reorganized company.
   ``By the end of next week, we should have confirmation in which
we satisfy that the plan is feasible, that the company can pay for
everything the (U.S.) Bankruptcy Code provides and, regarding
deferred obligations, whether there is a reasonable basis for the
business plan so that creditors who vote for the plan have a
reasonable chance of getting their money,'' said Simon.
   Whitaker said the two Hunts' personal bankruptcy petitions did
not list value of their assets but that, ``as the case proceeds
through the bankruptcy court, those values will be established.''
   However, brief summaries of their assets detailed 13,649
Byzantine coins and 44 pieces of a Roman and Greek bronze
collection for Herbert Hunt. Bunker Hunt's petition noted ancient
coins and ``various art objects and bronze statues.''
   Bunker Hunt listed oil and gas properties in 40 counties
nationwide, three gas plants, 14 ranches, 1,390 acres of raw land,
a condo in Kauai, Hawaii, five cars and a host of other assets, the
Dallas Morning News reported.
   Herbert Hunt listed half-interest in a ski lodge in Vail, Colo.
between one-third and one-fourteenth interest in 3,442 acres in
Louisiana, a 3-year-old Cadillac and a 15-year-old Mercedes Benz,
according to the newspaper.
   Rarely have brothers Bunker, Herbert and Lamar offered public
glimpses of their empire, once valued at some $6 billion. But the
silver crash prompted a $1.6 billion loss for Bunker and Herbert,
who had bought 59 million ounces of silver, once estimated as
one-third of the world's supply.
   Other heavy losses in oil and real estate have, according to
some estimates, cut the trio's wealth to about $1 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
