<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street,0506</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices gave ground Thursday in selling
apparently prompted by impatience over the market's recent sluggish
performance.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, down more than 18
points at its midafternoon low, closed with a 10.49 loss at
2,080.01.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 8 to 5 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
556 up, 881 down and 518 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 150.67 million
shares, up from 127.40 million Wednesday, when activity was
curtailed somewhat by the observance of the Jewish holiday Yom
Kippur.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 177.06 million shares.
   Analysts said the market's uninspired behavior of late
apparently convinced some investors that stocks were unable to
break out of the trading range in which they have fluctuated for
several months now.
   They also noted an absence of conviction about the business
outlook to encourage any buying.
   Some prominent analysts and policymakers, including Chairman
Alan Greenspan of the Federal Reserve Board, have been warning of
the dangers of revived inflation.
   Yet the price of gold, a primary gauge of inflationary
expectations, has fallen below $400 an ounce this week for the
first time in more than a year and a half.
   Similarly, brokers say, there is widespread confusion and
uncertainty among investors about prospects for continued economic
growth in 1989 under a new administration whose makeup and policies
are not yet known.
   Among actively traded blue chips, International Business
Machines dropped 1\ to 112; American Express [ to 27}; Ford Motor {
to 49{; Exxon { to 44{, and American Telephone & Telegraph \ to 26\.
   Middle South Utilities, also among the volume leaders, rose ] to
14\, trading at a new 52-week high. The company said it will
consider more transactions like a sale-leaseback deal it announced
earlier this week involving one of its nuclear power plants.
   Such transactions would stand to improve the company's prospects
for restoring its dividend.
   Coleman Co. rose 3[ to 39[. Analysts said news of the death of
the company's chairman prompted investors to conclude that it might
become a takeover candidate.
   Reebok International, which reported a higher order backlog than
a year ago, rose | to 11\ in active trading.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market lost $8.99 billion, or 0.30
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
dropped .56 to 152.08.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index fell 1.29 to 308.82, and
S&P's 500-stock composite index was down 0.98 at 269.18.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
slipped .05 to 384.86. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index closed at 298.25, down .72.
</TEXT>
