<HEAD>Dollar Rises; Gold Prices Mixed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS Tuesday to Wednesday in 2nd graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar gained ground in quiet trading
Thursday despite a bout of central bank intervention.
   Gold prices fell overseas but recovered somewhat in domestic
dealings. Republic National Bank of New York quoted bullion at $399
a troy ounce, up from $396.35 late Wednesday, when the metal slid
below the $400-an-ounce level for the first time in the United
States since early last year.
   Dealers attributed the rise in domestic gold prices to technical
factors.
   Trading in currency markets was dull. Dan Holland, a vice
president at Discount Corp., said the Federal Reserve intervened
when the dollar topped 1.88 West German marks. Because the market
was thin, ``it didn't take much to turn the dollar around,'' he
said.
   Many dealers were waiting on the sidelines for Saturday's
meeting of the leading industrialized democracies. While no policy
changes are expected to result from the Group of Seven gathering in
West Berlin, a cloud of caution still hung over the markets.
   The G-7 nations include the United States, West Germany, Japan,
France, Great Britain, Italy and Canada.
   Trading the yen remained paralyzed due to the serious illness of
Japanese Emperor Hirohito. ``When (he) dies, Tokyo will shut down
the markets for two days, and then it will be difficult to close
on's yen positions,'' said a dealer at a U.S. bank in Frankfurt.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar rose 0.29 Japanese yen to a closing 134.47 yen. Later in
London, it fell to 134.45 yen. In New York, the dollar rose to
134.69 yen from 134.29 yen on Wednesday.
   The dollar gained against the British pound. In London it cost
$1.6675 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.6755 late Wednesday.
Later in New York, it cost $1.6702 to buy one pound, less expensive
than Wednesday's $1.6738.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday's rates, included: 1.8763 West German marks, up from
1.8745; 1.5851 Swiss francs, up from 1.5820; 6.3860 French francs,
up from 6.3650; 1,399.25 Italian lire, up from 1.395.75, and 1.2187
Canadian dollars, up from 1.2159.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late
Wednesday's rates, included: 1.8790 West German marks, up from
1.8748; 1.5870 Swiss francs, up from 1.5833; 6.3955 French francs,
up from 6.3710; 2.1150 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1145; 1,401.50
Italian lire, up from 1,395.60; 1.2188 Canadian dollars, up from
1.2183.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current delivery
rose to $399.30 a troy ounce from $398.40 on Wednesday.
   But gold prices in Europe mirrored Wednesday's plunge in the
United States, closing below the $400-an-ounce level. Traders in
Zurich described the market as ``panicked and frenzied.''
   Gold finished in London at a late bid price of $397.75 a troy
ounce, compared with late Wednesday's $401.50. In Zurich, gold
dropped to a bid of $397, compared with $400.50 late Wednesday.
Earlier in Hong Kong, gold fell $2.96 to close at a bid $402.42.
   Silver for current delivery finished at $6.250 a troy ounce on
the New York Comex, up from $6.177 on Wednesday. In London, the
metal was quoted at a late bid price of $6.24 a troy ounce,
compared with Wednesday's $6.22.
</TEXT>
