<HEAD>Late Rally Called Key Reversal For Grain Futures</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A late rally that pushed grain and soybean futures prices higher
Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade could mark a key reversal in
the market's recent downward trend, analysts said.
   On other markets, gold struggled back to $400 an ounce; copper
surged; frozen pork bellies rose sharply while livestock futures
were mixed; energy futures were mostly higher; and stock-index
futures retreated.
   Soybeans for November delivery, which had traded as high as
$9.03{ a bushel just one week earlier, swung in a 28-cent range
Thursday, plunging to $8.15 but settling near the day's high at
$8.42, 4{ cents above Wednesday's final price.
   Corn and wheat futures also finished moderately higher but were
less volatile due to the supportive influence of new export
business, analysts said.
   ``The (soybean) market liquidated early until there just wasn't
any selling left below $8.20. Then the strength in the wheat and
corn really supported the bean complex,'' said Pat O'Connell, a
grain analyst with Refco Inc., a Chicago futures brokerage.
   ``I think the market told us today that it's in good shape,'' he
said.
   Ted Mao, grain specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in
New York, said the drop to $8.15 ``appears now in hindsight to have
been the end of the liquidation,'' he said.
   ``Today could be a bullish key reversal,'' agreed Mario
Balletto, soybean market analyst with Merrill Lynch Capital Markets
in New York.
   Much of the buying apparently was based on indications of
increased global demand for grain and soybeans, particularly by the
Soviet Union. A large purchase this week of U.S. soybean oil by
Pakistan also supported the soybean complex, analysts said.
   Talk that the United States and the Soviet Union were nearing
agreement on a new long-term grain agreement further fueled the
rally, analysts said.
   Wheat settled 5{ cents to 6} cents higher with the December
contract at $4.26{ a bushel; corn was } cent to 3{ cents higher
with December at $2.91\ a bushel; oats were unchanged to 4\ cents
higher with December at $2.58\ a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent lower
to 5\ cents higher with November at $8.42 a bushel.
   Silver futures posted solid gains on New York's Commodity
Exchange and gold for October delivery rallied to $400 a troy
ounce, the psychologically important level the contract had
breached a day earlier.
   ``My gut feeling is that there's not much of any significance
here,'' said Jack Barbanel, director of futures trading for Gruntal
& Co. in New York.
   He said the inflation-sensitive gold market reacted to higher
grain prices but that the lack of strong inflationary signals would
continue to depress speculative buying.
   Buying could surface below $390 a troy ounce, a level that gold
is likely to reach within two or three weeks, he said.
   Gold settled 60 cents to 80 cents higher with October at $400 a
troy ounce; silver was 7.1 cents to 7.3 cents higher with September
at $6.25 a troy ounce.
   Copper futures soared on the Commodity Exchange, resuming a
month-long upward trend linked to tight supplies and growing
demand, analysts said.
   Copper settled 1.8 cents to 3.05 cents higher with September at
$1.1535, a new lifetime high for that contract.
   Frozen pork belly futures surged as much as 1.82 cents a pound
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange in a technical rally in the
absence of fresh supply-and-demand factors, analysts said.
   Hog futures were mostly higher in anticipation of a heavy
weekend kill and cattle futures were mixed. The bearish effect of
weaker cash cattle markets was offset by expectations for higher
cash prices, analysts said.
   Live cattle settled .40 cent lower to .43 cent higher with
October at 69.40 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .55 cent lower
to .02 cent higher with September at 79.20 cents a pound; hogs were
unchanged to .57 cent higher with October at 39.25 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .95 cent to 1.82 cents higher with
February at 52.15 cents a pound.
   Oil futures prices ended mostly higher on the New York
Mercantile Exchange as the market awaited this weekend's OPEC price
committee meeting.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 5 cents to 9 cents
higher with November at $14.65 a barrel; heating oil was .03 cent
lower to .07 cent higher with October at 41.06 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .10 cent lower to .50 cent higher with
October at 45.85 cents a gallon.
   Stock-index futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for December delivery of stocks on the
Standard & Poor's 500 index settled 1.2 points lower at 272.10.
</TEXT>
