<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MinimumWage 1stLd-Writethru f0203 09-22 0793</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Minimum Wage, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0203,0814</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Fail to Limit Debate on Higher Minimum Wage</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to FIX to seven votes short, sted six</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Democrats failed Thursday to break a
Republican filibuster of a bill clouded in presidential politics to
raise the $3.35 an hour minimum wage for the first time since 1981.
   On a 53-43 vote _ seven short of the 60 needed _ the Senate
refused to limit to 30 more hours debate on legislation by Sen.
Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., to raise the wage floor to $3.75 in
January, $4.15 in 1990 and $4.55 in 1991.
   ``It's only clear that there is a deliberate attempt to stall
action on this bill,'' said Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd,
D-W.Va., who called the Republican tactics a filibuster.
   Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, the leader of the Republican
opposition to any increase in the minimum wage that does not
include a subminimum wage for new hires, said the issue needs
extended debate.
   ``I know a little bit about filibustering and I've certainly led
my share around here,'' Hatch said. ``But I only lead them on very,
very important issues where we really have to have extended debate
or what I would call extended educational dialogue. This particular
bill needs a lot of that.''
   Hatch a week ago introduced the first Republican amendment in
the debate _ a 90-day, 80 percent subminimum wage applicable to all
new hires.
   As a parlimentary tactic, Kennedy immediately offered a
substitute amendment slightly expanding a currently allowed but
little used 85 percent subminimum wage for full-time students who
work no more than 20 hours a week.
   Since then, there have been no votes in five days of debate.
   Under the Senate's rules, approval of Kennedy's substitute would
effectively kill what Republicans call a subminimum training wage
that President Reagan and Vice President George Bush have coupled
to their approval of any incease in the $3.35 wage floor.
   ``We're not going to get a fair hearing on the training wage
because the labor leaders don't want it,'' said Senate Republican
Leader Bob Dole of Kansas. ``It's not the Republicans versus the
Democrats; it's the Republicans versus the labor leaders. They're
telling us we can take this or leave it; we're not going to play
that game.''
   AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland said Republicans supporting the
filibuster ``obviously know that the presidential nominee of their
party, George Bush, wasn't serious when he told Americans he wanted
an increase in the minimum wage.''
   Bush has declined to specify in the past two weeks how a big an
increase in the minimum wage he could support, saying any raise
should be coupled to a subminimum training wage.
   His vice presidential running mate, Sen. Dan Quayle, R-Ind.,
this week again mentioned a raise to $4 over two years, a proposal
he submitted to the Senate Labor Committee two months ago.
   Byrd scheduled a second cloture vote for Friday in an effort to
break the logjam amid indications that some of the support for the
filibuster may be waning.
   ``We may not be successful tomorrow, but we're going to try,''
Dole said.
   Three Republicans _ Sens. Lowell Weicker of Connecticut, William
Roth of Delaware and John Chafee of Rhode Island _ joined 50
Democrats in Thursday's vote to end the filibuster.
   Three Democrats _ Sens. James Exon of Nebraska, David Boren of
Oklahoma and Richard Shelby of Alabama _ joined Republians in
voting to allow it to continue.
   ``It's an open secret in the Senate that the White House has
asked the Republicans to vote in favor of a filibuster,'' Kennedy
said. ``And the White House has asked them to keep on voting for a
filibuster tomorrow and next week.''
   Kennedy and other supporters of a minimum wage increase say it
would only restore the 30 percent loss of purchasing power that
inflation has taken away from workers on that ``bottom rung'' since
it was last raised in 1981.
   Proponents said the raise will directly benfit some 15 million
workers now paid below $4.55 an hour.
   Hatch, however, said only about 2 million of the minimum wage
earners are what he called ``working poor'' heads of households.
   ``The minimum wage really is irrelvevant except that by pushing
up the bottom some 38 percent ... every other wage scale in the
country has to go up correspondingly, and the cost of every good
and service in this country has to go up correspondingly,'' he said.
   The Congressional Budget Office estimates that raising the
minimum wage would increase the rate of inflation by 0.2 to 0.3
percentage points a year. Inflation so far the first eight months
of 1988 is running at 4.6 percent.
</TEXT>
