<2ND_LINE>AM-Gearhart-Halliburton,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State, Oil Services Companies Agree to Judgment in Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Texas attorney general's office has agreed to
a judgment dissolving the state's suit to block the acquisition of
Gearhart Industries Inc. by Halliburton Co., the companies said
Thursday.
   State District Judge Sharolyn Wood of Houston signed the final
judgment Thursday.
   ``They (the companies) agreed to this final judgment which
requires Gearhart to continue servicing the smaller clients they
had in the past _ the clients we were concerned about,'' said Ron
Dusek, spokesman for Attorney General Jim Mattox. ``That was one of
our main goals, to ensure that services to these smaller clients
were continued.''
   The attorney general's office, after reviewing state antitrust
laws, had obtained a temporary restraining order in an Austin court
against the $305 million merger plan.
   The case was transferred to state district court in Houston so
it could be decided by Friday, when some Gearhart creditors had the
right to withdraw their consent to the merger.
   ``We decided to withdraw our case,'' said Dusek, adding that the
antitrust questions no longer existed. ``There is an agreed, final
judgment.''
   Mattox had contended the merger would eliminate competition in
the wireline services industry.
   The attorney general's challenge came only days after
Halliburton had reached a final agreement on the merger with
Gearhart debtholders and creditors.
   The merger also had won the approval of Gearhart shareholders
and the U.S. Justice Department.
   Gearhart, a struggling Fort Worth-based oilfield services
company that employs 7,000 people worldwide, said it would file for
protection from creditors under Chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings
if the merger was not completed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
